<HR>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A NAME="notes"></A><B>NOTES</B></P>
<P>1 The Act does not define religion.  This Court's precedents have
alternatively insisted on a theistic definition of religion, Wisconsin v. Yoder,
406 U.S. 205 (1972) and a non-theistic one, Welsh v. United States, 398 U.S. 333
(1970); United States v. Seeger, 380 U.S. 163 (1965).  The issue has not yet
arisen in the RFRA context.  Courts have allowed RFRA claims to be made by
members of a truly broad spectrum of religions, including non-traditional ones. 
Plainly religion should be given a generous construction so as not to set up
government endorsed criteria for religion, a construction that would avoid
potential constitutional difficulties.  Cf. Ashwander v. TWA, 297 U.S. 288
(1936).</P>
<P>2 The status of the three-part test is not entirely clear. Compare Board of
Educ. v. Grumet, 114 S.Ct. at 2494-95 (Blackmun, J.) with id. at  2498-99
(O'Connor, J.).  The amici themselves are divided on the desirability and
vitality of that test.</P>
<P>3 Fullilove, 448 U.S. at 476-80 used this same analysis with regard to
congressional power to enact contract set-asides.  Adarand Contruction, Inc. v.
Pena, 115 S.Ct. 2097 (1995), restricts the use of contract set-asides not
because Congress lacks the power to enact broad remedies for discrimination, but
because the Equal Protection Clause imposes special restraints on the use of
race conscious remedies.</P>
