<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/courthdr.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<H1>Felker v. Turpin</H1>
<CENTER><P>No. 95-8836</P><P>In the<BR>Supreme Court of the United States<BR>October
Term, 1995</P><P>Ellis Wayne Felker, <I>Petitioner</I></P><P>v.</P><P>Tony
Turpin, Warden, <I>Respondent</I></P><P>On Writ of <I>Certiorari</I> to the

United States Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit and Petition for Habeas
Corpus</P><P>Brief Amicus Curiae of the American Civil Liberties Union and the
ACLU of Georgia in Support of Petitioner</P>
</CENTER>
<CENTER><B>TABLE OF CONTENTS</B></CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>
 <A HREF="#TABLE">TABLE OF AUTHORITIES</A>	</P>
<P>
 <A HREF="#INTEREST">INTEREST OF <I>AMICI</I></A>	 </P>
<P>
 		<A HREF="#STATEMENT">STATEMENT OF THE CASE</A></P>
<P>
 		<A HREF="#SUMMARY">SUMMARY OF ARGUMENT</A></P>
<P>
 		<A HREF="#ARGUMENT">ARGUMENT</A></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>
 	I.	THIS CASE, AT THIS TIME, IS NOT AN APPROPRIATE VEHICLE FOR THE COURT TO
DECIDE WHETHER AND TO WHAT EXTENT CONGRESS MAY LIMIT THE COURT'S APPELLATE
JURISDICTION UNDER ARTICLE III	</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>
 		A.	The 1996 Act Does Not Foreclose Supreme Court Review Under 28 U.S.C. 2241</P>
<P>
 		B.	If Reached, The Fundamental Constitutional Issues Presented By This Case
Deserve Careful And Deliberate Review	</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
 	II.	THIS COURT SHOULD REJECT ANY INTERPRETATION OF THE EXCEPTIONS CLAUSE THAT
PERMITS CONGRESS, IN ITS SOLE DISCRETION, TO LIMIT THIS COURT'S APPELLATE
JURISDICTION TO HEAR CONSTITUTIONAL CLAIMS</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>
 		A.	The Language, History, And Structure Of Article III Do Not Support An
Expansive Reading Of The Exceptions Clause</P>
<P>
 		B.	The &quot;Essential Functions&quot; Test Effectively Reconciles The
Structure Of Article III And The Meaning Of The Exceptions Clause	</P>
<P>
 		C.	The 1996 Act Intrudes Upon The Essential Functions Of The Court</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
 		<A HREF="#CONCLUSION">CONCLUSION</A></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><B><A NAME="TABLE">TABLE OF AUTHORITIES</A></B></CENTER>
