<P>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%>
<blockquote>
                 <h3>INTRODUCTORY STATEMENT</h3>
<p>
     This action is brought by the named plaintiffs, individually and on behalf of all other persons
similarly situated, seeking to end the defendant City of Pittsburgh's historical and long-standing
practice of condoning and acquiescing in unconstitutional conduct on the part of its police officers that
has become accepted practice within the City's police department.  Specifically, the plaintiffs bring this
action to enjoin the defendants from condoning or acquiescing in known police misconduct and to
enjoin those practices, policies and procedures which permit the unconstitutional conduct complained
of herein to occur without meaningful sanction, penalty, or discipline.    
<p>
  The unconstitutional conduct described by the plaintiffs attests to misconduct that can be directed at
any citizen, at any time, and at any place within the City of Pittsburgh, placing all citizens at risk. 
This unconstitutional conduct -- including false arrests, the use of excessive force, and the initiation of
false and malicious prosecutions -- is often meted out in retaliation against citizens for the exercise of
protected first amendment activities such as questioning or criticizing police conduct.  In addition, a
heightened pattern of abuse and a pervasive disregard of citizens' constitutional rights occurs in
African-American communities where the right under the fourth amendment to the United States
Constitution to be free from unreasonable searches and seizures and to be secure in one's person and
property is routinely disregarded. 
<p>
     The conduct complained of herein, including retaliation against citizens for engaging in
protected first amendment activities, the disregard of citizens' rights to be free from unreasonable
searches and seizures, the complicity of police officers who abide by the "Code of Silence" and
acquiescence in such conduct by the defendant City of Pittsburgh, and its elected or appointed officials
violates the plaintiffs' rights as guaranteed to them under the first, fourth and fourteenth amendments
to the United States Constitution, and as enforceable under the Civil Rights Act of 1871, as amended,
42 U.S.C. 1983.  The plaintiffs, who seek declaratory and injunctive relief, both for themselves and
on behalf of the class they represent, are also entitled to receive and seek in their individual capacities
appropriate monetary damages for the violation of their constitutional rights and the injuries sustained
as a result.
<p>     
<h3>JURISDICTION</h3>
<p>     
1.   Plaintiffs seek to vindicate rights protected by the first, fourth and fourteenth amendments to the
United States Constitution and by 42 U.S.C. 1983, 1985 and 2000d.  This court has jurisdiction of
this civil action pursuant to 28 U.S.C. 1331 and 1343(a)(3) and (4).  Plaintiffs seek declaratory
relief
pursuant to 28 U.S.C.  2201 and 2202.  This Court has supplemental and pendant jurisdiction
to adjudicate state claims pursuant to 28 U.S.C.  1367(a).
<p>                                      
                              <h3>Venue</h3>
<p>     
2.   Venue is proper in the Western District of Pennsylvania.  Each claim herein arises out of
an incident that occurred in the City of Pittsburgh, and involves officers employed by the Pittsburgh
Police Department.

                            <h3>PARTIES</h3>
<p>     
3.   Plaintiff ERNEST WILLIAMS is an African-American male residing in a small town west
of Pittsburgh.  He is an ordained Baptist minister with a master's degree in mathematics.  He currently
works as a minister at a local college, where he also teaches mathematics. 
<p>     
4.   Plaintiff JOHN IMMEKUS is a Caucasian male resident of suburban Pittsburgh.  He has a
wife and children and works as a mental health professional.  He travels through the City of Pittsburgh
to and from his place of regular employment. 
<p>
 5.   Plaintiff JENIFER BRANCH is a Caucasian female residing in Pittsburgh's Hill District.   She is
married and has two children.  She is employed as a billing clerk by a local healthcare provider. 6.  
Plaintiff MARTHA BASKINS is an African-American female residing in the Northside section of
Pittsburgh.  She is married and expecting her third child.  She is currently employed as a nurse by
a local hospital.  
<p>     
7.   Plaintiff LARNELL BULLS is an African-American male whose family resides in the
Northside section of Pittsburgh.  He is currently a student at a nearby University.
<p>     
8.   Plaintiff DARRYL JONES is an African-American male who resides in the Highland Park
section of Pittsburgh.  He has a family and is employed as a systems analyst by a local financial
institution.
<p>     
9.   Plaintiff RHONDA THOMAS MAY is an African-American female who resides in
the Hazelwood section of Pittsburgh.  She is employed as an executive secretary and is a
part-time comedienne. 
<p>     
10.  Plaintiff JEFFREY LUCAS is a white male who resides outside the City of Pittsburgh.  He
is married and has two children.  He is a restaurant manager.
<p>     
11.  Plaintiffs GRINAGE ("Dion") WILSON and TROY WILSON are nineteen year-old
and seventeen year-old African-American males, respectively, who reside in the Northside area of
Pittsburgh.  They live with their mother, SHIRLEY SLOAN, who is a Lieutenant in the Pittsburgh
Police Department.  Both WILSON Plaintiffs are students in the Pittsburgh Public School System.
TROY WILSON, a minor, sues by and through his natural guardian, SHIRLEY SLOAN. 
<p>     
12.  Plaintiff JOHN NEIDIG is a Caucasian male who resides in suburban Pittsburgh.  He is
married and is expecting his second child.  He is employed by a Pittsburgh delivery service.
<p>     
13.  Plaintiff JUNE BRYANT is an African-American female residing in the East Hills section
of Pittsburgh.  She is a local democratic committee select woman and helps to run the youth
community center located in the housing project where she lives. 
<p>     
14.  Plaintiff DANINE KAERCHER is a caucasian female resident of Pittsburgh's
Sheridan neighborhood.
<p>     
15.  Plaintiff GEORGE DIGGS is an African-American male residing in the City of Pittsburgh.  He is
a retired Allegheny County Port Authority bus driver.
<p>     
16.  Plaintiff TRACY LILLER is a Caucasian female residing in the Mt. Washington section
of Pittsburgh.  She is the mother of six children. 
<p>     
 17. Plaintiff LLOYD WILLACY is a black Jamaican citizen who resides in the Southside section of 
Pittsburgh.  He is a musician.
<p>     
18.  Plaintiff DAMON WILLIAMS is an African-American male residing in the Northside section
of Pittsburgh. 
<p>     
19.  Plaintiff MELVIN MARIE WILLIAMS is an African-American female residing in the
Northside section of Pittsburgh. 
<p>     
20.  Plaintiff ERIC SIMPSON is an African-American male residing in the City of Pittsburgh.  He
is an unordained minister who performs social work for local social services agencies and the NAACP.
<p>     
21.  Plaintiff DAVID KINTU is a resident alien from Uganda attending the University of
Pittsburgh Law School in the City of Pittsburgh.
<p>
22.  Plaintiff WILLIAM F. MARTIN is an African-American male residing in the Northside
section of the City of Pittsburgh.  He is married and has two children.  He is a former City of
Pittsburgh municipal employee.  
<p>     
23.  Plaintiff ERIC JACKSON is an African-American male, who resides in the West End section
of the City of Pittsburgh.  He is employed as a law enforcement officer.
<p>     24.  Plaintiff Emmanuel S. Anthou is a caucasian male residing in Southwestern, Pennsylvania.  He is
a real estate broker and a licensed attorney.
<p>     25.  Plaintiff ROBERT NEUBAUER is a caucasian male, resident of Los Angeles, California, who is
originally from Pittsburgh and frequently comes to Pittsburgh to visit family and friends.  He is
a licensed attorney specializing in civil rights litigation.
<p>     26.  Plaintiff ARLENE HENDERSON is an African-American female resident of Pittsburgh's
Hill District.  She has been employed in the environmental services department of a local hospital for
almost twenty years.
<p>     27.  Plaintiff, PITTSBURGH BRANCH OF THE NATIONAL ASSOCIATION FOR
THE ADVANCEMENT OF COLORED PEOPLE ("NAACP"), is a branch of the eighty-nine year
old  national civil rights organization.  The NAACP's mission is to improve the political, educational,
social and economic status of minority groups, to eliminate racial prejudice, to keep the public aware
of the adverse effects of racial discrimination, and to take lawful action to secure its elimination. 
The PITTSBURGH BRANCH of the NAACP has a longstanding and ongoing concern about
misconduct perpetrated by Defendant CITY OF PITTSBURGH police officers against NAACP
members.  Members of the NAACP and their respective families have been and may in the future be
victims of constitutional torts committed by officers of the Defendant CITY OF PITTSBURGH.
<p>     28.  Plaintiff PARENTS AGAINST VIOLENCE is an unincorporated organization
comprised primarily of Pittsburgh residents.  The group's mission is to coordinate with parents, youth,
schools, local government, religious institutions, businesses and organizations in an effort to reduce
violence in our communities.  PARENTS AGAINST VIOLENCE has a long-standing concern over
misconduct by Pittsburgh police officers, especially against minors.  Members of the group and their
respective families have been and may in the future be victims of constitutional torts committed by
officers of the Defendant CITY OF PITTSBURGH.
<p>     29.  Defendant CITY OF PITTSBURGH (hereinafter "CITY") is a local government unit
operating under Pennsylvania law and is a recipient of federal funds.  The CITY operates the Police
Department, for whom all of the individual Defendant police officers were working when they
engaged in the acts that have precipitated this law suit.  As described below, the CITY'S official
policy, custom and practice of not adequately investigating acts of misconduct and the violations of
citizens' constitutional rights by CITY OF PITTSBURGH police officers, and of routinely
acquiescing in that misconduct, and of not taking obvious and necessary measures to prevent the
repeated instances of misconduct has led to the constitutional wrongs that are alleged herein.  At all
times relevant hereto, the Defendant CITY OF PITTSBURGH was acting by and through its duly
authorized agents and/or employees who were then and there acting within the scope and course of
their employment.
<p>     30.  Defendant TOM MURPHY was, and is, the Mayor of the CITY OF PITTSBURGH.  As such, he
is the Chief Executive Officer of the Defendant CITY OF PITTSBURGH.  Defendant  Murphy was at
all relevant times hereinafter mentioned acting under color of state law.  Defendant MURPHY is
sued in his official capacity.
<p>     31.  Defendant SALVATORE SIRABELLA was, and is, the Deputy Mayor of the Defendant
CITY OF PITTSBURGH.  His responsibilities include supervision of the Pittsburgh Police
Department.  As such, he has final authority to review and modify disciplinary action against
Pittsburgh police officers.  The Defendant was at all relevant times hereinafter mentioned acting under
color of state law.   Defendant SIRABELLA is sued in his official capacity.
<p>     32.  Defendant EARL BUFORD was the Chief of Police from 1992 until the end of 1995.    As
Chief, he was responsible for the training, supervision and discipline of subordinate police officers. 
The Defendant was at all relevant times hereinafter mentioned acting under color of state law.   
BUFORD is sued in his individual capacity.
<p>     33.  Defendant WILLIAM BOCHTER is the Acting Chief of the Pittsburgh Police Department. 
As Acting Chief, he is responsible for the training, supervision and discipline of subordinate police
officers.  The Defendant was at all relevant times hereinafter mentioned acting under color of state
law.   Defendant BOCHTER is sued in his official capacity.
<p>     34.  Defendants CORDELL BROWN, JOSEPH TUNGEL, MARK MUSHINSKY, 
DANIEL PRATT, TODD TRIVUS, LAWRENCE ROSS, REGIS BEATTIE, J. R. HICKY, JOHN
D. JOHNSON, ROBERT THOMAS, CHARLES JOHNSON, CHARLES DESHIELDS, PAUL
CLARK, KENNETH KOHNFELDER, SAMUEL BARRONE, DAMIAN WILES, JOHN DOE
SYNKOWSKI, JOHN DOE LAGOWSKI, ANTONIO CIUMMO, DAVID CANNON, SCOT
OBER, TIMOTHY KREGER, ANTHONY CHARLES, KEVIN GIFORE, JOSEPH BENZ, JOHN
DOE SCOLAROTI, ROSEMARY BORELLI, JOHN DOE PALMIERI, KEVIN GASIOROWSKI,
RAYMOND PODVOREC, JOHN DOE THIROS, LEO O'NEAL, ANTHONY SCARPINE, LT.
FRIEK, DEBBIE EYNON, and JANE DOE PULEO were at all times relevant hereto CITY OF
PITTSBURGH police officers who were acting under color of state law within the scope of their
employment as CITY OF PITTSBURGH police officers.
<p>     35.  The true names of Defendants DOE 1-31, are presently unknown to Plaintiffs, who, therefore,
sue each of these Defendants by such fictitious name; but upon ascertaining the true identity of 
Defendants DOE 1-31, Plaintiffs will amend this Complaint or seek leave to do so by inserting the true
name in lieu of the fictitious name.  Each Defendant DOE named herein was at all relevant times an
officer of the Pittsburgh Police Department and is  responsible in whole or in part for the injuries and
damages complained of in this action.

                     <h3>CLASS ACTION ALLEGATIONS</h3>
<p>     
36.  With respect to the claims for declaratory and injunctive relief only, Plaintiffs bring this
action individually, and on behalf of all persons similarly situated, pursuant to Fed.R.Civ.P. 23(a) and
(b)(2). 
<p>     
37.  Only the named Plaintiffs seek damages for the injuries caused to them personally
and individually by the Defendants.  
<p>     38.  The class consists of all individuals who have been and will be deprived of their
constitutional right to be free from unreasonable searches and seizures, unlawful use of force, unlawful
arrest and malicious prosecution resulting from Defendants' policies, practices or custom of stopping,
detaining, searching, physically abusing and wrongfully charging individuals without cause or
justification and/or because of their race or minority status and/or in retaliation for the exercise of
constitutionally protected expression that is perceived to be offensive.
<p>     39.  The pre-requisites of Rule 23(a) are satisfied.   
<blockquote>
<p>      a.   The class is so numerous that joinder of all members is impracticable.  The class consists of all
persons in Pittsburgh who have been and will be subject to the complained of actions, thereby making
joinder of all members impracticable.  The size of the class is vast, encompassing not only
all Pittsburgh residents, but also those who may travel through the City.
<p>          b.   There are questions of law and fact common to the class, namely, the policies, customs and
practices of the Pittsburgh Police Department and the named defendant officials.     
<p>          c.   The claims of the named Plaintiffs are typical of the claims of the class, namely, that
the policies, customs and practices of the Pittsburgh Police Department are the moving force behind
the constitutional violations complained of herein.
<p>          d.   The named Plaintiffs will fairly and adequately protect the interests of the class because they
are and were subject to the complained of policies, customs and practices.   Plaintiffs' counsel,
the American Civil Liberties Foundation ("ACLF") and the undersigned attorneys, are experienced
in litigating federal civil rights cases and class actions.
</blockquote><p>     40.  In accordance with Fed. R. Civ. P.  23(b)(2), the parties opposing the class have acted or
refused to act on grounds generally applicable to the class, thereby making appropriate final injunctive
relief or corresponding declaratory relief with respect to the class as a whole.
<p>     
       <h3>FACTUAL ALLEGATIONS CONCERNING "OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS"</h3>
<p>     41.  Defendant, CITY OF PITTSBURGH and its police department, have for many years
subjected the Plaintiff class to unlawful and unconstitutional police practices, including, but not
limited to, retaliating against citizens for engaging in protected first amendment activities, subjecting
citizens to unlawful stops, seizures and arrests, particularly in African-American communities where
such conduct is pervasive, and otherwise subjecting citizens to the use of excessive force, the filing of
false charges and malicious prosecutions. 
<p>     42.  The unconstitutional conduct set forth in this Complaint has been proximately caused by
the failure of the Defendants CITY OF PITTSBURGH, MURPHY, SIRABELLA, BOCHTER
and BUFORD and their predecessors (hereinafter "OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS") to properly train,
supervise and discipline individual police officers in the Pittsburgh Police Department.  As a result of
this policy of deliberate indifference, the unconstitutional conduct alleged herein has become accepted
practice within the Defendant CITY OF PITTSBURGH police department and, as such, has been, and
can be perpetrated against citizens by CITY OF PITTSBURGH police officers with impunity.
<p>     43.  The conduct complained of herein has become accepted practice within the Defendant CITY
OF PITTSBURGH police department because the OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS and other officials in
the CITY OF PITTSBURGH police department have routinely acquiesced in, and have otherwise
failed to take the necessary measures to prevent and curtail such conduct.
<p>     44.  The Defendant CITY OF PITTSBURGH has failed to carry out its function to
properly investigate and adjudicate civilian complaints of police misconduct.  As a result, police
officers, including the named individual Defendant officers, who may pose a clear and present danger
to the safety, liberty and security of the Plaintiff class, are not properly disciplined or supervised,
notwithstanding instances of abuse and unconstitutional conduct on their part.  These officers and
others are thereby permitted and encouraged to engage in similar conduct in the future.  
<p>     45.  The OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS, at all times relevant hereto, including prior to the
unlawful police conduct hereinafter described in the Plaintiffs' allegations had a constitutionally
defective and inadequate practice and/or procedure with respect to investigating charges of misconduct
against its police officers, and/or in disciplining its officers found to have engaged in misconduct
against citizens, evaluating the performance of police officers employed by it, including, but not
limited to the following:
<p>     <blockquote>     a.   The OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS on numerous occasions have received notice that its
          police officers engaged in unconstitutional conduct, including carrying out false arrests,
          bad faith and/or arbitrary prosecutions, committing excessive force and/or engaging in
          other police misconduct and despite such knowledge and notice failed to discipline the
          officers who engaged in such conduct;
          <p>     
     b.   The OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS, despite receipt of complaints regarding the
          performance of CITY OF PITTSBURGH officers, including complaints of false
          arrest, use of excessive force, and the initiation of arbitrary, capricious and bad
          faith prosecutions, does not have any system whereby it regularly evaluates the
          performance of its police officers;
<p>     
     c.   The OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS' procedures for investigating citizens
          complaints routinely result in a finding that such complaints are "not sustained"
          even though there is ample evidence to establish misconduct on the part of its
          police officers;
<p>     
     d.   The OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS, despite having actual notice of police
          misconduct on the part of its police officers, including jury verdicts finding that
          one or more of the police officers violated a citizen's constitutional rights,
          routinely takes no disciplinary action against such officers;
<p>     
     e.   The OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS have never terminated the employment of any
          CITY OF PITTSBURGH police officer on account of alleged abuse towards a
          citizen, including proven allegations of constitutional violations such as false
          arrest, use of excessive force, and malicious prosecution unless the officer has
          been convicted of a felony;
<p>     
     f.   The Pittsburgh Police Department employs numerous officers, including several
          who are named Defendants in this action, who have more than ten (10)
          complaints of serious misconduct against them.  The OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS
          are aware of the allegations against these officers, yet have never taken effective
          disciplinary action to prevent further violations of citizens' constitutional rights;
<p>     
     g.   Internal police department recommendations that certain police officers should
          be discharged either for repeated instances or especially severe cases of
          misconduct against the public have been deliberately ignored by the OFFICIAL
          DEFENDANTS.  The OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS have permitted these officers
          to remain on active duty without sufficient supervision, retraining and discipline. 
          These officers have committed serious acts of misconduct since their discharge
          was recommended for earlier acts of misconduct;
<p>     
     h.   The OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS fail to punish police officers who abide by an
          unwritten "code of silence," and fail to protect officers who break the code of
          silence from harassment or retaliation by other officers.  The code of silence
          consists of one simple rule: an officer does not provide adverse information
          against a fellow officer.  The code of silence, which influences the behavior of
          many officers in a variety of ways, violates a police officer's public responsibility
          to ensure compliance with the law.  Police officers, therefore, believe that if they
          fail or refuse to participate in the "code of silence" or fail to cover up or conceal
          the misconduct of other officers, that such failures will cause them to be
          ostracized by fellow officers, will adversely affect their ability to get support from
          other officers in the field, and will adversely affect their opportunities for
          promotion and other employment benefits.  The OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS'
          failure to eliminate the code of silence encourages constitutional violations even
          though witnessed by other officers and enables such violations to continue with
          impunity; and
<p>     
     I.   The OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS condone and encourage police officers in their
          belief that they can violate with impunity the federally secured rights of Plaintiffs
          and class members by implementing policies and procedures whereby misconduct
          does not adversely affect opportunities for promotion and other employment
          benefits.
<p>     </blockquote>
46.  Over the past 30 years substantial documentation of police abuse and unconstitutional
conduct has been disclosed to the OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS and/or their predecessors in office (by
way of indictments, investigations, civil law suits or complaints), yet the OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS
and other policy making CITY officials have asserted, and continue to assert, that there are no
systemic or institutional patterns of abuse or illegal conduct within the Police Department.
<p>     47.  In 1995, a Pittsburgh police officer attacked a Pittsburgh public school teacher, for which she
(the police officer) was charged with several misdemeanors.  The OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS have
taken no meaningful disciplinary action against the officer.  To the contrary, the OFFICIAL
DEFENDANTS transferred the officer, at her request, to the detective branch of the police force. 
Such a transfer is generally considered to be a promotion.
<p>     48.  In 1989, a Pittsburgh police officer was video-taped punching a citizen attending a Grateful
Dead concert in the face without provocation or legal justification.  Even though there was persuasive
evidence of misconduct, the officer was never disciplined.  This same officer was arrested and charged,
on more than one occasion, with domestic violence.  He also has willfully violated court issued
Protection From Abuse Order ("PFA's").  Recently a firearm was discharged at his home.  Despite
such conduct , the officer remains on the CITY OF PITTSBURGH police force and was recently
promoted to the rank of sergeant.
<p>     49.  In 1983, a Pittsburgh police officer arrested an African-American couple in the City of Pittsburgh. 
He then drove the couple to Butler County in an official police vehicle and dropped them off on a
deserted road.  Upon the filing of a complaint by the wronged couple, the officer was only found to
have violated the departmental rule against falsifying mileage records.  He did not receive any
significant punishment or discipline for the numerous constitutional violations inflicted on the couple. 
This officer remains on the police force and has been the subject of repeated citizen misconduct
complaints since this incident.
<p>     50.  In Bielevicz v. Dubinon, 915 F.2d 845 (3d Cir. 1990), two CITY OF PITTSBURGH
police officers, John Dubinon and Virginia Beck, were found by a federal court jury to have arrested
the Plaintiffs  on pretextual charges of public intoxication in retaliation for displaying a "bad attitude"
towards the police.  Despite the  jury's unanimous finding, neither officer was ever disciplined by the
Defendant,  CITY OF PITTSBURGH, for violating the Plaintiffs' constitutional rights.
<p>     51.  In Betz v. The CITY OF PITTSBURGH, et. al., (C.A. No. 88-789), two CITY
OF PITTSBURGH police officers were found by a federal court jury to have arrested the Plaintiff
on pretextual charges in retaliation for what the officers perceived to be the Plaintiff's "bad attitude". 
In that case, the jury specifically found that the CITY OF PITTSBURGH had a custom, practice and
policy of using summary offense charges (e.g., public intoxication) as a pretext to arrest citizens for
displaying what the police officers believed was a bad attitude.  Despite the unanimous finding of the
jury, neither of the two police officers involved in the Betz case was ever disciplined by the CITY OF
PITTSBURGH Police Department.  In fact, one of the officers was promoted.
<p>     52.  In Dutchko v. The CITY OF PITTSBURGH, et. al., (C.A. No. 91-1506), the court found that the
Defendant police officer had violated the Plaintiff's constitutional rights to be free from
unreasonable searches and seizures by subjecting him to an unlawful arrest.  In that case, the judge
specifically found that:
<p><blockquote>
 "...at least some of the City's police officers routinely arrest people and
          incarcerate them on routine summary offenses rather than issuing them
          citations and that the city at least encouraged and acquiesced in this
          practice or custom.  (Dutchko v. CITY OF PITTSBURGH, C.A. No. 91-1506, Slip. op. 12).
</blockquote><p>     
Despite the court's specific finding that the Defendant officer had committed a constitutional
violation, no disciplinary action was ever taken against the officer involved.
<p>     53.  In Sweitzer v. The CITY OF PITTSBURGH, et. al., (C.A. No. 93-1838), the court found that the
Defendant CITY OF PITTSBURGH had a policy of arresting non-residents of the Commonwealth of
Pennsylvania for petty offenses in violation of the Privileges and Immunities Clause of the
fourteenth amendment to the United States Constitution.  A police officer, designated by the CITY
OF PITTSBURGH to testify on its behalf, and an instructor at the Police Academy, admitted that
CITY OF PITTSBURGH police officers routinely make decisions to arrest citizens based upon the
citizens' attitude towards the police officer.  Despite this admission made in court documents, neither
the police officer making such admission, nor the Defendant police officer who was found to have
violated the Plaintiff's constitutional rights, was ever disciplined by the Defendant CITY OF
PITTSBURGH.
<p>     54.  In a 1995 out-of-court settlement, Pittsburgh City Council approved the payment of $175,000
to a citizen who was the victim of misconduct by a CITY OF PITTSBURGH police officer.  The
officer wrongfully arrested an individual and placed him in the back seat of a police car.  Then, in
violation of department rules and procedures, the officer responded to another incident.  In the course
of doing so he ran a red light striking a pedestrian and also seriously injuring his passenger.  Despite
this incident and numerous other citizen misconduct complaints against the officer involved,
OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS have imposed no meaningful discipline and have ordered no re-training.
<p>     55.  The U.S. Attorney's Office for the Western District of Pennsylvania in a federal court
criminal prosecution of  Allegheny County criminal justice and court officials for fixing traffic tickets
(Criminal Action No. 94-233) identified several CITY OF PITTSBURGH police officers as having
assisted the criminal Defendants fix tickets in violation of citizens' civil rights.  Five current CITY OF
PITTSBURGH police officers testified to participating in such criminal conduct.  A former Pittsburgh
police sergeant who recently headed the Pittsburgh police department's traffic division and who trained
young police recruits at the training academy, also testified and admitted to such conduct.  Despite this
evidence, OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS neither conducted an investigation into the named officers nor
disciplined any of the officers for such conduct.
<p>     56.  By ignoring the obvious systemic causes of police misconduct the OFFICIAL
DEFENDANTS have demonstrated their deliberate indifference to misconduct in the Pittsburgh
Police Department.  
<p>     
Unconstitutional Practices Carried Out By CITY OF PITTSBURGH Police Officers
Retaliation for Protected First Amendment Activity<p>     
57.  As a direct result of the OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS' conduct as hereinbefore described, a
custom, policy, or procedure has developed within the CITY OF PITTSBURGH police department
whereby it has become accepted practice for police officers to retaliate against citizens who engage in
protected first amendment activities by subjecting such citizens to unlawful arrests and seizures and/or
the use of excessive force and/or the initiation of false and malicious prosecutions.  
<p>     58.  The practice of CITY OF PITTSBURGH police officers retaliating against citizens for
engaging in protected first amendment activities is sufficiently widespread as to have a generally
chilling effect on such expression by citizens in and about the City of Pittsburgh in direct violation of
the first amendment to the United States Constitution.
<p>     
Violation of Fourth Amendments Rights In African-American Communities<p>     
59.  As a direct result of the OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS' conduct as hereinbefore described, a
custom, policy or procedure has developed within the CITY OF PITTSBURGH police department
whereby it has become accepted practice to subject citizens residing in predominately
African-American communities within the CITY OF PITTSBURGH to wholesale violations of their
fourth amendments rights to be free from unreasonable searches and seizures.
<p>     60.  The practices referred to in the preceding paragraph include, but are not limited to,
stopping, seizing, and searching African-American citizens without probable cause, using routine stops
for alleged traffic violations to carry out unlawful searches of vehicles operated by African-American
citizens without probable cause or the consent of the owner; using dragnet tactics and sweeping
searches and seizures of young African-American males who reside in or happen to be present in
communities where gang activities are suspected, and otherwise routinely failing to respect
African-American citizens' rights to be free from unreasonable searches and seizures.
<p>     61.  The practice of violating African-American citizens' rights to be free from unreasonable
searches and seizures as protected under the fourth amendment to the United States Constitution is
sufficiently widespread that African-American citizens residing in the City of Pittsburgh or traveling
therein are not confident in the belief that either their persons or their possessions are secure from
unreasonable searches and seizures on the part of CITY OF PITTSBURGH police officers in direct
violation of their rights as protected by the fourth amendment to the United States Constitution.
<p>     
Initiation of False and Malicious Prosecutions to Cover-up Police Misconduct<p>     
62.  As a direct result of the OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS' conduct as hereinbefore described, a
custom, policy or procedure has developed within the CITY OF PITTSBURGH police department
whereby it has become accepted practice to initiate more serious charges against citizens than
warranted by the commission of any alleged illegal conduct by the citizen as part of an overall scheme
to justify warrantless and/or improper arrests, and/or to cover up other police misconduct such as the
use of excessive force.  
<p>     63.  The practices referred to in the preceding paragraph include, but are not limited to, initiating
more serious charges against persons suspected of committing summary offenses to justify arrests of
such persons without a warrant when arrests are not otherwise proper and includes such practices as
charging citizens with pretextual charges of resisting arrest or more serious offenses in order to justify
the improper use of force and/or excessive force.
<p>     64.  The practice of initiating false or pretextual charges against citizens in order to cover up or
justify improper police misconduct is in direct violation of citizens rights to free from unreasonable
and malicious prosecutions as protected under the due process clause of the fourteenth amendment to
the United States Constitution.
<p>     
Summary Punishment Of Citizens Who Offend Police Officers<p>     
65.  As a direct result of the "OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS' conduct as hereinbefore described,
a custom, policy or procedure has developed within the CITY OF PITTSBURGH police
department whereby it has become accepted practice for CITY OF PITTSBURGH police officers to
carry out summary punishment against citizens for reasons of a police officer's animosity against a
citizen unrelated to any belief or suspicion that the citizen has committed any violation of the Crimes
Code of Pennsylvania.<p>     
66.  The practices referred to in the preceding paragraph include, but are not limited to,
subjecting citizens to false arrests and imprisonments, the use of unreasonable or excessive force, and
the initiation of malicious and false prosecutions.<p>     
67.  The practice of subjecting citizens to summary punishment based on a police officer's
personal animosity towards a citizen unrelated to the commission of any offense under the Crimes
Code of Pennsylvania is in violation of the due process clause of the fourteenth amendment to the
U.S. Constitution.
<p>     
Code of Silence<p>     
68.  As a direct result of the OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS' conduct as hereinbefore described, a
custom, policy or procedure has developed within the CITY OF PITTSBURGH police department
whereby it has become accepted practice for police officer's to abide by a "Code of Silence" whereby
police officers charged with upholding the law routinely ignore and otherwise fail to report or take
action against fellow police officers who have engaged in misconduct, including, but not limited to,
carrying out unlawful searches and seizures, using excessive force and initiating false and malicious
prosecutions.<p>     
69.  The accepted practice within the CITY OF PITTSBURGH police department of abiding by
a "Code of Silence" deprives citizens within the jurisdiction of the CITY OF PITTSBURGH of the
equal protection and enforcement of the laws as guaranteed to them under the fourteenth amendment
of the U.S. Constitution.  
<p>     
           <h3>ALLEGATIONS CONCERNING THE NAMED PLAINTIFFS</h3>
<p>     
<b>Ernest Williams</b><br>
70.  On or about Easter Sunday, April 16, 1995, ERNEST WILLIAMS was subjected to a false
arrest, the use of excessive force, and the filing of false and malicious charges against him by
Defendant Pittsburgh police officers JOSEPH TUNGEL and MARK MUSHINSKY.
<p>     71.  Mr. WILLIAMS is an ordained Baptist Minister, who, on the date in question, was at home with a
friend studying for a mathematics project due in a Masters' program in which both were enrolled. 
At or about 11:30 P.M., on the date in question, officers TUNGEL and MUSHINSKY, with their
guns drawn, demanded that Plaintiff and his friend exit the apartment with their hands up.   The police
officers contended that they were responding to a domestic abuse call.
<p>     72.  Plaintiff complied in all respects with the Defendants' demand, and while Defendants did not
have probable cause to believe that Mr. Williams was engaged in any domestic abuse, or was in
violation of any provision of the Pennsylvania Crimes Code, they, nonetheless, carried out a
warrantless search of WILLIAMS' apartment, physically assaulted him, subjected him to a false arrest,
and filed false and malicious charges against him, including felony charges of aggravated assault, two
counts of reckless endangerment, and an alleged Uniform Firearms Act violation.  Plaintiff was
transported to the Public Safety Building after his arrest by officers TUNGEL and MUSHINSKY,
where he was incarcerated for over fifteen (15) hours.
<p>     73.  On or about February 21, 1996, a jury in the Court of Common Pleas of Allegheny
County acquitted Mr. WILLIAMS of all charges.
<p>     74.  The CITY OF PITTSBURGH was notified of the officers' misconduct when WILLIAMS filed a
complaint against them with the CITY OF PITTSBURGH's Office of Professional Standards
("OPS").  Despite the complaint, no disciplinary action or other sanction was imposed on  officers
TUNGEL and MUSHINSKY.
<p>     75.  As a result of the Defendants' conduct, WILLIAMS suffered a violation of his
constitutional rights, sustained physical and emotional injury, (including severe emotional distress,
embarrassment and humiliation), experienced injury to his reputation, and  incurred substantial
expenses to defend against the false and malicious charges brought against him.
<p>     76.  At all times relevant hereto, all of the actions taken against WILLIAMS by the officers were
done in retaliation for the exercise of protected first amendment speech and because WILLIAMS is
African-American. 
<p>     
<b>John Immekus</b><br>
77.  On September 20, 1995, at approximately 8:15 p.m., JOHN IMMEKUS was stopped for
speeding on Browns Hill Road by Defendant police officer CORDELL BROWN.  
<p>     78.  While issuing the speeding citation, officer BROWN was abusive and insulting to
Mr. IMMEKUS.  When Mr. IMMEKUS asked BROWN for his name and badge number so that he
could file a complaint against him for the abusive behavior, BROWN grew even more abusive and
violent, forcibly pulling IMMEKUS from the car, slamming him up against it, and placing him in
handcuffs.<p>     
79.  JOHN IMMEKUS, who had committed no criminal offense in connection with the events
of September 20, 1995 was, nevertheless, placed under arrest by Officer BROWN and confined in a
cell at the Public Safety Building for approximately 11 hours.  At that time, lock-up personnel could
find no official papers to warrant holding IMMEKUS, and he was released.  No charges were filed
against him.<p>     
80.  The arrest was based not on any crime committed by IMMEKUS, but rather on
Officer BROWN'S deliberate attempt to intimidate Plaintiff into not filing a complaint and in
retaliation for IMMEKUS'S expression of his desire to petition the government for redress of
grievances, a right protected by the first amendment to the U. S. Constitution.
<p>     81.  On February 26, 1996, IMMEKUS received in the mail, a summons to appear in City Court
the next day on a disorderly conduct summary charge.  The charge is pending.
<p>     82.  Upon information and belief, no disciplinary action has been taken by the
OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS against officer BROWN as a result of the excessive force, retaliation and
false arrest inflicted on Mr. IMMEKUS.  
<p>     83.  In 1992, an internal police investigation into allegations of misconduct by officer
BROWN resulted in the conclusion that he "does not have the emotional stability or competence to be
a Pittsburgh Police officer.  If the City chooses to retain him they shall be responsible for any
liability incurred due to his lack of competence, honesty and judgment."  OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS
took no action on this recommendation to correct the misconduct or to deter future misconduct. 
Rather, OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS rewarded Officer BROWN with a transfer that he desired.
<p>     
<b>Jenifer Branch & Martha Baskins</b><br>
84.  On August 18, 1995, Plaintiff JENIFER BRANCH stopped her car at a red light at the corner
of East Ohio Street and Cedar Avenue on the North Side section of Pittsburgh.  At that time,
Pittsburgh police officers were involved in an altercation with an unknown male on the sidewalk in
front of J.R.'s Bar.  Also, at that time, a police officer entered the intersection and began directing
traffic from a position directly in front of Ms. BRANCH'S car and signaled to her to stay where she
was and not move her car.<p>     
85.  At the same time, another Pittsburgh Police Officer, Defendant JOSEPH BENZ, roared
at BRANCH to "move your fucking car."  BRANCH, however, was unable to move her car because
the police officer directing traffic was immediately in front of it.  When Ms. BRANCH failed to move
her car, BENZ, in a loud, angry voice, said "move your fucking car, you stupid bitch."
<p>     86.  BENZ then instructed the officer directing traffic to pull BRANCH'S car over to the side of
the road.  Then  Plaintiff was told to turn off her car and get out.  At that time, BENZ continued to use
profane and vulgar language toward BRANCH. Ms.  BRANCH was asked to produce her license and
registration.
<p>     87.  After getting out of her car, BRANCH was handcuffed, dragged from her car and her face hit
the driver's side of her car above the tire.  BENZ and LAGOWSKI were calling BRANCH an
"asshole" and a "stupid bitch".<p>     
88.  BRANCH also had a friend in the car, MARTHA BASKIN, and two children, BRANCH'S
10 month old son and BASKIN'S 5 year old son.<p>     
89.  Officer BENZ then dragged BRANCH to a paddy wagon.  When BRANCH asked about
her child, BENZ said, "fuck your kids, they're going to CYS, bitch."  At this point, BRANCH began
crying.<p>     
90.  BRANCH was illegally detained at the Public Safety Building for fourteen hours and was
falsely charged with disorderly conduct and failure to obey an officer.  While at the Public Safety
Building, in the garage area, another police officer, Defendant SCOLAROTI went to punch the
individual who had been beaten on the sidewalk.  That individual ducked and Defendant
SCOLAROTI punched BRANCH.<p>     
91.  After being released, Plaintiff BRANCH was taken for treatment to the Emergency Room
at Shadyside Hospital.  Treatment was received for a black eye, contusions and tenderness in the neck
and back.  Plaintiff BRANCH was on medication for three weeks.<p>     
92.  Despite the fact that her husband came to the scene and offered to remove BRANCH'S car,
the police told him to "get the fuck out of here before we take your black ass to jail" and impounded
the car.  When Plaintiff BRANCH picked up her car, both the interior of the car and personal property
contained therein had been damaged.     <p>     
93.  MARTHA BASKINS was present during the events involving Plaintiff JENIFER  BRANCH
and witnessed those events.<p>     
94.  After the car was pulled over and BRANCH had gotten out of the car, Plaintiff BASKIN got
out of the car.  At that time, BRANCH called out to BASKINS to go get her husband who was nearby. 
On hearing that, Officer BENZ said, "fuck that bitch, you're going to jail."<p>     
95.  Ms. BASKINS was then grabbed by the throat by Defendant LAGOWSKI, who threw her to
the ground while choking her.  Officer LAGOWSKI said, "don't you ever fucking touch a cop." <p>     
96.  After BASKINS stood up, LAGOSWKI grabbed Plaintiff BASKINS by the neck a second
time and said, "try me, you stupid fucking nigger bitch.  We'll take your black ass to jail."  At this
point both children in the car were crying.  BASKINS' son was hysterical and screaming "please let
my mommy go."  At that time, Ms. BASKINS was two months pregnant.<p>     
97.  BASKINS asked what she was supposed to do and Officer BENZ told her to "take these kids
the fuck out of here."<p>     
98.  Officer LAGOWSKI was also kicking Plaintiff BASKINS' shoes and telling her he would
"take her black ass to jail."<p>     
99.  When Officer LAGOWSKI saw BASKINS trying to read his name tag, he said, "take me to
court - I don't give a shit - I've been there over a hundred times before and it doesn't make a difference.
 They can't do anything to me; I can do whatever I want so go ahead and sue; you'll lose, you'll lose."
<p>     
<b>Larnell Bulls</b><br>
100. On July 25, 1994, LARNELL BULLS was returning home from his friend's house on the
lower north side, driving in a car with two young African-American male friends, when a Pittsburgh
police car began following them.<p>     
101. When BULLS and his friends pulled into the driveway of BULLS' home, the police car pulled up
with lights flashing.  The two officers, Defendants DANIEL PRATT and TODD TRIVUS, got out
of the car, and without justification or provocation pointed their guns at the passengers and said
"freeze."  The officers, without reasonable suspicion or probable cause, searched the three boys
individually, including book bags that they had with them.  The boys produced identification upon
request.<p>     
102. During the confrontation, LARNELL BULLS' parents emerged from the home to inquire of
the police and, eventually, to complain of the treatment.  The BULLS are members of Plaintiff
organization PARENTS AGAINST VIOLENCE.  <p>     
103. One of the officers on the scene justified the treatment of the boys by telling the BULLS that
the boys "looked suspicious" and were seen "leaving a high crime area."<p>     
104. The BULLS complained about the treatment of their son and his two friends to OPS, and
appeared before Pittsburgh City Council.  OPS concluded that the BULLS' complaint could not be
sustained.  This finding was made even though OPS internal investigation showed that the evidence
relied on by the officers to justify stopping the boys, i.e., that a 1989, dark blue Dodge Dynasty car
had been reported stolen, was false.  Indeed, the officers even claimed to OPS that they had stopped a
"dark blue car." The boys had been driving a 1994 light gray Oldsmobile.  <p>     
105. No disciplinary action was ever taken against the officers as a result of this incident.
<p>     
<b>Darryl Jones</b><br>
106. On April 5, 1994, Plaintiff DARRYL JONES was driving to his Highland Park home from
the drug store, where he had gone to fill a prescription for pain medicine.  Mr. JONES had a wisdom
tooth extracted earlier that day. <p>     
107. Mr. JONES, while proceeding home, was unable to make a left hand turn at an
intersection because a police van was blocking  the left lane.  Mr. JONES was concerned that if he
went into the opposite lane of traffic to go around the police car, that he might commit a traffic offense
or cause  an accident. <p>     
108. When Mr. JONES sounded his horn, the police officer, Defendant LAWRENCE ROSS,
exited his vehicle and began screaming at JONES.  ROSS instructed JONES that he should just go
around the stopped police vehicle. <p>     
109. When JONES  proceeded to go around the stopped police van, ROSS pulled JONES over. 
The JONES vehicle was stopped by Officer ROSS for between forty-five (45) minutes and one (1)
hour.  At the end of this period of time, ROSS approached the JONES vehicle and  told JONES he
could leave and said in a nasty voice, "I hope you're late for something".  ROSS did not issue a citation
to JONES at the scene of the alleged traffic offense.<p>     
110. Subsequently, JONES received a citation in the mail for disorderly conduct.   JONES took a
day off from work to go to traffic court to challenge the citation.  The citation was dismissed when
ROSS did not appear for the hearing, although he was present in the courthouse.<p>     
111. JONES filed a complaint with OPS.  OPS concluded that the complaint could not be sustained.
 JONES' witnesses were never contacted by OPS.     
<p>     
<b>Rhonda Thomas May</b><br>
112. On the evening of April 22, 1994, Plaintiff RHONDA THOMAS (MAY) and her niece
were attacked by a gang of people at St. Clair Village. <p>     
113. Ms. THOMAS went to the Southside Police Station to seek assistance.  THOMAS explained
the situation to Defendant REGIS BEATTY.  THOMAS asked BEATTY if a police officer could
accompany her back to St. Clair Village so that she and her niece could safely remove certain items of
clothing from her apartment.  BEATTY informed THOMAS that there were no officers available to
provide such assistance and even if there were officers available, he would not send them to St. Clair
Village.<p>     
114. Ms. THOMAS stood up and said to her niece, "come on, let's go to Beltzhoover and find us
a cop."  BEATTY replied in a nasty voice, "you do that and I'm not going to file your fucking papers."
 He then took the papers he had filled out and threw them across the desk onto the floor.  Ms.
THOMAS began to leave the station and said to her niece,  "come on, this guy's an asshole."<p>     
115. Ms. THOMAS was out of the station and at her driver's side car door when BEATTY
came running out screaming, "you're under arrest." Two other officers, Defendants J. R. HICKY and
JOHN D. JOHNSON, without legal justification or provocation,  grabbed Ms. THOMAS violently by
the arms and placed her hands in cuffs behind her back. <p>     
116. The Defendants used excessive and unreasonable force on THOMAS, causing injury. 
Ms. THOMAS was falsely charged with disorderly conduct, theft and resisting arrest.  She was taken
to the public safety building where she was detained for eighteen (18) hours.<p>     
117. The conditions of Ms. THOMAS confinement in the Public Safety Building were cruel
and unusual.  During her eighteen (18) hour detention, she was given nothing to eat.  Besides sharing
an incredibly filthy cell with many other detainees, Ms. THOMAS was forced to use an open toilet
stall, positioned so that other prisoners and officers could observe her.  Ms. THOMAS, who was
menstruating at this time, suffered great embarrassment and humiliation from this.  Finding no
garbage cans, she asked an officer where she could dispose of her sanitary pad.  She was told to just
throw it on the floor.<p>     
118. At a hearing before a district justice, the theft and resisting arrest charges were dismissed. 
Ms. THOMAS was only found guilty of disorderly conduct, a summary offense, for allegedly
"screaming." 
Ms. THOMAS did not challenge this conviction for disorderly conduct even though it was
unfounded since she did not have sufficient resources to pursue the matter on appeal.   <p>     
119. Ms. THOMAS complained directly to Defendant MURPHY about the incident.  No action
was taken.  Ms. THOMAS also filed a complaint with OPS.  OPS made a finding of "not sustained" as
to such complaint.  At the recommendation of the Chief's Office, Defendant SIRABELLA disapproved
the "not sustained" recommendation, reducing it to "unfounded."  Since "not sustained" findings are at
least recorded in an officer's personnel file, SIRABELLA's action insured that no mention of the
incident was recorded in the officers' files.  Otherwise, the officers were never disciplined or given any
retraining as a result of this incident in question.
<p>     
<b>Jeffrey Lucas</b><br>
120. On May 31, 1994, Plaintiff JEFFREY LUCAS attended the Pink Floyd concert at Three
Rivers Stadium with his wife.  During the concert, LUCAS observed police escorting two men from
his section who had been yelling obscenities and disturbing other attendees.  Shortly thereafter, two
other men were disruptive and blocking the LUCAS'S view of the show.  Mr. LUCAS approached
Defendant CHARLES JOHNSON to tell him about the developing problem and asked if he could
speak with the two gentlemen so that perhaps they could sit down.  JOHNSON rudely replied, "shut
the fuck up and sit down or I'll arrest your ass."  He then said, "this is a fucking concert, what do you
expect?  Now sit down or I'll arrest your ass."  LUCAS replied, "don't say I didn't warn you about
these guys."  When LUCAS bent over to look at JOHNSON's badge, JOHNSON replied angrily,
"number 3050 punk; now sit down."<p>     
121. Mr. LUCAS and his wife decided to leave the concert early to beat traffic.  As they were
walking out, they passed Defendant JOHNSON and another officer, Defendant ROBERT THOMAS.
 LUCAS informed JOHNSON that he would be hearing from LUCAS' attorney tomorrow.<p>     
 122.     THOMAS grabbed LUCAS, and without provocation or reasonable justification, used
excessive force against LUCAS, causing injury.  THOMAS then placed the cuffs on Mr. LUCAS's
hands so tight that they became numb. <p>     
123. Mr. LUCAS was falsely arrested for disorderly conduct, resisting arrest and aggravated assault.
 He was wrongfully detained at the Public Safety Building for seventeen hours.  At a hearing before a
City magistrate, the resisting arrest and aggravated assault charges were dismissed.  LUCAS was
found guilty of a summary offense, disorderly conduct.  Mr. LUCAS did not, for reasons of finance
and time, pursue an appeal of the false charge.<p>     
124. Mr. LUCAS filed a complaint with OPS.  OPS concluded that there was conflicting evidence
so that the complaint could not be sustained.  Defendant SIRABELLA disapproved the "not
sustained" recommendation, reducing it to "unfounded."  Accordingly, Defendant SIRABELLA over
ruled the recommendation of OPS to ensure that no mention of the incident was contained in the
officers' files.  Otherwise, the officers were never disciplined or given retraining as a result of this
incident.
<p>     
<b>John Neidig</b><br>
125. On August 30, 1995, Plaintiff JOHN NEIDIG was driving in Pittsburgh's Northside. 
Upon seeing a Pittsburgh Police van making a left turn without using a turn signal, NEIDIG called out
the window, "nice turn signal."  The police van immediately made a U-turn and pulled NEIDIG over.<p>     
126. Defendant TIMOTHY KREGER approached the car and asked NEIDIG for his license
and registration.  When NEIDIG asked why, KREGER replied, "I don't like your attitude; who do you
think you are?"  <p>     
127. Approximately 15 minutes later, KREGER returned from the van and instructed NEIDIG to
turn on his right turn signal, sound the horn, turn on the headlights and buckle his seat belt.  KREGER
then informed NEIDIG that he was being issued two citations: one for failing to use a turn signal when
the police pulled him over, and the other for not having signed his temporary driver's license. 
KREGER then told NEIDIG to "take the tickets and your attitude back to [his suburban home]." 
NEIDIG informed KREGER that he intended to fight the tickets, to which KREGER responded,
"good, I get overtime for that."<p>     
128. NEIDIG immediately proceeded to his place of employment, approximately one and one
half miles away.  NEIDIG was surprised to see that the van followed closely behind until he reached
the destination.  Angered by the ongoing harassment over a simple comment to the police, NEIDIG
exited his vehicle in the parking lot and said to KREGER and JOHN DOE 10 that the magistrate was
going to hear about this ongoing harassment when he went in to challenge the tickets.   DOE 10 began
mocking NEIDIG in the manner of a first grader.  NEIDIG replied, "you said I have an attitude;
maybe you have a fucking attitude, too."  <p>     
129. NEIDIG proceeded to the rear of his building, where KREGER and DOE 1 falsely arrested
him for disorderly conduct.  After placing NEIDIG in handcuffs, KREGER used unnecessary and
excessive force against NEIDIG causing injuries to his neck and head that required medical treatment. <p>     
130. While transporting NEIDIG, KREGER and DOE 1 drove at a high rate of speed and
twice slammed on the brakes, hurtling NEIDIG into the sides of the van.  Each time the officers
laughed.<p>     
131. KREGER and DOE 1 falsely charged NEIDIG with disorderly conduct and resisting arrest.  As a
result, NEIDIG was illegally detained for twenty-four hours at the Public Safety Building. 
Both criminal charges were subsequently dismissed by a magistrate.<p>     
143. At all times relevant hereto, the unlawful arrest, incarceration, and the use of excessive force
in the filing of false and malicious charges against the Plaintiff NEIDIG, were carried out in
accordance with the accepted practice of the Defendant CITY OF PITTSBURGH police department
to retaliate against citizens who engage in protected first amendment activities.
<p>     
<b>June Bryant</b><br>
132. On April 27, 1994, Plaintiff JUNE BRYANT was sitting in her car talking with her
grandson, who was standing alongside the vehicle.  A Pittsburgh police car drove up and the two
officers stared at BRYANT and her grandson.  When the grandson returned the stare, Defendant
GIFORE said, "what you lookin' at?"  BRYANT told Defendant GIFORE he had no business talking
to her grandson in that manner. <p>     
133. BRYANT then left the area and drove to a nearby video store.  The police car followed her. 
When she parked at the video store and exited her vehicle, Defendant GIFORE approached to question
her.  A number of young men who were in the area knew BRYANT from her work at the local
community center.  They asked her if there was any problem and why the police were bothering her. 
She told them that everything was alright and that they should just mind their own business.  At all
relevant times, BRYANT'S speech was peaceful and protected by the first amendment to the U.S.
Constitution.<p>     
134. GIFORE then told BRYANT she was under arrest and ordered her to place her hands on the
hood of the car, illegally searched her person and her car, and then placed her in handcuffs.  GIFORE
falsely arrested BRYANT for disorderly conduct, recklessly endangering another person and
conspiracy.   These charges were brought without probable cause and/or  without reason to believe or
suspect that BRYANT's conduct violated any provision of the Crimes Code of Pennsylvania.  To the
contrary, such charges were brought because the officer was offended by BRYANT'S constitutionally
protected comments, in retaliation for said comments and/or because of Ms. BRYANT'S race or color. <p>     

135. GIFORE refused to allow BRYANT, who suffers from asthma, to get her inhaler out of the
car before he drove her away.  The Defendants drove BRYANT'S car to the Zone 5 police station.
 Subsequently, GIFORE ordered that BRYANT'S car be towed to the pound.<p>     
136. BRYANT was illegally detained at the Public Safety Building for approximately 20 hours. 
All of the charges except the one for disorderly conduct (a summary offense) against BRYANT
were dismissed during a hearing in City Court.  The judge found BRYANT guilty of disorderly
conduct because BRYANT had admitted arguing with the officer.  BRYANT did not appeal the
finding for lack of resources.<p>     
137. BRYANT filed a complaint with OPS.  OPS found no wrongdoing on the part of GIFORE
and no disciplinary action was taken against him as a result of the incident. 
<p>     
149. At all times relevant hereto, the arrest of BRYANT, and the filing of serious charges against
her, carried out in accordance with the Defendant CITY OF PITTSBURGH police department's
accepted practice of retaliating against a citizen for engaging in protected first amendment activities
and as a result of the fact that she is African-American.
<p>     
<b>Grinage & Troy Wilson</b><br>
138. GRINAGE WILSON and TROY WILSON have on more than 15 occasions during the past
two years been illegally harassed, searched without reasonable suspicion or probable cause, beaten
without sufficient legal authority or justification, and/or illegally   detained and arrested.  It is believed
and thereon alleged that the repeated violations of Plaintiffs' constitutional rights by the individually
named Defendants are caused by Plaintiffs' appearance, namely, they are young African-American
males.<p>     
139. On or about July, 1994, GRINAGE WILSON and a friend drove to a Western Avenue 
auto garage.  GRINAGE WILSON'S brother drove a van to the garage for repair work.  Upon
completing the business transaction with the owner and entering the car, three police officers,
including Defendant CHARLES DESHIELDS, surrounded the car with their guns pointed at
WILSON and the two others.  The officers' use of force was excessive and unjustified.  The officers
demanded to know whether the young men had drugs or guns.  Without a warrant or legally justifiable
cause, the Defendant officers searched WILSON'S person.  After telling the three young men to leave
the scene, the officers drove away.  Upon information and belief, WILSON and his two colleagues
were illegally stopped and detained solely  on account of their gender, race and age.  It is also believed
that this illegal, racially motivated stop was one of many that occurred in the geographic area on or
about that same day.<p>     
140. During the fall of 1994, Plaintiffs GRINAGE and TROY WILSON were illegally stopped
and questioned four or five times, mostly on Pittsburgh's Northside. <p>     
141. In addition, on October 21, 1994, TROY WILSON and two friends were driving on the
Northside when a police car began following them.  When they pulled into the parking lot of a Kuhn's
Market, the officer flashed his police car lights just as WILSON and his friends were parking the car. 
The plaintiffs sat in the car with their hands in the air.  When additional police cars arrived, Defendant
DOE 2 told the three plaintiffs to step outside.  Defendant CLARK then used excessive and
unjustifiable force in throwing TROY WILSON across the hood of the car and violently pushing him
against the back window of the car.  CLARK then illegally searched TROY WILSON.  After the 
search, CLARK grabbed and squeezed TROY WILSON'S  testicles at least two times while verbally
taunting him.  When TROY WILSON complained about the police abuse, DOE 2 issued TROY
WILSON a disorderly conduct citation in retaliation for the constitutionally protected comments. 
When TROY WILSON continued to complaint, DOE 2 threw WILSON against the car, handcuffed
him, and illegally detained him.  WILSON was transported to Zone 1 station, where he was released
into his mother's custody.  A complaint filed with OPS resulted in no discipline of the officers.<p>     
142. In February of 1995, at approximately 6 p.m.,  TROY WILSON and a friend stopped their
vehicle in front of the friend's house on Perrysville Road.  Two police officers, Defendants DOE  3 and
DOE 3 illegally detained TROY WILSON, forcing him from the car, and illegally searched both his
person and the vehicle.  No contraband was found and the plaintiffs were released.<p>     
143. In early March, 1995, GRINAGE WILSON was walking up Perrysville Avenue. 
Defendant CLARK pulled his police car next to him, got out of the driver's seat and told GRINAGE
WILSON to get up against the wall, and conducted an illegal search by patting him down and pulling
out his pockets.  No contraband was found.  CLARK asked WILSON where he was going and then
told him to "get the fuck home." <p>      
144. On March 20, 1995, TROY WILSON, GRINAGE WILSON and a friend were walking
to another friend's home, about three blocks away from their own residence.  TROY and his friend
had walked up ahead when a police car pulled up next to GRINAGE.  The driver, Defendant CLARK,
hopped out of the car, placed a hand on his gun and  walked towards GRINAGE.  CLARK asked
GRINAGE where his gun was.  GRINAGE, without being asked,  spread eagled up against the police
car.  CLARK conducted an illegal search of GRINAGE, finding no contraband.  At this time TROY
and his friend walked back from around the corner to see what was happening.  CLARK told
GRINAGE not to look back or he would "split [his] head open."  TROY asked CLARK why he had
stopped GRINAGE.  CLARK told TROY to leave.  TROY  refused, indicating that it was his brother
and that he did not want to leave him alone.  TROY sat down in a nearby grassy area.  Defendant
KOHNFELDER came over and grabbed TROY by the shirt and threw him up on the police car.  
KOHNFELDER then illegally searched TROY and placed him under arrest.  GRINAGE looked back
when KOHNFELDER grabbed TROY, at which point CLARK and Defendant SAMUEL
BARRONE used excessive and unreasonable force on GRINAGE WILSON, causing injury. 
Simultaneously, KOHNFELDER and DOE 5 used excessive and unjustifiable force against TROY
WILSON, causing injury.  The officers falsely arrested both GRINAGE and TROY WILSON.  Both
GRINAGE and TROY WILSON received medical treatment for their injuries.  TROY WILSON was
illegally detained for two hours.  GRINAGE WILSON was illegally detained for twelve hours.  All
charges against GRINAGE WILSON were dismissed by a judge.  TROY WILSON was found guilty
of a summary offense, disorderly conduct, in juvenile court.  A complaint filed with OPS resulted in
no discipline of the officers.<p>     
145. In April, 1995, at approximately 4:00 p.m., GRINAGE and TROY WILSON were driving
on the Northside with a friend.  A Pittsburgh police car began following them.  As soon as they pulled
over at the friend's home to let him off, police cars surrounded them. Defendants DAMIAN WILES
and DOES 6 and 7 searched the three in the middle of the street, forcing cars to navigate around them. 
These searches, which were unsupported by probable cause or consent, involved looking inside
pockets, putting the contents found in their pockets on the hood of the car and taking off their shoes. 
This humiliating search lasted approximately 20 minutes.  The three men were subsequently let go
with no charges filed against them.<p>     
146. On June 26, 1995, TROY and GRINAGE WILSON and a friend stopped their vehicle on
the corner of Perrysville Road and Clayton Avenue.  Just as the four were about to pull away,
Defendant JOHN DOE SYNKOWKI walked across the parking lot and held up his hand instructing
them to stop.  Within five minutes four or five police cars and vans arrived on the scene.  Defendant
SYNKOWSKI and DOES 8 through 15 placed the plaintiffs up against the car, searched, without
sufficient probable cause or consent, their persons and possessions, including their wallets.   The
Defendants then illegally searched the interior of the car.  Upon finding no contraband, the Defendants
informed the four young men that they could leave.  The entire search and detention took
approximately 20-25 minutes.  Neither TROY nor GRINAGE WILSON were charged with any
criminal offense.<p>     
147. July 29, 1995, GRINAGE WILSON returned home at approximately 1:20 a.m.  He
encountered 3 police cars in front of his house.  He pulled into the driveway.  One of the police cars
pulled in behind him.  GRINAGE exited the car.  Defendant KENNETH KOHNFELDER, without
sufficient cause or consent, searched GRINAGE by going through his pockets and patting down his
clothing.  KOHNFELDER then illegally placed GRINAGE in handcuffs and put him into the back of
the police car.  KOHNFELDER then proceeded to search GRINAGE'S  car, including the trunk. 
KOHNFELDER then released GRINAGE WILSON after speaking with GRINAGE's mother, Shirley
Sloan.  No charges were filed against GRINAGE WILSON.<p>     
148. In early September, 1995, TROY WILSON and two friends parked in a lot by WPXI-TV
studios while one of the young men ran into his aunt's home.  Three or four police cars pulled into the
parking lot, surrounding TROY'S car.  DOES 16 and 17 ordered TROY and his friend out of the car. 
The young men were then searched, without sufficient cause or consent.  Finding no contraband, DOE     
16 said something about a "suspicious vehicle" and then the police cars left the scene. <p>     
149. After several other encounters not discussed herein between Pittsburgh police officers and the
two WILSON Plaintiffs, Shirley Sloan asked CITY OF PITTSBURGH Deputy Police Chief Moffat
to instruct Zone 1 police officers to leave her children alone.  Moffat promised to call Zone 1
Commander McNeilly about the situation.  At approximately 1:30 the next morning, GRINAGE
WILSON was returning home from his girlfriend's house when a police officer pulled him over. 
GRINAGE walked back to the police car and asked what he had done wrong.  The driver of the car,
Defendant JOHN DOE LAGOWSKI,  informed GRINAGE that he was speeding.  At this time, the
other officer, Defendant DOE 18, walked up to GRINAGE, told him to "shut up," and then proceeded
to abuse him verbally.   When GRINAGE objected to the verbal abuse, DOE 18  immediately placed
GRINAGE under arrest and threw him into the back of the police van.    The Defendants held
GRINAGE in the van for approximately thirty (30) minutes, whereupon he was released without
charge. 
<p>     
150. On October 6, 1995, at approximately 4:30 p.m., GRINAGE WILSON and a friend
parked their van on Burgess Street, where they were waiting for GRINAGE'S girlfriend.  Defendant,
DOE 19 approached GRINAGE and asked for his driver's license and insurance papers.  GRINAGE
produced both.  DOE 19 then instructed the two young men to exit the car and to put their hands on
the car door.  The officer then searched, without sufficient cause or consent, GRINAGE'S pockets and
clothing, with all of GRINAGE'S loose coins being spilled on the street.  DOE 19 then instructed
GRINAGE and the other young man to sit on the police car hood.  DOES 19 and 20 then searched the
entire interior of the van.  GRINAGE did not consent to the search, nor was there sufficient cause to
conduct such a search.  No charges were filed.
<p>     151. On October 6, at approximately 7:00 p.m., TROY WILSON and a friend were in their van
going to pick up GRINAGE at his girl friend's house.  Upon arriving at the destination, where
GRINAGE was waiting out front, Defendant CIUMMO got out of a police car and approached the
driver, TROY WILSON.  CIUMMO asked TROY how old he was, then demanded his license and
registration.  Defendant CANNON then told GRINAGE, who was standing next to the van, to "get the
fuck out of there."  GRINAGE replied that he was getting ready to get into the van.  CANNON, using
excessive and unjustified force,  grabbed GRINAGE and threw him up against an adjacent storefront,
pushed him back, and tried to throw GRINAGE on the ground.  CIUMMO assisted CANNON in
attempting to bring GRINAGE to the ground.  TROY stepped out of the van to see what the officers
were doing to GRINAGE.  The officers reached for their guns and ordered TROY not to move.  Upon
placing GRINAGE in handcuffs, CIUMMO placed TROY in handcuffs and violently threw him into
the back of the police wagon.  DOE 21 then hit GRINAGE in the face with  his fist while GRINAGE
was in handcuffs.  CIUMMO then threw GRINAGE into the back of the police wagon.   As
GRINAGE lay sprawled in the back of the wagon, DOE 21 hit GRINAGE in the legs with a night
stick.  TROY WILSON was falsely charged with and arrested for disorderly conduct, aggravated
assault and interfering with justice.  He was illegally detained for three and a half days at Shuman
Center and then held under house arrest until October 21, 1995.  All charges against TROY were
dismissed by a Juvenile Court judge.  GRINAGE WILSON was falsely charged with and arrested for
disorderly conduct, interfering with justice and three counts of aggravated assault.  GRINAGE was
held at the Public Safety Building over night.  He was released on his own recognizance the next
morning.  The charges are pending.  Shirley Sloan complained that same day to then Chief of Police,
Defendant EARL BUFORD.  She asked that the harassment of her children cease immediately.
<p>     152. On October 22, 1995, GRINAGE WILSON and a friend were returning from his aunt's
house when he pulled his vehicle to the curb to avoid a possible collision with a City of Pittsburgh
police cruiser that was being operated in a reckless manner.  This same police vehicle pulled behind
the stopped vehicle which GRINAGE WILSON was operating.  Defendant SCOT OBER and DOE
22 emerged from the police car with their guns drawn and pointed at GRINAGE and his friend.  The
officers told the young men to put both hands in the air and to drop the keys out of the window. 
OBER walked up to GRINAGE, opened the door while pointing his gun at GRINAGE'S head,
grabbed him around the waist, pushed him into the middle of the street and told him to get down. 
Meanwhile, cars were coming down the street.  DOE 22 told OBER to get GRINAGE out of the street
before he was run over.  OBER moved GRINAGE to the sidewalk, where he illegally searched his
person and clothing.   OBER then falsely issued GRINAGE citations for reckless driving and failure
to stop at a stop sign.  Shortly after this incident, Defendant OBER was involved in a widely
publicized stop of Pittsburgh Steeler wide receiver, Johnny Barnes, whereby OBER held a gun to
Barnes's head while he kneeled by the side of the road.
<p>     153. During this period of harassment, false detentions and arrests, illegal searches and excessive
force, Shirley Sloan filed at least five complaints with OPS.  No disciplinary action has been taken
against any of the officers involved.
<p>     154. As a result of all of these illegal stops, searches and arrests, the police have never found a
weapon or drugs on either GRINAGE or TROY WILSON.  To date, GRINAGE WILSON has no
criminal record.  TROY WILSON has one juvenile court, disorderly conduct conviction.  The same
charge against GRINAGE WILSON arising from the same incident was dismissed by the Common
Pleas Court.
<p>     
<b>George Diggs</b><br>
<p>     155. On October 18, 1994, at approximately 6:00 p.m.,  Plaintiff GEORGE DIGGS was sitting on
the steps of an abandoned building in the Hill District speaking with a long-time friend, who is 86
years old.   
<p>     156. Defendant ANTHONY CHARLES approached the two men in his patrol car, stopped in front
of the abandoned building and, without lawful authority or sufficient justification, ordered them to
"get off the steps and move along."  DIGGS attempted to explain that the two men were just sitting
there talking.  CHARLES asked DIGGS if he "owned the building."  DIGGS replied, "do you own it." 
CHARLES became visibly angered by this response, jumping out of his police car and ordering
DIGGS to get up against the car, spread his hands as far apart as he could and to do the same with his
feet.
<p>     157. CHARLES patted down DIGGS' clothing and then ran his hand up the inside of DIGGS'
pant legs, forcibly, excessively and without justification driving the side of his hand into DIGGS'
crotch.  CHARLES initially told DIGGS he was under arrest and then said that he was not under
arrest.
<p>     158. CHARLES issued DIGGS a citation for obstructing traffic in retaliation for
DIGGS' constitutionally protected comments.  The citation was dismissed by the magistrate when
CHARLES failed to show up for the hearing.    The older gentleman with DIGGS was not issued a
citation.
<p>     159. DIGGS filed a complaint with OPS.  OPS issued a report exonerating Defendant CHARLES
of any wrongdoing.  No disciplinary action was taken against CHARLES.
<p>     
<b>Tracy Liller</b><br>
160. On October 22, 1995, Plaintiff TRACY LILLER, while traveling with her 8-year old son and
a friend, was pulled over and arrested for driving under the influence.  The arresting officers indicated
that a pat down search was necessary.<p>     
161. LILLER, who is handicapped because of a serious back condition, agreed but requested that
the pat down search be done by a female police officer.  At the time of this request,LILLER was
handcuffed.  Defendant ROSEMARY BORELLI was called to the scene by the arresting officers.<p>     
162. Immediately upon arriving, BORELLI began screaming at LILLER, asking her what was
so special about her body. BORELLI said that she would "show everyone what's so precious." <p>     
163. BORELLI then roughly pulled up LILLER'S shirt and bra, exposing her breasts to 5 male
police officers, as well as other motorists.  In addition, BORELLI violently grabbed LILLER's left
breast.<p>     
164. When LILLER said that she would complain about this treatment, BORELLI hit LILLER in
the eye and two other male officers, WRIGHT and (white, male) JOYCE, slammed her into a brick
wall.  At that time, BORELLI said, "I'll give you something to complain about."  BORELLI also said
that "nothing's going to happen to me anyway."<p>     
165. LILLER was held for twelve hours by the police before being released.  Upon being
released, LILLER went to South Side Hospital where she called the police to report the beating she
had received.<p>     
166. Despite her obvious injuries, the police refused to take a report from LILLER.
<p>     
<b>Lloyd Willacy  </b><br>
167. LLOYD WILLACY, a 37 year old black Jamaican citizen, was lawfully and peacefully
standing in the doorway of his South Side residence in the early evening of August 11, 1994, looking
in the direction of the street.  He was on a study break.<p>     
168. A City of Pittsburgh police car that had circled the block once while Mr. WILLACY was
standing in the doorway, stopped the second time as it approached the Plaintiff's residence.<p>     
169. The officer in the car, Defendant DOE 23, called out to the Plaintiff, referring to him in
a derogatory fashion as "boy", and ordered Mr. WILLACY to come over to the car, and then,
without explanation, asked him whether he had immigration papers to confirm that he was legally in
the United States.<p>     
170. In response to DOE 23's question, Mr. WILLACY informed him that he had a green card
inside his residence and would retrieve it for him.  When the Plaintiff turned toward the house to
retrieve his green card, the officer indicated that he was going to enter the house with the Plaintiff.  a)
Mr. WILLACY did not want DOE 23 to enter his residence and unequivocally informed the officer of
that fact.  Despite expressly telling the officer to wait outside--on the street side of his screen door--the
officer, without a warrant or probable cause for doing so, opened the screen door and entered Plaintiff's
residence.<p>     
171. WILLACY then told DOE 23 that he had no right to be in his residence without a warrant.
 Despite that legitimate protestation, the officer refused to leave.<p>     
172. When Mr. WILLACY walked over to a dresser in his bedroom to retrieve his green card,
the officer pushed him aside and, without Plaintiff's permission, started sifting through papers on top of
the dresser.  Some of the papers contained sensitive medical information.<p>     
173. When WILLACY complained about what the officer had done--repeating that the Defendant
had no right to be in his residence and was harassing him, the Defendant officer threatened to arrest
him and ordered the Plaintiff to "shut [his] fuckin' mouth," or he would arrest him.<p>     
174. Finally, after other Pittsburgh police officers, who had been summoned by DOE 23 arrived at
Mr. WILLACY's residence and pacified DOE 23, he left.<p>     
175. Mr. WILLACY's reasonable expectation that his residence would not be entered without
probable cause or a warrant, and his right of privacy in his personal papers and effects was trampled
on by DOE 23.<p>     
176. The illegal entry into Plaintiff's residence, the handling and reading of Plaintiff's
privileged papers, and the officer's hostile behavior and threats of arrest engendered emotional distress,
anxiety, humiliation and pain and suffering.<p>     
177. In the wake of the incident, Mr. WILLACY filed a complaint with OPS alleging misconduct
on the part of the officer whose name was unknown to the Plaintiff but whose photograph the Plaintiff
picked out of a photo-lineup.<p>     
178. Despite receiving a graphic report of an illegal entry and search of his residence, OPS
exonerated the officer and dismissed the complaint without explanation.
<p>     
<b>Danine Kaercher</b><br>
179. The factual allegations contained in KAERCHER's civil rights complaint, Kaercher v.
Officer Plamier, et. al.  Civil Action No. 96-417 (W.D. Pa.) are incorporated herein by reference.
180. KAERCHER is represented by the undersigned counsel.  Her complaint was filed earlier to
avoid the statute of limitations.  KAERCHER's attorneys will file appropriate motions to consolidate
her case with this one.
<p>     
<b>Damon Williams</b><br>
181. On October 4, 1994, DAMON WILLIAMS and three friends were in the alleyway behind
his Manchester residence.  They were not engaged in any criminal activity.
<p>     182. The Plaintiff saw a van driving the wrong way up the one way alleyway--without headlights
on--and feared that the vehicle was being driven by gang members.  To avoid a confrontation, he ran
down the alleyway away from the vehicle.<p>     
183. CITY OF PITTSBURGH police officer, KEVIN GASIOROWSKI, who was on foot in the
area, suddenly appeared, ran toward the Plaintiff with his gun drawn, and without warning or
justification, struck the Plaintiff in the face with the gun barrel, slammed him to the ground and kneed
him in his back while the Plaintiff was lying face down.<p>     
184. A complaint was filed by Mr. WILLIAMS with OPS describing what had occurred and
alleging that GASIOROWSKI had harassed him previously.<p>     
185. Four days after the incident in question, GASIOROWSKI again searched the Plaintiff
without reason to believe or suspect he had committed a crime and in an unnecessarily abusive
manner.  A complaint about that incident was joined with the previous OPS complaint.<p>     
186. On January 14, 1995, OPS issued a decision exonerating GASIOROWSKI concluding that
"[n]o evidence has been presented that Officer GASIOROWSKI violated any of the Rules and
Regulations of the Pittsburgh Police Department" and that the allegations "cannot be proven or
disproven" because there was no documentation of injuries or corroboration by an "independent
witness".  The case was closed.
<p>     
<b>Melvin Marie Williams</b><br>
187. In the early morning of December 17, 1994, CITY OF PITTSBURGH Officers
RAYMOND PODVOREC and KEVIN GASIOROWSKI came to an alleyway behind Ms.
WILLIAMS' residence in conjunction with the arrest of a young African-American man for disorderly
conduct.<p>     
188. In the course of that transaction, MARIE WILLIAMS (a member of a community
organization that monitors police abuses of Manchester residents) objected to the treatment of the
young man by the police officers; questioned why the man was being arrested; stated, in substance,
that officers had a low regard for the African-American community; questioned Officer PODVOREC's
comment that the residents of Manchester didn't deserve police protection because they didn't pay
taxes; emphasized to the handful of persons who were witnessing the transaction that because of police
hostility to blacks, it was important for African-Americans to understand the law and their rights; and
noted that her organization was attempting to bring a representative from the State to teach residents
about ethnic intimidation issues and their rights when dealing with police officers.<p>     
189. At that, Defendant PODVOREC (who was visibly angered by Plaintiff's statement) said
in substance that the Plaintiff had too much to say, was going to learn, and proceeded to arrest her with
the assistance of Officer GASIOROWSKI.<p>     
190. Marie WILLIAMS was charged by Officer PODVOREC with Failure to Disperse, Inciting a
Riot, and Disorderly Conduct, all criminal offenses under state law that are punishable by
imprisonment.  Because of those false and baseless charges, she was confined in the Pittsburgh Public
Safety Building for more than a day while awaiting release on bail.<p>     
191. MARIE WILLIAMS had committed none of the offenses for which she was charged
and PODVOREC lacked probable cause when arresting the Plaintiff to believe that she had.<p>     
192. The unjust arrest and prosecution that were triggered by the Defendants' false charges were
in retaliation for Plaintiff's statements and her peaceful exercise of free speech.  She was arrested,
charged and prosecuted for the content of her speech rather than for an actual commission of a crime.<p>     
193. In the course of the arrest, Office GASIOROWSKI used excessive force and physically
injured the Plaintiff.<p>     
194. On December 22, 1994, after a hearing before a City of Pittsburgh Magistrate all charges
against the Plaintiff were dismissed.
<p>     
<b>Eric W. Simpson</b><br>
195. ERIC W. SIMPSON is an unordained practicing minister in the City of Pittsburgh. 196. On the
afternoon of July 19, 1995, SIMPSON was peaceably speaking to a friend in Market Square when
ordered by CITY OF PITTSBURGH police officer JOHN DOE THIROS to leave the square.
<p>     197. As Reverend SIMPSON began walking from the Square, THIROS came up behind him,
twisted his arm behind his back, and ordered the Plaintiff to get on his knees.  At that, Officer
THIROS said: "This is my Square.  I run the Square.  Next time you'll do what I say", or words to that
effect.
<p>     198. The Defendant called for a patrol car, carried Reverend SIMPSON off to the Public
Safety Building, and held the Plaintiff against his will for nearly an hour before charging him with the
summary offense of disorderly conduct and releasing him from confinement.
<p>     199. There was no legitimate reason or justification for arresting and imprisoning Reverend
SIMPSON on the afternoon of July 19, 1995 in Market Square.
<p>     
<b>David Kintu</b><br>
200. On or about October 22, 1995, at approximately midnight, DAVID KINTU was attending a
party in the Shadyside section of the City of Pittsburgh when CITY OF PITTSBURGH police officers
ordered him and other persons in attendance to leave the premises.  Mr. KINTU cooperated with the
order to leave the premises along with other friends who had accompanied him to the party, and after
exiting  the building stood outside waiting for another friend who was still at the party to come out so
that the group could leave together.  <p>     
201. As Mr. KINTU stood outside of the building, Defendants, CITY OF PITTSBURGH
police officers DEBBIE EYNON and Officer PULEO, ordered KINTU to leave the area. When
KINTU attempted to explain why he was waiting outside of the building, the Defendants demanded to
see his identification, and upon discovering that he was a resident alien, declared to him "Why don't
you go back to your country!" and then issued a citation to KINTU for failure to disperse, a summary
offense.<p>     
202. Upon receipt of the citation, KINTU began walking away from the police officers and turned
to the police officers and stated that "he had a right to be in this country and that the police officer
should have known that", at which point, DAVID KINTU, who had committed no criminal offense in
connection with the events of October 22, 1995, was placed under arrest, transported to the Public
Safety Building, and confined in a cell in the Public Safety Building for approximately 12 hours. 
KINTU was charged with  the criminal offenses of failure to disperse and disorderly conduct,
although, at the time of his arrest Officer EYNON told him that he was arrested because he was
"drunk", even though Mr. KINTU had only consumed one beer during the entire evening.
<p>     203. A Preliminary Hearing was scheduled on the charges brought against KINTU on the 6th day
of November, 1995, at which time both police officers failed to appear.  At a subsequent
Preliminary Hearing, the charges of failure to disperse were dropped, and the charge of disorderly
conduct was dismissed.  At all times relevant hereto, all of the charges filed against Mr. KINTU were
brought in retaliation for the exercise of protected first amendment speech and/or because Mr. KINTU
was black, and/or because of his national origin, Ugandan.
<p>     
<b>William Martin</b><br>
204. On March 28, 1994, WILLIAM MARTIN, at approximately 5:00 P.M. appeared at the Zone
One CITY OF PITTSBURGH police station to inquire about a traffic citation that had been issued to
his son for the use of headlight covers on a vehicle that was being operated in daylight hours.  Mr.
MARTIN was initially assisted by the sergeant on duty, without incident, when the Defendant, CITY
OF PITTSBURGH police officer, Lt.  FRIEK, loudly and in a threatening voice stated that the
headlight covers were illegal, and that Mr. MARTIN should leave the police station.  When Mr.
MARTIN explained that he was being assisted by the sergeant on duty, FRIEK demanded that
MARTIN immediately leave the police station stating to MARTIN "get out of my police station", and
upon failing to do so, arrested MARTIN on false charges of disorderly conduct and defiant trespass. 
When Mr. MARTIN's son, Dennis, asked why his father had been arrested, he was also threatened
with arrest.  MARTIN was then forcibly handcuffed and placed in a cell at the Number One Station. 
When Mrs. MARTIN arrived at the Number One Station and inquired about her husband's condition,
she was also threatened with arrest by Defendant FRIEK.<p>     
205. The condition of Mr. MARTIN's confinement in the Public Safety Building constituted cruel
and unusual punishment during several hours of his detention, despite the fact that the CITY
OF PITTSBURGH Police Department knew of his diabetic condition and the need for medication,
none was provided.  Mr. MARTIN, during the period of his confinement, went into diabetic shock and
required medical treatment at the Central Medical Pavilion.  Although Mr. MARTIN offered no
resistance to his arrest, he was handcuffed so tightly that he became numb from the right wrist to the
right shoulder up to his neck.  In addition, he was handcuffed behind his back while a white inmate at
the Number One Station was handcuffed loosely and in the front.  <p>     
206. At the Preliminary Hearing held in July of 1994, all charges brought against
WILLIAM MARTIN were dismissed.  At all times relevant hereto, all of the charges brought against
MARTIN were brought in retaliation for the exercise of protected first amendment speech and/or
because Mr. MARTIN is African-American.
<p>     
<b>Eric Jackson</b><br>
207. On or about October 24, 1995, at approximately 11:00 P.M., Mr. JACKSON drove to
the Westgate Apartment Complex to visit his cousin, who resides in such complex.  When JACKSON
exited his vehicle, he was approached by several CITY OF PITTSBURGH police officers, who were
identified as Task Force Police Officers.  DOE 24 ordered JACKSON to put his hands in the air, and
DOE 25 threw him up against his vehicle while DOE 26 grabbed JACKSON by the throat, choking
him, and ordering him to open his mouth.  While this unwarranted physical assault took place, DOES
27 through 30, without JACKSON's consent or probable cause, began searching JACKSON's vehicle.
<p>     208. When JACKSON protested his treatment, and demanded to know the officers' names and
badge numbers, the officers refused to provide him with such information, other than one officer who
identified himself as SERGEANT LEO O'NEAL.  During the course of the above incident, the
officers, who assaulted Mr. JACKSON, called him "stupid", told him to "shut up", told him he had no
rights, and that the "Task Force" made the laws in this area.  One officer yelled to another " We got
him" and then turned to JACKSON and said "Just joking". 
<p>     209. After assaulting JACKSON and searching his vehicle, the police officers who engaged in
such conduct then left the area without charging Mr. JACKSON with any criminal offense.  The
Defendant police officers involved in this incident did not have reason to believe or suspect that
JACKSON had violated any provision of the Crimes Code of the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania.
<p>     210. At all times relevant hereto, the illegal search and seizure of the Plaintiff was carried out
on account of the Plaintiff's race and/or because he was in a predominately African-American
community.
<p>     
<b>Arlene Henderson</b><br>
211. On July 30, 1995, HENDERSON stopped a police officer passing in front of her house to
request assistance.  She asked the officer to have her adult son leave the premises.  The officer
instructed HENDERSON's son to leave.  The officer remained in the house, with HENDERSON's
permission.  He spoke on the telephone with HENDERSON's mother, to whose house the son had
been instructed to go. <p>     
212. Several minutes later, Ms. HENDERSON went to her entranceway.  She saw two other
police officers beating her son in front of the house.  HENDERSON left her home, touched the arm of
Defendant police officer, V. JOSEPH, asked him not to beat her son and informed him that a police
officer was inside the house and had already dealt with the situation.  Officer JOSEPH spoke back to
HENDERSON in a threatening manner, saying repeatedly, "you don't ever touch a police officer." 
HENDERSON apologized and backed away from the confrontation.  <p>     
213. JOSEPH then took HENDERSON aside and again repeated in a menacing tone, "you don't
ever touch a police officer."  HENDERSON again apologized and said that she meant no wrong. 
JOSEPH then violently grabbed HENDERSON's arms, put handcuffs on and with excessive and
unreasonable force, threw HENDERSON on the ground face down, causing injury.  JOSEPH then
turned HENDERSON on her back and again, without justification, hit HENDERSON in the right
eye, causing injury.  JOSEPH prepared to hit HENDERSON again in the face, but stopped when a
witness yelled, "Hey, don't you go hittin her again."<p>     
214. JOSEPH filed false charges of Obstructing Administration of Justice, Disorderly Conduct
and Public Drunkenness against HENDERSON.  HENDERSON was wrongfully detained for
approximately fourteen (14) hours at the Public Safety Building.<p>     
215. On November 30, 1995, a judge dismissed the charged of Obstructing Administration of
Justice and Public Drunkenness.  HENDERSON pled guilty to a summary offense disorderly conduct
charge, and received a fine and community service.  In her more than fifty years, Ms. HENDERSON
has never previously been arrested or convicted of an offense.<p>     
216. HENDERSON filed a complaint of misconduct with OPS against Defendant JOSEPH.  OPS
sent HENDERSON a letter indicating that no disciplinary action would be taken against JOSEPH. 
Emmanuel S. Anthou<p>     
217. On July 4, 1995, at approximately 7:00 P.M. in the vicinity of the Grandview Avenue area
across from the LeMont Restaurant, Plaintiff ANTHOU, who was not engaged in any criminal
activity, nor was there any reason to believe or suspect that he was engaged in such activity, was
assaulted by City of Pittsburgh police officer JOHN DOE 31, who struck ANTHOU in and about his
eye with a lit cigar which DOE  held in his hand when he punched Plaintiff ANTHOU in the face.
<p>     218. At or about the above time and place, Plaintiff ANTHOU was walking with several friends
along Grandview Avenue in the Mt. Washington section of the City of Pittsburgh, when one of the
persons accompanying him, and who was walking several feet ahead of ANTHOU became involved in
a dispute with a parking attendant.
<p>     219. As Plaintiff ANTHOU approached the location where his friend and the parking attendant
were involved in the dispute, and upon observing same, stated words to the effect that one of the
persons involved was his friend.
<p>     220. At the point Plaintiff made the statement that one of the persons involved in the dispute was
his friend, a uniformed City of Pittsburgh police officer, DOE 31, who was present at the scene of the
dispute, turned and without warning, provocation or reason to suspect that Plaintiff ANTHOU had
committed a criminal offense, struck Plaintiff in the face with his fist.
<p>     221. After Plaintiff was struck by Defendant DOE, the officer refused to give ANTHOU his
badge number or name and threatened to arrest ANTHOU if he persisted in his attempts to obtain
Defendant DOE's identification or take other action regarding the assault.
<p>     222. Plaintiff suffered injuries to his face and in and about his eye for which he received
emergency medical treatment.
<p>     
<b>Robert Neubauer</b><br>
223. On June 18, 1994 at approximately 7:30 P.M., ROBERT NEUBAUER was attending the
Three Rivers Arts Festival in and about the area of Point State Park in the City of Pittsburgh.  As
Mr. NEUBAUER and a friend proceeded from the area of Gateway Center towards Point State Park to
attend a scheduled Rock Concert, a sudden thunder storm caused them to seek shelter on the wide
pedestrian bridge beneath the parkway overpass at the entrance to Point State Park.  
<p>     224. As Mr. NEUBAUER and his friend waited for the rain to stop, Defendant, CITY
OF PITTSBURGH police officer, ANTHONY SCARPINE, approached Mr. NEUBAUER and
ordered him to leave the sheltered area of the pedestrian bridge into a driving rain.  When Mr.
NEUBAUER responded that he would leave the area as soon as the rain let up, Defendant,
SCARPINE, shouted "Don't give me any shit!  Get off the fucking bridge".  Mr. NEUBAUER then
asked Defendant, SCARPINE, why he (NEUBAUER and his friend) could not remain on the
pedestrian bridge since they were not  blocking any other pedestrian traffic, and also asked
SCARPINE to identify that section of the Penal Code or City Ordinance that was violated if
NEUBAUER remained on the bridge.  SCARPINE, at that point, became extremely abusive,
informing Mr. NEUBAUER that "I don't have to tell you.  I'm not taking any shit from you.  Move or
I'll arrest you".  
<p>     225. When Mr. NEUBAUER informed OFFICER SCARPINE that his actions were abusive,
and potentially constituted a violation of Mr. NEUBAUER's civil rights, OFFICER SCARPINE,
stated "I don't care.  You can't hurt me.  The City will pay for it anyway".  Defendant, SCARPINE, at
that point, grabbed NEUBAUER's right wrist, violently twisted it behind his back and began to apply
handcuffs in a direct, unwarranted attempt to arrest NEUBAUER.  Mr. NEUBAUER, wishing to
avoid any physical harm or further violation of his rights, agreed to leave the area and at that point
was released by OFFICER SCARPINE.
<p>     226. At all times relevant hereto, Plaintiff NEUBAUER had not violated any provision of the
Crimes Code of the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania, nor did the Defendant, SCARPINE, have any
reason to suspect or believe that NEUBAUER had committed any such offense, and all of the actions
taken by Defendant, SCARPINE, were in retaliation for NEUBAUER's exercise of protected first
amendment activities, including, but not limited to questioning Defendant SCARPINE's conduct.
<p>     227. Mr. NEUBAUER filed a complaint with OPS outlining the conduct of Defendant SCARPINE
in a lengthy correspondence dated July 28, 1994, wherein NEUBAUER informed the City of
Pittsburgh that, inter alia, he was a civil rights attorney, who was  among the attorneys representing
Rodney G. King, and that:
       <p>     <blockquote>   Officer Scarpine's actions were clearly in violation of the United States
          Constitution, and, moreover, seriously jeopardized the  interests of the
          taxpayers of the City of Pittsburgh.  Perhaps even more disturbing than
          Scarpine's unreasonable conduct, was his cavalier attitude with respect
          to the municipal [fiscal]  Apparently, Scarpine operates under the
          assumption that his actions are not circumscribed by law and, even if he
          oversteps his bounds, the people of the City of Pittsburgh will pay for it.
</blockquote><p>     
228. No action was taken against OFFICER SCARPINE by the Defendant, CITY OF
PITTSBURGH, or OPS, which dismissed NEUBAUER'S complaint as "not sustained".
<p>     
          <h3>ALLEGATIONS RELATING TO PRELIMINARY INJUNCTION</h3>
229. Plaintiffs and class members have a reasonable fear that they will continue to be subjected
to Defendants' unlawful and unconstitutional actions, policies, and practices and that Plaintiffs and
class members will continue to suffer injury and damage as a result thereof.<p>     
230. The named Plaintiffs live and travel in Pittsburgh and continue to encounter Pittsburgh
police officers.  Until such times as the deliberate indifference of the OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS is
remedied, the named individual Plaintiffs will continue to be at risk for the deprivation of their
constitutional rights.<p>     
231. The Plaintiff class has suffered and will continue to suffer irreparable injury unless this
Court orders injunctive relief sufficient to end the pattern, practice and custom of abuse of the
constitutional rights of Plaintiff class.<p>     
232. Named Plaintiffs have been subjected to repeated instances of unconstitutional conduct
by Pittsburgh police officers.   The ongoing abuse, harassment and misconduct is particularly
prevalent in the African-American neighborhoods of the City.<p>     
233. Plaintiffs are informed and believe and thereon allege that class members have been and are
being subjected to repeated instances of unconstitutional conduct by Pittsburgh police officers. <p>     
234. Constitutional violations by Pittsburgh police officers are pervasive.   Over 800
misconduct complaints were filed with OPS between 1992 and 1994.  The number of complaints set a
record high in 1994.  Plaintiffs are informed and believe and thereon allege that the number of
misconduct complaints filed with OPS in 1995 is at the same or at a higher level than in 1994.<p>     
235. Plaintiffs are informed and believe and thereon allege that many instances of police
misconduct go unreported to OPS.  Citizens perceive OPS to be an arm of the Police Department and,
therefore, are reluctant to file complaints.  Moreover, the community perceives OPS to be ineffective,
thereby further discouraging citizens from filing complaints with the agency.<p>     
236. Pittsburgh police officers have had multiple allegations of misconduct filed against them. 
The OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS have taken no effective measures to prevent recurring misconduct by
these and other officers.<p>     
237. Plaintiffs are informed and believe and thereon allege that based upon the the historical pattern of
misconduct by Pittsburgh police officers, the deliberate indifference of the OFFICIAL
DEFENDANTS to this pattern of misconduct, and the repeated denials by OFFICIAL
DEFENDANTS that a pattern of abuse and misconduct exists, Plaintiffs and class members are likely
to be the victims of future incidents similar to those set forth in this Complaint, and that there is a real
and immediate threat that Defendants will inflict further injury and damage on them, for which there is
no adequate remedy at law.
<p>     
<h3>Causes of Action</h3>
<p>     
<b>First Cause of Action</b><br>
238. The actions and conduct of the Defendants violated, and violates, the first, fourth and
fourteenth amendment rights of the named Plaintiffs in that said conduct constitutes unconstitutional
searches, seizures, detentions, arrests, malicious prosecution, excessive use of force, deprivations of
liberty and property without due process of law and denial of equal protection of the laws.
<p>     239. By reason of the aforementioned acts of Defendants, Plaintiffs were injured in their health,
strength and activity, sustained great mental pain, suffering and shock to their nervous system,
torment, anxiety, anguish, humiliation, and severe emotional distress, all to their damage in an amount
according to proof at trial. 
<p>     240. As a proximate result of the foregoing wrongful acts of Defendants, property belonging
to Plaintiffs was damaged and destroyed in an amount according to proof at trial.
<p>     241.      By reason of the aforementioned acts of Defendants, Plaintiffs were or will in the future
be required to receive hospital, medical, doctor, nursing, dental and psychological care and treatment,
and by reason thereof, will incur expenses related thereto in an amount according to proof at trial.
<p>     242. By reason of the aforementioned acts of Defendants, Plaintiffs were compelled to retain
legal counsel, at their own cost and expense, to defend criminal charges that were wrongfully filed
against them, in an amount according to proof at trial.
<p>     243. By reason of the aforementioned Defendants and each of them, Plaintiffs were unable to work,
and sustained and will in the future sustain, a loss and impairment of earnings in an amount according
to proof at trial.
<p>     244. Defendants' acts were done and committed by each Defendant knowingly, deliberately
and maliciously, with the intent to oppress, injure and harass Plaintiffs, and with reckless indifference
to the civil rights, personal security and safety of these Plaintiffs; and by reason thereof, Plaintiffs pray
for punitive and exemplary damages from and against the individual Defendants in an amount
according to proof at trial.
<p>     
<b>Second Cause of Action</b><br>
245.      The actions and conduct of the Defendants constitutes false arrest, false imprisonment,
malicious prosecution, defamation, slander, assault, battery, excessive use of force, cruel and unusual
punishment, deprivations of liberty and property without due process of law and denial of equal
protection of the laws, all in violation of the Pennsylvania Constitution and laws of the
Commonwealth of Pennsylvania.<p>     
246. By reason of the aforementioned acts of Defendants, Plaintiffs were injured in their health,
strength and activity, sustained great mental pain, suffering and shock to their nervous system,
torment, anxiety, anguish, humiliation, and severe emotional distress, all to their damage in an amount
according to proof at trial. <p>     
247. As a proximate result of the foregoing wrongful acts of Defendants, property belonging
to Plaintiffs was damaged and destroyed in an amount according to proof at trial.<p>     
248. By reason of the aforementioned acts of Defendants, Plaintiffs were or will in the future
be required to receive hospital, medical, doctor, nursing, dental and psychological care and treatment,
and by reason thereof, will incur expenses related thereto in an amount according to proof at trial.<p>     
249. By reason of the aforementioned acts of Defendants, Plaintiffs were compelled to retain
legal counsel, at their own cost and expense, to defend criminal charges that were wrongfully filed
against them, in an amount according to proof at trial.<p>     
250. By reason of the aforementioned Defendants conduct, Plaintiffs were unable to work,
and sustained and will in the future sustain a loss and impairment of earnings in an amount according
to proof at trial.<p>     
251. Defendants' acts were done and committed by each Defendant knowingly, deliberately
and maliciously, with the intent to oppress, injure and harass Plaintiffs, and with reckless indifference
to the civil rights, personal security and safety of these Plaintiffs; and by reason thereof, Plaintiffs pray
for punitive and exemplary damages from and against the individual Defendants in an amount
according to proof at trial.<p>     

<b>Third Cause of Action</b><br>
252. By authorizing and tolerating the policies, customs, and practices of stopping,
questioning, detaining, searching, physically abusing and wrongfully charging individuals in violation
of their federally secured rights, the conduct of the OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS themselves violates
the fourteenth amendment to the United States Constitution, and 42 U.S.C. 1983 and 2000d.
<p>     
<b>Relief</b><br>
     WHEREFORE, Plaintiffs and members of the class they seek to represent respectfully pray that the
Court will:
<p>     <blockquote>
     a.   Certify this case to proceed as a class action;<p>     
     b.   Issue a declaratory judgment that the actions, policies and practices described above cause and
in the past caused the deprivation of  rights guaranteed to the Plaintiffs and the Plaintiff class by
the fourth and fourteenth amendments to the United States Constitution, 42 U.S.C. 1983, 2000d,
and  by the Constitution and laws of the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania;<p>     
     c.   Preliminarily and permanently enjoin Defendants and all persons acting in concert with them
from stopping, questioning, detaining, searching and physically and mentally abusing individuals in
the absence of constitutionally sufficient grounds;<p>     
     d.   Preliminarily and permanently enjoin Defendants and all persons acting in concert with them
from stopping, questioning, detaining, searching, physically abusing or wrongfully
charging individuals because of their race or minority status;<p>     
     e.   Preliminarily and permanently enjoin Defendants and all persons acting in concert with them
from stopping, questioning, detaining, searching, physically abusing or wrongfully
charging individuals because of their protected first amendment activities or their race or minority
status; <p>     
     f.   Preliminarily and permanently enjoin Defendants and all persons acting in concert with them
from engaging in or abiding by a "Code of Silence" that intentionally and deliberately
ignores unlawful conduct by police officers.<p>     
     g.   Enjoin the OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS from accepting, acquiescing in or condoning the police
misconduct as hereinbefore described;<p>     
     h.   Enjoin the OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS from following policies, practices or procedures which
are intended to, and/or are known to have the effect of establishing, as accepted practice, the
police misconduct as hereinbefore described;<p>     
     I.   Enjoin OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS to take all necessary action to eliminate the "Code of
Silence" followed by the CITY OF PITTSBURGH police officers, including the implementation
of appropriate disciplinary measures against any officers who participate in the "Code of Silence" and
the establishment of appropriate procedures and protections to ensure that all police officers who
report misconduct are not subject to retribution.<p>     
     j.   Enjoin the OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS to initiate, adopt and otherwise implement procedures
and practices to eliminate and ensure the prevention of the police misconduct as
hereinbefore described, including but not limited to:<p>     <blockquote>
          1.   establishing effective procedures for the investigation of charges
               of police misconduct that at a minimum, are designed to
               determine the veracity of such charges, including the authority to
               make findings of fact and credibility determinations, to subpoena
               witnesses and the like;
<p>     
          2.   establish procedures that set forth clearly established penalties to
               be imposed against officers who have engaged in police
               misconduct, and which provide for appropriate disciplinary
               action, including, but not limited to, suspension and termination;
<p>     
          3.   establish procedures whereby police officers employed by the
               CITY OF PITTSBURGH are subject to regular written
               evaluations of their work performance;
<p>     
          4.   establish procedures whereby appropriate training and retraining
               is required or available to police officers who have engaged in
               misconduct or who are known or suspected to be incapable of
               performing their duties without violating the constitutionally
               protected rights of citizens;
<p>     
          5.   enjoin the OFFICIAL DEFENDANTS to otherwise establish
               effective policies and programs with respect to the training,
               supervision, discipline and promotion of officers within the 
               Pittsburgh Police Department designed to eliminate the
               unconstitutional practices hereinbefore described;
 </blockquote><p>     
     k.   Award the named Plaintiffs exemplary and punitive damages against the individual
 Defendants;
<p>     
     l.   Award reasonable costs and attorneys' fees pursuant to 42 U.S.C. 1988;
<p>          
     m.   Such other relief as is just and appropriate.
<p></blockquote>     
