<Center><H1>Civil Liberties NewsClips</h1>
<H2>January 17th, 1996</h2></center>
<brclear=all></h2>

<dl>
<dt>
<img src="http://www.aclu.org/graphics/redline.gif" width="100%">
<br>
<blockquote>
<img src="/graphics/leftbutton.gif">
<b>ACLU and Indian Law Center File Suit Questioning Montana Districts</b>
<blockquote><P>The ACLU and the Indian Law
Center have filed a federal lawsuit charging that Montana's legislative
districts dilute the voting power of the state's Indian population. The
lawsuit, filed on January 12, seeks a court order to block the primary and
general election in Montana this year unless new districts are drawn.  "One
in twenty Montanans are Americans Indians," said ACLU
attorney Laughlin McDonald, one of the leading voting rights
litigators in the nation.  "Yet, there was only one Indian in the
entire 150-member Montana legislature last year."
</blockquote>

<P>
<h5><i>[Source: The Washington Post - January 14, 1994]</h5></i>
<P>
 </blockquote>
<p>
<img src="http://www.aclu.org/graphics/redline.gif" width="100%">
<br>
<blockquote>
<img src="../graphics/leftbutton.gif">
<b>Mississippi Court of Appeals Upholds Ruling Student-Prayer Ban</b>
<blockquote><P> In an important case brought by the ACLU of Mississippi, the
Federal First Circuit Court of Appeals today upheld a preliminary injunction
barring enforcement of a Mississippi statute that authorized
"student-initiated" prayer in the public schools. ACLU Legal Director Steven
R. Shapiro called the decision "remarkable" because of its strong language.
The court, Shapiro said, said "the statute was not necessary to protect, and
the decision does not disrupt, the rights of students to 'pray silently or in
a non-disruptive manner whenever and wherever they want.'"

<P>
