<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">SUPREME COURT OF THE UNITED STATES                     
<BR>Argument Schedule for Cases Involving Civil Liberties Issues</H2>
<H5 ALIGN="CENTER">Full Argument Calendar available from
<A HREF="http://www.usscplus.com/news/argcal.htm">USSC+</A></H5>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER" CELLPADDING="2" CELLSPACING="0">
<TR>
<TD COLSPAN="2" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H4>Case</H4></TD>
<TD ALIGN="CENTER">
<H4>Civil Liberties Issue</H4></TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD ROWSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><FONT SIZE="+1">Monday, <BR>January 6</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><B>95-1441 <BR>BLESSING v. FREESTONE</B></P>         
</TD>
<TD>Can individual parents sue states that fail to pursue child support
payments under Title IV-D of the Social Security Act? At least some amici on the
government's side, have used the case to raise the far larger issue of whether
42 U.S.C. &#167;1983 -- the principal vehicle for litigating civil rights claims
in federal court -- can ever be used to challenge the violation of a federal
statute by state officials. (<A HREF="/court/blessing.html"><I>amicus</I>
brief</A>)</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><B>95-2031 <BR>YOUNG v. FORDICE</B></P></TD>
<TD>Should a dual registration scheme adopted by Mississippi after enactment of
the Federal &quot;motor voter&quot; law be subject to preclearance by the
Justice Department under Section 5 of the Voting Rights Act?  The ACLU is
co-counsel in this case.</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP"><FONT SIZE="+1">Tuesday, <BR>January 7</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><B>95-1717<BR> UNITED STATES v. LANIER</B></P>       </TD>
<TD>Can federal civil rights laws be used to criminally prosecute a state court
judge for sexual assault? (<A HREF="/court/lanier.html"><I>amicus</I> brief</A>)</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ROWSPAN="2"><FONT SIZE="+1">Wednesday, <BR>January 8</FONT></TD>
<TD>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><B>96-110<BR> WASHINGTON v. GLUCKSBERG</B></P></TD>
<TD ROWSPAN="2">Are state statutes banning &quot;physician-assisted suicide&quot;
in Washington and New York constitutional? (<A HREF="/court/quill.html"><I>amicus</I>
brief</A>)</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><B>95-1858<BR> VACCO v. QUILL</B></P></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP"><FONT SIZE="+1">Monday, <BR>January 13</FONT></TD>
<TD>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><B>95-1853<BR> CLINTON v. JONES</B></P> </TD>
<TD>Should the President have complete immunity from all civil litigation
during his term in office? (<A HREF="/court/jones.html"><I>amicus</I> brief</A>)</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP"><FONT SIZE="+1">Tuesday, <BR>January 14</FONT></TD>
<TD>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><B>96-126<BR> CHANDLER v. MILLER</B></P>       </TD>
<TD>Is a Georgia statute requiring candidates for political office to take a
drug test constitutional?   (<A HREF="/court/chandler.html"><I>amicus</I>
brief</A>)</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="+1">Wednesday, <BR>February 19</FONT></TD>
<TD>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><B>95-2074 <BR>CITY OF BOERNE v. FLORES</B></P></TD>
<TD>Is the Religious Freedom Restoration Act unconstitutional, either because
it goes beyond the power of Congress under the Fourteenth Amendment, or because
it violates the separation of church and state? (<A HREF="/court/boerne.html"><I>amicus</I>
brief</A>)</TD></TR>
