<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> ACLU News Wire -2/1/97 Virginia Senate Rejects
"Parental Rights" Amendment</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">

<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/newshdr.gif">

<P><TT>February 1, 1997: Virginia Senate Rejects
"Parental Rights" Amendment
</TT></P>

<P></P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/graphics/rbline.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<P><TT>RICHMOND -- An effort the amend the Virginia Constitution to recognize the &quotfundamental right&quot of parents to control their children's upbringing and education was narrowly defeated Wednesday by Senate Democrats, The Washington Post reports.</TT></P>

<P><TT>Opponents, led by the ACLU of Virginia, argued that schools could be paralyzed by lawsuits from parents who would have the power to veto everything from the curriculum to the dress code. </TT></P>

<P><TT>Dr. Robert Alley, a nationally recognized expert on religion, spoke out against the amendment at a public hearing last week of the Senate Committee on Privileges and Election.  </TT></P>

<P><TT>The amendment is &quotwrong-headed, unnecessary and destructive of domestic tranquility,&quot Dr. Alley told the Committee, according to a story in the Richmond Times-Dispatch.</TT></P>

<P><TT>Alley represented both the ACLU of Virginia and  Americans United for Separation of Church and State, and is a board member of both organizations.  His most recent book, Without A Prayer: Religious Expression in Public Schools, studies families who have taken a stand against formal religious expression in public schools.  </TT></P>

<P><TT>Alley said that  the ACLU was concerned that the inevitable result of the parental rights amendment would be to undermine the public school system and to allow parents who abuse their children a constitutional justification for such actions.</TT></P>

<P><TT>The proposed amendment to the Virginia constitution is just 17 words: &quotThe right of parents to direct the upbringing and education of their children is a fundamental right.&quot </TT></P>

<P><TT>Christian Conservatives have made the amendment one of their key political goals for the last two years. In its new agenda introduced earlier this week, the Christian Coalition once again called for a parental rights amendment to the constitution.  The amendment has been introduced in 28 legislatures but has not passed in any of them.</TT></P>

<P><TT>&quotDon't be fooled by the innocuous sound of this proposal,&quot said Kent Willis, executive director of the ACLU of Virginia.  &quotThe state has a responsibility to offer a public education system that is fair to all children, regardless of their race or religion.  Some parents in Virginia would like to turn back the public education clock, and this amendment could give them a legal basis for doing just that.&quot</TT></P>

<P><TT>Sen. Joseph V. Gartlan Jr. (D-Fairfax), who voted against the initiative, said the amendment would mean that a parent could sue a school system because it allowed students to wear only white shirts, not blue ones.</TT></P>

<P><TT>&quotIt is an absurd proposition,&quot Gartlan said, &quotbut that is where it lead us....It will throw into a tailspin our system of protecting children from abuse.&quot  </TT></P>

<P><TT>Supporters of the measure, which lost 21-19, vowed to raise the proposal again next year and to make it an issue in this fall's elections.
</TT></P>



</BLOCKQUOTE>




<P></P>
