<blockquote>
<img src="/graphics/courthdr.gif">

<Center><h1><i>COMPLAINT</i></h1>

<br>

<b>UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT<BR>
SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK</b>

<pre><P>                                            
           RAFAEL SENCION,              
Plaintiff,   
 
 v. 

RUDOLPH GIULIANI, Mayor of the City of  
New York; RUBEN FRANCO, Chair of the  
New York City Housing Authority; HENRY     
COIRA, Chief of Staff of the New York   
City Housing Authority; DAVID ZORNOW, 
Chair of the New York City Civilian     
Complaint Review Board; EUGENE LOPEZ,   
Executive Director of the New York City 
Civilian Complaint Review Board; and    
CITY OF NEW YORK,                       
   Defendants.     
                        
</pre>

<P>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%>
<blockquote>

<h3>                      PRELIMINARY STATEMENT</h3>
</center>
<P>
<pre>
      1.  Plaintiff Rafael Sencion brings this civil-rights action
to challenge the conduct of defendant officials of the City of
New York that has infringed and continues to infringe his free
speech rights.  In May 1995 the New York City Housing Authority
offered Mr. Sencion a job as a tenant organizer -- a position
with no policymaking responsibility -- after learning from press
reports that Mr. Sencion had volunteered to be laid off from his
job of eight years so that another worker who had a family to
support would not be laid off.  Shortly after accepting the job
offer, Mr. Sencion published an op-ed piece in New York Newsday
that criticized the mayor's budget cuts because of their impact
on critical social services.  The Housing Authority rescinded its
job offer the same day the op-ed piece appeared, with defendant
Coira telling Mr. Sencion that the job was rescinded because of
the critical nature of the op-ed piece.  Two weeks later Mayor
Giuliani stated, in response to a question about Mr. Sencion,
that the City was entitled to hire only those New Yorkers who
agreed with the Mayor's political agenda.  Six weeks later the
New York City Civilian Complaint Review Board offered Mr. Sencion
a job as an investigator, which also was a position with no
policymaking responsibility.  The defendants, however, never
permitted Mr. Sencion to report to work, and they finally
rescinded the offer on February 2, 1996.  The defendants' actions
violated and continue to violate Mr. Sencion's rights under the
First and Fourteenth Amendments to the United States
Constitution, and Article I, Section 8 of the Constitution of the
State of New York.

                       JURISDICTION AND VENUE


     2.  This Court has subject matter jurisdiction over the
federal claims pursuant to 28 U.S.C.    1331, 1343(3-4).  This
suit is authorized under 42 U.S.C.   1983.  Supplemental juris-
diction is asserted over claims arising under Article 1, section
8, of the Constitution of the State of New York pursuant to 28
U.S.C.   1367.

     3.  Venue is proper pursuant to 28 U.S.C.   1391(b) in that
plaintiff's claims arose in the Southern District of New York.

     4.  Jurisdiction to grant declaratory judgment is conferred
by 28 U.S.C.    2201, 2202.  Injunctive relief is authorized by
Rule 65 of the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure.  An award of
costs and attorneys fees is authorized pursuant to 42 U.S.C. 
  1988.



                             PARTIES



     5.  Plaintiff, Rafael Sencion, is a citizen of the United
States residing in New York, New York.

     6.  Defendant Rudolph Giuliani is, and at all times
pertinent to this action has been, the Mayor of the City of New
York, with an office address of City Hall, New York, N.Y. 10007. 
Mr. Giuliani is sued in his official capacity.

     7.  Defendant Ruben Franco is, and at all times pertinent to
this action has been, the Chair of the New York City Housing
Authority, with an office address of 250 Broadway, New York, New
York 10007.  Mr. Franco is sued in his official capacity.

     8.  Defendant Henry Coira is, and at all times pertinent to
this action has been, the Chief of Staff of the New York City
Housing Authority, with an office address of 250 Broadway, New
York, New York 10007.  Mr. Coira is sued in his official
capacity.

     9.  Defendant David Zornow is, and at all time pertinent to
this action has been, the Chair of the New York City Civilian
Complaint Review Board, with an office address of 40 Rector
Street, 2nd Floor, New York, New York 10006.  Mr. Zornow is sued
in his official capacity.

     10.  Defendant Eugene Lopez is the Executive Director of the
New York City Civilian Complaint Review Board, with an office
address of 40 Rector Street, 2nd Floor, New York, New York 10006. 
Mr. Lopez is sued in his official capacity.

     11.  Defendant City of New York is a municipality organized
pursuant to the laws of the State of New York.


                       FACTUAL ALLEGATIONS


     12.  As of November 1994 plaintiff Rafael Sencion was
employed as a tenant organizer with the West Side SRO Law
Project.  He had worked there for eight years and was paid an
annual salary of $33,000.

     13.  In the fall of 1994 the West Side SRO Law Project
experienced a significant decrease in funding provided to it by
the City of New York.  As a result, it announced that it would
have to lay off two of its tenant organizers.

     14.  At the time of the announced layoffs, the West Side SRO
Law Project also employed as a tenant organizer a Larry Wood, who
was married and had two young children.  Because Mr. Wood had
less seniority than Mr. Rafael, Mr. Wood was designated to be
laid off.

     15.  Because he was single and did not have any children to
support, Mr. Sencion volunteered to be the laid off instead of
Mr. Wood.  The West Side SRO Law Project accepted Mr. Sencion's
offer, and he was laid off on March 6, 1995.

     16.  In April 1995 Mr. Sencion was contacted by a reporter
for New York Newsday.  The reporter had learned of Mr. Sencion's
situation and interviewed him about the circumstances of the
layoff.

     17.  On Friday, May 12, 1995, New York Newsday published a
story about Mr. Sencion.  The cover of the newspaper showed a
picture of Mr. Sencion with Mr. Wood's family and included the
headline, "Saint Of the City" and the subheadline, "Bachelor
Sacrifices His Job So Family Man Can Keep His."

     18.  As a result of the New York Newsday story, many major
press organizations contacted and interviewed Mr. Sencion on the
day the article appeared.  These organizations included
television channels 1, 2, 4, 5, 7, 9, 11, 41, and 47; radio
stations 1010 WINS Radio and CBS Radio; and the Associated Press.

     19.  On Friday, May 12, 1995, Mr. Sencion received a call
from John Hamill, the press secretary of the New York City
Housing Authority (NYCHA).  Mr. Hamill told Mr. Sencion that
defendant Mayor Giuliani was concerned about his situation, and
Mr. Hamill invited Mr. Sencion to come to the agency for a job
interview.  Mr. Sencion agreed to come to an interview on Monday,
May 15.

     20.  On Saturday, May 13, 1995, New York Newsday published a
story reporting that NYCHA had contacted Mr. Sencion and
scheduled a job interview.  The story quoted Mr. Hamill as
saying, "This guy has a housing background.  We're the biggest
landlord in the United States.  It makes sense."

     21.  On Monday, May 15, 1995, Mr. Sencion was introduced to
Ruben Franco, the Chair of the NYCHA, and then met with Henry
Coira, the Chief of Staff of NYCHA.  At that meeting Mr. Coira
offered Mr. Sencion a job as a tenant organizer for NYCHA with an
annual salary of $35,000.  Mr. Sencion accepted the offer, and
Mr. Hamill then accompanied him to complete personnel paperwork
and to have a required physical examination.

     22.  The tenant-organizer position for which Mr. Sencion was
hired at the NYCHA was not a policymaking or confidential
position.

     23.  Though there had been considerable, sympathetic press
attention focusing on Mr. Sencion's situation following the first
story in New York Newsday, he was concerned that the press was
paying too little attention to what he considered to be the most
important part his story:  the fact that city budget cuts were
having devastating consequences for important social services
such as those provided by the West Side SRO Law Project.

     24.  Given these concerns, Mr. Sencion contacted New York
Newsday on or about May 16, 1995, and told them that he wished to
write an op-ed piece about his situation.  They informed him that
they would be interested in publishing such a piece.

     25.  As a courtesy to defendant Coira of the NYCHA, Mr.
Sencion called to inform him of his intention to submit an op-ed
piece to New York Newsday that would be critical of the city
budget.  In that conversation Mr. Coira told Mr. Sencion that he
should not report for work until after the piece appeared.  He
also warned Mr. Sencion that he risked losing his job if he
published an op-ed piece critical of the Mayor.

     26.  On Thursday, May 18, 1995, Mr. Sencion submitted his
piece to New York Newsday, which published an edited version of
it on Tuesday, May 23, 1995.  In the piece Mr. Sencion discussed
the impact of the city budget cuts and called on Mayor Giuliani
"to reconsider his proposed budget cuts and to do the right
thing: fully restore the budgets of the Law Project and other
community organizations that provide vital services, so that they
can hire adequate, competent staff people to serve New York City
residents in need."

     27.  On the day New York Newsday published the op-ed piece,
Mr. Sencion called Mr. Coira to find out when he could start to
work.  Mr. Coira informed him that the agency was rescinding its
job offer and was doing so because of the content of the op-ed
piece.

     28.  The views expressed by Mr. Sencion in his op-ed piece
were on matters of public concern and would not have disrupted
his ability to perform his duties as a tenant organizer for the
NYCHA.

     29.  On June 5, 1995, Mr. Sencion, at the invitation of El
Diario, attended a breakfast meeting for the Latino news media at
City Hall.  When a reporter in the audience asked the Mayor about
Mr. Sencion's situation, the Mayor stated that he was entitled to
hire only those persons who agreed with his political agenda.

     30.  In a June 6, 1996, editorial, El Diario reported,
"[W]hen our reporter Angela Aquino asked [Mayor Giuliani] about
his administration's ideological loyalty requirement, Giuliani
confirmed that indeed, the administration reserved the right to
hire only those New Yorkers that agree with his agenda."

     31.  In July 1995 Mr. Sencion was contacted by defendant
Hector Soto, Executive Director of the New York City Civilian
Complaint Review Board (CCRB).  Mr. Soto subsequently interviewed
Mr. Sencion and offered him a job as an investigator for the CCRB
at an annual salary of $27,000.  Mr. Sencion accepted the job.        
The investigator position for which Mr. Sencion was
hired at the CCRB was not a policymaking or confidential
position.

     32.  After accepting the job offer, Mr. Sencion completed
all the personnel paperwork that was given to him and was ready
to start work immediately.  He was told by a personnel officer
that he could not start work until his position was cleared by an
entity known as the Vacancy Control Board.

     33.  For the next several months Mr. Sencion repeatedly
spoke with the CCRB personnel officer to find out when he could
start his job at the CCRB.  She continued to tell him that she
had heard nothing from the Vacancy Control Board.

     34.  In December 1995 the CCRB personnel officer informed
Mr. Sencion that the Vacancy Control Board has rejected him
without explanation.  She informed Mr. Sencion that the CCRB
intended to appeal the decision.

     35.  In January 1996 the CCRB personnel officer informed Mr.
Sencion that the CCRB appeal had been rejected.

     36.   By letter dated February 2, 1996, Hector Soto notified
Mr. Sencion that a request for his hire had been submitted to
"the Vacancy Control Board of the Mayor's Office."  The letter
then stated that "[t]his request was subsequently denied by the
VCB, with no reason being given.  However, this decision has
since been appealed.  I regret to inform you that we do not
expect an approval for your hire."

     37.  Attached to the February 2, 1996, letter from Mr. Soto
was a handwritten note that stated in relevant part, "Dear
Rafael, I'm sorry.  Tried everything I could but VCB wouldn't
approve and now there's a freeze."  The note was signed with the
initials "HWS."

     38.  Defendant Eugene Lopez has succeeded Hector Soto as the
Executive Director of the CCRB.

     39.  The CCRB job offer was rescinded in further retaliation
for the views Mr. Sencion expressed in his May 1995 op-ed piece
in New York Newsday.

     40.  The views expressed by Mr. Sencion in his op-ed piece
were on matters of public concern and would not have disrupted
his ability to perform his duties as an investigator for the
CCRB.

     41.  Upon information and belief, the Vacancy Control Board
is controlled by the Office of the Mayor of New York and makes
decisions about the hiring of city employees based on factors
other than the employees' ability to perform their prospective
job duties and other than budget considerations.

     42.  Following NYCHA's rescission of its job offer to Mr.
Sencion, he continuously searched for employment until January
16, 1996, when he commenced employment with Citizen Advice Bureau
(a private, not-for-profit organization in the South Bronx) as a
tenant organizer with an annual salary of $20,000.  He continues
to be employed in that position at that salary.

     43.  As a result of the NYCHA's rescission of its job offer
in May 1995 and the actions of the CCRB, Mr. Sencion has suffered
from financial hardship.  He was unemployed from May 15, 1995,
until January 16, 1996.  During that time he exhausted the modest
savings he had and was forced to rely upon unemployment benefits.

     44.  In his current position with Citizen's Advice Bureau
Mr. Sencion's annual salary is significantly less than the
$35,000 and $27,000 salaries offered by NYCHA and the CCRB,
respectively.

     45.  Because of his substantial loss in salary, Mr. Sencion
can no longer afford to live in the apartment he shares with a
roommate and for which he pays a monthly rent of $572.  He is
actively searching for a less expensive apartment, but he has
been unable to find one.  He wants to remain in his current
apartment, where he has lived since September 1992.

     46.  Mr. Sencion now has no savings or other financial
resources.

     47.  As a result of the NYCHA's rescission of its job offer
in May 1995, Mr. Sencion has lost opportunities for promotions
and pay increases within his profession.

     48.  As was the case in May 1995, Mr. Sencion would like to
work for the NYCHA as a tenant organizer.

     49.  As was the case in July 1995, Mr. Sencion would like to
work as an investigator for the CCRB.

     50.  The defendants have adopted a policy and/or practice of
excluding Mr. Sencion from city employment for which he is
qualified in retaliation for the views he expressed in the May
1995 op-ed piece in New York Newsday.

     51.  The defendants' actions have been taken under color of
law.



                      FIRST CAUSE OF ACTION



     52.  The defendants' retaliatory rescission of the NYCHA job
offer to Mr. Sencion violates his right to freedom of speech as
guaranteed by the First and Fourteenth Amendments to the United
States Constitution, 42 U.S.C.   1983.



                      SECOND CAUSE OF ACTION



     53.  The defendants' retaliatory rescission of the NYCHA job
offer to Mr. Sencion violates his right to freedom of speech as
guaranteed by Article 1, section 8 of the New York State
Constitution.



                      THIRD CAUSE OF ACTION



     54.  The defendants' retaliatory rescission of the CCRB job
offer to Mr. Sencion violates his right to freedom of speech as
guaranteed by the First and Fourteenth Amendments to the United
States Constitution, 42 U.S.C.   1983.


                      FOURTH CAUSE OF ACTION


     55.  The defendants' retaliatory rescission of the CCRB job
offer to Mr. Sencion violates his right to freedom of speech as
guaranteed by Article 1, section 8 of the New York State
Constitution.




     WHEREFORE, the plaintiff requests that this Court:



(1)  Assume jurisdiction over this action;

(2)  Issue a preliminary and permanent injunction directing the
     defendants

     a)   to restore Mr. Sencion to the position as a tenant
           organizer at the New York City Housing Authority with
           all the benefits and privileges he would have enjoyed
           had he been employed starting on May 16, 1995, or, in
           the alternative, to restore Mr. Sencion to the position
           of investigator with the New York City Civilian
           Complaint Review Board with all the benefits and
           privileges he would have enjoyed had he been employed
           as of August 1995;

     b)   to cease interfering with Mr. Sencion's exercise of his
          right of free speech; and

     c)   to cease enforcing any practice or policy that
          interferes with Mr. Sencion's exercise of his right of
          free speech;

(3)  Enter a declaratory judgment declaring that the defendants
     have violated and continue to violate the plaintiff's rights
     under the First and Fourteenth Amendments to the
     Constitution of the United States, and Article I,   8 of the
     Constitution of the State of New York;

(4)  Award plaintiff compensatory and punitive damages against
     defendants;

(5)  Grant plaintiff costs and reasonable attorneys fees pursuant
     to 42 U.S.C.   1988; and

(6)  Grant such other and further relief as this Court deems just
     and proper.



Respectfully submitted,




                              NEW YORK CIVIL LIBERTIES UNION
                              FOUNDATION


                          By: ____________________________
                              STEVEN HYMAN (SH-2097)
                              JANET C. NESCHIS
                              Leavy, Rosensweig & Hyman
                              11 East 44th Street
                              New York, N.Y.  10017
                              (212) 983-0400


                              NORMAN SIEGEL (NS-6850)
                              CAROLYN H. PELLING
                              132 West 43rd Street
                              New York, New York 10036
                              (212) 382-0557

                              Attorneys for Plaintiff



Dated:    March 4, 1996
</blockquote>
