<HEAD>
<TITLE> ACLU News Wire -2/5/97 Free Bibles in WV Schools Causes Uproar </TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">

<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/newshdr.gif">

<P><TT>February 5, 1997: Free Bibles in WV Schools Causes Uproar 
</TT></P>

<P></P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/graphics/rbline.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<P><TT>BUCKHANNON, WV -- A stack of Bibles on a table in school here is ground zero in the latest legal battle over separation of church and state, according to the Associated Press.</TT></P>


<P><TT>The Bibles, which were donated by businesses to be provided free to schoolchildren in Buckhannon, are the subject of a federal case. Opponents say it could go all the way to the U.S. Supreme Court.</TT></P>


<P><TT>The giveaway is the work of the Rev. J. Edward McDaniels, a pastor of Christian Fellowship Church in Buckhannon and a health and physical education teacher at Buckhannon-Upshur High School.</TT></P>


<P><TT>According to a recent AP report, McDaniels recruited businesses to donate the books, then asked the Upshur County school board for permission to set up an unstaffed table providing free religious material. Students would be free to stop or pass on by.</TT></P>


<P><TT>But some parents objected, including Jeannie O'Holloran, a Quaker parent from Buckhannon. &quotReligion definitely should start at home, not in the schools,&quot she told the news service.</TT></P>


<P><TT>She and others turned to the American Civil Liberties Union affiliate in West Virginia. </TT></P>


<P><TT>&quotThey had businesses who donated Bibles and wanted to distribute them. And they had students who wanted them. Great. Put them together,&quot Hilary Chiz, director of the West Virginia Civil Liberties Union, told the AP.</TT></P>


<P><TT>&quotBut don't do it in the schools,&quot she added. &quotUse the churches. There are more churches than schools in Upshur County, anyway.&quot</TT></P>


<P><TT>Last September, a federal judge in Clarksburg, W.Va., ruled the Bibles could be given out on school property provided they were not forced on students. School officials had to post a disclaimer saying they didn't endorse the practice of religion.</TT></P>


<P><TT>It was the first time a federal court had upheld the distribution of Bibles in a public school during school hours.  Federal appeals courts in Indiana and New Jersey have ruled the practice unconstitutional in recent years.</TT></P>


<P><TT>The dispute pits two constitutional rights against each other: the right to practice religion and speak freely of it, and the mandatory separation of church and state. The case has been appealed by the ACLU to the Fourth Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals.</TT></P>


<P><TT>Mary Pat Peck, a taxpayer with no children in the schools, is a plaintiff in the case. A lector in a Roman Catholic church, she is deeply religious but equally committed to the separation of church and state.</TT></P>


<P><TT>&quotWe have plenty of evidence around the world about how disastrous it is when government does take a role in religion,&quot she told AP. &quotLook at the Middle East, Northern Ireland, Bosnia.&quot
</TT></P>



</BLOCKQUOTE>




<P></P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
