<TD></TD>
<TD><A HREF="/cgi-bin/aclu/store/as.pl?View=1&session=970213072055_93&page=book1.html&lastpage=">View Order</A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<HR>
<P><A NAME="1065"></A><IMG SRC="/graphics/as1065.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" BORDER="0"><B><I>Death
at Midnight: The Confession of an Executioner</I></B><BR><I>by Donald A.
Cabana</I><BR>(Northeastern University Press, 1996, 100pp.) Cloth.</P>
<P>An insider's view of capital punishment by a former warden at the
Mississippi State Penitentiary.  ACLU President Nadine Strossen says of this
book, &quot;Since Cabana can hardly be accused of being 'soft on crime,' his
narrative may touch those readers who are unmoved by abstract philosophical or
legal arguments.&quot;</P>
