<H1 ALIGN="CENTER"><I>ACLU GOOD READS</I></H1>
<H4 ALIGN="CENTER">Selected titles of interest, offered at discount prices to
ACLU members and supporters</H4>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><IMG SRC="/graphics/rbline.gif" WIDTH="80%"></P>
<H3><A NAME="1209"></A><IMG
SRC="/graphics/as1209.gif" ALIGN="RIGHT" BORDER="0"><I>Without a Prayer:
Religious Expression in Public Schools</I><BR><FONT SIZE="-1">by Robert S.
Alley</FONT></H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4>The first thorough examination of families contesting school-sanctioned
prayer and Bible reading since they were rendered unconstitutional &#150;
features ACLU clients.</H4>
<P>Over the past three decades there have been hundreds of overt violations and
dozens of federal court cases seeking to undermine the principle of church/state
separation established by the Supreme Court in the <I>Engel</I> and <I>Abington</I>
decisions. <I>Without a Prayer</I> brings together the experiences of parents
and children who are contesting school prayer and Bible study.</P>
<P>The author explores how terms like &quot;nonpreferentialism,&quot; &quot;toleration,&quot;
and &quot;accommodation&quot; have been craftily used to obscure what are in
fact blatant First Amendment violations &#150; and how in some cases the
controversies have led to violence. The accounts of ACLU clients Joann Bell and
Lucille McCord are featured, as are the ACLU's significant recent school prayer
cases:<I> Herdahl v. Pontotoc County School District</I> and<I> ACLU v. Black
Horse Pike Regional Board of Education.</I></P>
<P>As the author writes, &quot;For three decades now knowledge of the personal
suffering of dissenters and of the human rights violations associated with the
'school prayer' issue have been largely confined to court records. A major
purpose of relating the real-life situations that follow is to expose the

personal suffering inflicted upon some American citizens by others in the name
of prayer.&quot;</P>
<P>As our Congress prepares once again to consider a school-prayer
Constitutional Amendment, <I>Without a Prayer</I> is crucial reading.</P>
<P>Robert S. Alley is a professor emeritus of humanities at the University of
Richmond (Virginia) and the author of the books <I>The Supreme Court on Church
and State</I> and <I>School Prayer </I>as well as the editor of <I>James
Madison on Religious Liberty.</I></P>
<P><FONT SIZE="-1">277 pages, published by Prometheus Books, 1996. Hardcover.
ISBN #1-57392-097-5</FONT></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50%">
<P>List Price: $25.95; <B>Good Reads Price $17.75</B></P></TD>
<TD>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="/cgi-bin/aclu/store/as.pl?startpage=book1.html#1209">Order
this book from the ACLU Store</A></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="7092"></A><IMG SRC="/graphics/as7092.gif" ALIGN="RIGHT"><I>All
God's Children: The Bosket Family and the American Tradition of Violence</I><BR><FONT
SIZE="-1">by Fox Butterfield</FONT></H3>
<P></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4>This stunning book traces a heritage of violence and values, from the
pre-Revolutionary south to today's urban America.</H4>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;With fresh perspective the author connects a black juvenile killer
to a narrative of white and black violence spanning more than three hundred
years of American history. It is a story that will keep you on the edge of your
seat, but it will also leave you troubled and challenged.</I>&quot;</P>
<P ALIGN="LEFT">&#150; Henry Hampton, Executive Producer, <I>Eyes on the Prize</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Meet Willie Bosket: a celebrity by his fifteenth birthday, admittedly
responsible for two thousand crimes including 200 armed robberies and 25
stabbings. Called a &quot;mad dog killer&quot; by the city's mayor and &quot;the
baby faced killer&quot; by the media, he even has a law named after him: &quot;the
Willie Bosket Law&quot; which allows the state to try children as young as
thirteen as adults, and was the first such statute in our country. </P>
<P>Even behind bars, this young man whose IQ breaches the genius level is so
uncontrollable &#150; nearly stabbing to death a prison guard he didn't even
know &#150; that the state custom-built a super isolation chamber to contain
him. Was Willie Bosket merely following in the footsteps of his father, the only
person ever to earn a Ph.D. in prison? Or did his legacy reach even further back
into our nation's history?</P>
<P>Celebrated <I>New York Times</I> national correspondent Fox Butterfield
delves into Bosket's past and unearths a saga of one African American family,
from colonial days, through slavery, unfulfilled emancipations and lynchings, to
the present. The author reveals how the southern code of honor &#150; which
could easily induce one man to take another's life &#150; begat a code of
violence that was handily transferred from slave owners to their slaves, and
that manifests itself today in our urban ghettoes, where the demand for &quot;respect&quot;
can sometimes lead to deadly results. </P>
<P>Fox Butterfield is a national correspondent for <I>The New York Times</I>
and the author of <I>China: Alive in the Bitter Sea</I>, which won the National
Book Award. He was a member of the <I>Times</I> reporting team that won the
Pulitzer Prize for its publication of the Pentagon Papers, and has served as a
correspondent for the newspaper in several cities and in Asia, where he opened
the Beijing bureau in 1979.</P>
<P><FONT SIZE="-1">389 pages, published by Alfred A. Knopf Publishers, 1996.
Hardcover. ISBN #0-394-58286-1</FONT></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50%">
<P>List Price: $30.00; <B>Good Reads Price: $24.00</B></P></TD>
<TD>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="/cgi-bin/aclu/store/as.pl?startpage=book1.html#7092">Order
this book from the ACLU Store</A></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="1065"></A><IMG
SRC="/graphics/as1065.gif" ALIGN="RIGHT" BORDER="0"><I>Death at Midnight: The
Confession of an Executioner</I><BR><FONT SIZE="-1">by Donald A. Cabana</FONT></H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4>A courageous insider's view of capital punishment by a former prison warden
&#150; and the story of a transformation from executioner to abolitionist.</H4>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;Death at Midnight<I> is a compelling personal account of the
experiences that impel a lifelong corrections official and death penalty
supporter, to bear witness to the inevitable inhumanity and injustice of capital
punishment.&quot;</I></P>
<P ALIGN="LEFT">&#150; Nadine Strossen, President ACLU</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Donald Cabana relates his personal journey through our nation's prison
system and tells his tale of moral awakening. He recounts his twenty-five year
career in corrections, provides insight into prison life and describes in
compassionate detail the lives of a young black man on death row and also the
prison staff preparing to kill him. </P>
<P>The author explains his transformation: &quot;I spent most of my career as a
prison administrator convinced of the need for capital punishment.... Not until
I was confronted with supervising and carrying out the ultimate retribution did
I begin to question the process in earnest....  </P>
<P>&quot;But it was the execution of Connie Ray Evans that became, for me, a
personal moment of truth.... That a young black man, who had no choice but to
die in a gas chamber, and a middle-aged white man, the warden who had no choice
but to carry the execution to its conclusion, could have come to regard each
other as friends is an achievement that is surely cause for joy and celebration.&quot;</P>
<P>This is a riveting personal account of the awakening of an abolitionist &#150;
and one who is well-placed to know how truly awful the death penalty is.</P>
<P>Donald A. Cabana worked in the criminal justice system for twenty-five
years: as a prison administrator at the Massachusetts Correctional Institution

in Bridgewater, the Mississippi State Penitentiary in Parchman, the Alachua
County Department of Corrections in Gainesville, Florida, and the Missouri State
Penitentiary in Jefferson City. He now teaches criminal justice at the
University of Southern Mississippi.</P>
<P><FONT SIZE="-1">200 pages, published by Northeastern University Press,
1996. Hardcover. ISBN #1-55553-264-0</FONT></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50%">
<P>List Price: $24.95; <B>Good Reads Price: $20.00</B></P></TD>
<TD>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="/cgi-bin/aclu/store/as.pl?startpage=book1.html#1065">Order
this book from the ACLU Store</A></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="7042"></A><IMG SRC="/graphics/as7042.gif" ALIGN="RIGHT"><I>The
Voices of AIDS: Twelve Unforgettable People Talk About How AIDS Has Changed
Their Lives</I><BR><FONT SIZE="-1">by Michael Thomas Ford</FONT></H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4>A book for young adults revealing the human side of the AIDS epidemic.</H4>
<P>A young woman leads protest marches in memory of the friends she has lost. 
Another young woman, living with AIDS, runs an AIDS organization. A young man
uses pop music to spread the message of AIDS education.A mother speaks about her
daughter who died from the disease; another mother is living with the disease
itself.</P>
<P>These are a few of the dozen inspirational and informative stories in <I>The
Voices of AIDS, </I>a book which also includes basic information about the
disease, a resource guide with more information about AIDS and HIV, and contact
addresses for the twelve people who share their stories.</P>
<P>As the author writes, &quot;Some of these people are infected with HIV; some
of them are not. Some may be just like you. Others may be very different. But
even if they have nothing in common with you, I hope that you will listen to
what they have to say.&quot;</P>
<P>Michael Thomas Ford works as an AIDS educator and has written books for
young readers and adults, including <I>100 Questions and Answers about AIDS</I>
and<I> What You Need to Know Now</I>, which was selected as an American Library
Association Best Book for Young Adults.</P>
<P><FONT SIZE="-1">225 pages, published by Morrow Junior Books, 1995.
Hardcover. ISBN #0-688-05322-X</FONT></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50%">
<P>List Price: $15.00; <B>Good Reads Price: $9.00</B></P></TD>
<TD>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="/cgi-bin/aclu/store/as.pl?startpage=book1.html#7042">Order
this book from the ACLU Store</A></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="1205"></A><IMG SRC="/graphics/as1205.gif" ALIGN="RIGHT"><I>The
Right to Privacy</I><BR><FONT SIZE="-1">by Ellen Alderman and Caroline Kennedy</FONT></H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4>What is privacy; how well are we protected; and what exactly are we
protected from?</H4>
<P>Although the word &quot;privacy&quot; does not appear in the United States
Constitution, most Americans believe their right to it is not just legally
protected but fundamental to their lives, their way of living and this country's
democratic system. It's considered one of our most basic and coveted rights. Yet
privacy is one of the most vulnerable rights in our society.</P>
<P>Through the analysis of landmark cases, lesser-known but equally important
trial decisions and dozens of anecdotal narratives, the authors translate the
law into relevant human experience. They demonstrate how whether an individual

has a recognized right to privacy largely depends on the type of &quot;privacy&quot;
in question. </P>
<P><I>The Right to Privacy</I> covers six general areas:</P>
<UL>
<LI> Privacy versus Law Enforcement
</LI>
<LI> Privacy and Your Self
</LI>
<LI> Privacy versus The Press 
</LI>
<LI> Privacy versus The Voyeur
</LI>
<LI> Privacy in the Workplace
</LI>
<LI> Privacy and Information including Cyberspace
</LI></UL>
<P>The authors explain, &quot;we wrote this book to explore why people believe
so strongly in the right to privacy, and what the legal system does to protect
it.... We came to the subject with very different experiences, though with
similar legal training as attorneys., One of us is a public figure who grew up
with little privacy. The other is like the people in this book who, until
recently, had taken the right to privacy for granted.... We began our research

with the same gut reaction that most people have: there is less privacy than
there used to be. As we immersed ourselves further in the topic... we concluded
that things were worse than we originally thought.&quot;</P>
<P>Ellen Alderman and Caroline Kennedy are attorneys who met at the Columbia
University School of Law. They are co-authors of the best-selling book <I>In
Our Defense</I>, a highly-acclaimed layperson's guide to the Bill of Rights.</P>
<P><FONT SIZE="-1">405 pages, published by Alfred A. Knopf Publishers, 1995.
Hardcover. ISBN #0-679-41986-1</FONT></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50%">
<P>List Price: $26.95; <B>Good Reads Price: $18.50</B><BR><BR>Paperback
edition available in March</P></TD>
<TD>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="/cgi-bin/aclu/store/as.pl?startpage=book1.html#1205">Order
this book from the ACLU Store</A></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="1126"></A><A><IMG SRC="/graphics/as1126.gif" ALIGN="RIGHT"></A><I>Antidiscrimination
Law and Social Equality</I><BR><FONT SIZE="-1">by Andrew Koppelman</FONT></H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4>An important look at how the legal system attempts to function within a
discriminatory society.</H4>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>This is the best guide to the philosophical and constitutional questions
raised by the culture wars. Koppelman's clarity and insight set a new standard
for the debate.</I></P>
<P ALIGN="LEFT">&#150; Bruce Ackerman, Sterling Professor of Law and Political
Science, Yale University</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>What are the moral principles that should guide a free society? Can a
liberal state allow its lawmakers to penalize hate speech and pornography, or to
combat discrimination against blacks, women, gays and lesbians, and others
without shaping citizens' beliefs by force?</P>
<P>&quot;Part of what defines a free society is that it is none of the
government's business what citizens believe and that the shaping of citizens'
beliefs is not a legitimate task of a liberal state,&quot; the author writes in
the Introduction. &quot;Racism, sexism and similar ideologies are so evil and
destructive of the proper workings of a free society that the state should do
whatever it can to eradicate them.</P>
<P>&quot;The two propositions are, of course, contradictory, and ever since the
Civil War, antidiscrimination law has attempted to devise some accommodation
between them.&quot;</P>
<P>The author, an assistant professor of politics at Princeton University,
provides a thorough analysis of how the legal system can begin closing the gap
between these two disparate precepts.<I> Antdiscrimination Law and Social
Equality</I> was selcted for the American Political Science Association's Edward
S. Corwin Award.</P>
<P><FONT SIZE="-1">276 pages, published by Yale University Press, 1996.
Hardcover. ISBN #0-300-06482-9</FONT></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50%">
<P>List Price: $32.50; <B>Good Reads Price: $18.50</B></P></TD>
<TD>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="/cgi-bin/aclu/store/as.pl?startpage=book1.html#1126">Order
this book from the ACLU Store</A></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="7094"></A><IMG SRC="/graphics/as7094.gif" ALIGN="RIGHT"><I>Shades
of Freedom: Racial Politics and Presumptions of the American Legal Process</I><BR><FONT
SIZE="-1">by A. Leon Higginbotham, Jr.</FONT></H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4>Ranging from the earliest colonial times to the present, <I>Shades of
Freedom</I> is a superb work of history &#150; and a mirror to the American soul
&#150; by a noted scholar and celebrated jurist.</H4>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;Written with the eloquence of a Martin Luther King, the
scholarship of a W.E.B. Du Bois, and the superb legal craftsmanship and wisdom
of Chief Justice Warren and Thurgood Marshall.&quot;</I></P>
<P ALIGN="LEFT">&#150; Kweisi Mfume, President &amp; CEO, NAACP</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Instead of guaranteeing equal justice under the law, the judicial system has
more often than not played the opposite role: enforcing the inferior position of
African Americans.  Higginbotham analyzes how white perceptions of black
inferiority slowly became codified into law &#150; and persist to this day.</P>
<P>From colonial precepts of religion and racial inferiority to <I>Dred Scott</I>,
Uncle Tom, the Civil War, Reconstruction, <I>Plessy v. Ferguson, </I>courthouse
apartheid, civil rights, Voting Rights and the Contract With America, the author
examines how racial bias has permeated both the American legal system and the
American consciousness. Do we still operate under a system of total racial
oppression, or have we acceded to &quot;shades of freedom&quot;?</P>
<P>This seminal work is the long-awaited sequel to Higginbotham's 1978 book
<I>In the Matter of Color.</I></P>
<P>A. Leon Higginbotham is Public Service Professor of Jurisprudence at the
John F. Kennedy School of Government, Harvard University, and of Counsel to
Paul, Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton and Garrison. He was formerly Chief Judge of the
United States Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit. A recipient of the

Presidential Medal of Freedom, he has taught at Yale, Harvard, New York
University, and University of Pennsylvania Law Schools. His landmark volume <I>In
the Matter of Color</I> won the highest award given by the American Bar
Association, the Silver Gavel Award, as well as the National Bar Association's
Literary Award and numerous other national and international awards.</P>
<P><FONT SIZE="-1">304 pages, published by Oxford University Press, 1996.
Hardcover. ISBN #0-19-503822-3</FONT></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50%">
<P>List Price: $30.00; <B>ACLU Good Reads Price: $24.00</B></P></TD>
<TD>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="/cgi-bin/aclu/store/as.pl?startpage=book1.html#7094">Order
this book from the ACLU Store</A></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="1127"></A><IMG
SRC="/graphics/as1127.gif" ALIGN="RIGHT" BORDER="0"><I>Tragic Failure: Racial
Integration in America</I><BR><FONT SIZE="-1">by Tom Wicker</FONT></H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>A consideration of race relations in America by a former <I>New York Times</I>
political columnist and one of the nation's most respected observers of
contemporary society.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;This provocative book offers a bold political proposal to achieve
racial reconciliation. </I>Tragic Failure<I> should be read and debated by all
Americans who still believe that a real democracy can overcome racial prejudice.&quot;</I></P>
<P ALIGN="LEFT">&#150; William Julius Wilson, Professor of Sociology and Public
Policy, University of Chicago, <BR>and author of <I>When Work Disappears: The
World of the New Urban Poor.</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Racial integration in America has failed. Today, under the crush of a white
backlash, race has become our nation's &quot;dirty little secret&quot; &#150; a
subtext for all political debate, from affirmative action to poverty, crime,
unemployment and welfare. </P>
<P>&quot;Neither civil war in the nineteenth century nor the civil rights
movement in the twentieth has brought racial equality, much less racial amity,
to America,&quot; the author writes in the introduction He goes on to analyze
why America's ability to create racial equality is a tragic failure of national
proportions &#150; and one that demands new answers to old questions.</P>
<P>Through twenty-five years as political columnist for <I>The New York Times,</I>
Tom Wicker has been a keen eyewitness to the significant events of the last
three decades, from the passage of the Civil Rights Act to the Million Man
March. He is the author of nine novels and five books of nonfiction.</P>
<P><FONT SIZE="-1">218 pages, published by William Morrow, 1996. Hardcover.
ISBN: 0-688-10629-3</FONT></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50%">
<P>List Price: $25.00; <B>ACLU Good Reads Price $17.00</B></P></TD>
<TD>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="/cgi-bin/aclu/store/as.pl?startpage=book1.html#1127">Order
this book from the ACLU Store</A></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
