<HEAD>
<TITLE> ACLU News Wire -2/3/97 ABA Calls for End to Death Penalty</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">

<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/newshdr.gif">

<P><TT>February 3, 1997: ABA Calls for End to Death Penalty
</TT></P>

<P></P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/graphics/rbline.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<P><TT>SAN ANTONIO -- The American Bar Association today called for a halt to executions of prison inmates until the U.S. government and states that impose the death penalty alter the current system, Reuters reports.</TT></P>

<P><TT>Delegates at the ABA's convention in San Antonio today approved a resolution saying the death penalty unfairly discriminates against minorities. The resolution, the wire service said, reflects increased concern in the legal community that Congress and the states have limited death row appeals. Congress last year eliminated all federal funding of death row appeals. Several states have restricted the appeals process to shorten stays on death row. </TT></P>

The American Civil Liberties Union, which opposes the death penalty, applauded the announcement. </TT></P>

<P><TT>&quotThe ABA's resolution confirms our nation's growing crisis of confidence in America's criminal justice system,&quot said Diann Rust-Tierney, director of the ACLU's Capital Punishment Project.</TT></P>

<P><TT>&quotIt is certainly significant that nation's largest legal organization, which does not take a position on the death penalty, is now calling for an end to the imposition of the death sentence until it can be administered fairly and impartially,&quot she added. </TT></P>

<P><TT>Reuter said that a report by the 370,000-lawyer national organization seeks:</TT></P>
<ul>
<li><tt>Competent counsel for all capital defendants.</tt></li>
<li><tt>Federal court review of state cases.</tt></li>
<li><tt>An effort to end racial bias in capital sentencing.</tt></li>
<li><tt>A ban on executions of mentally retarded defendants and those under 18.</tt></li>
</ul>

<P><TT>Rust-Tierney added that recent action by Congress to defund capital defenders' offices, as well as the passage last year of a law severely restricting federal court review of capital cases, &quotcreated a situation in which fundamental due process is systematically lacking.&quot </TT></P>

<P><TT>The ACLU vigorously opposed both initiatives, Rust-Tierney said, and has also worked to end race discrimination in the administration of death penalty cases.</TT></P>

<P><TT>In a related story, the Washington Post today reports that, given the choice, Virginia juries vote for life imprisonment in murder cases where parole is not an option.</TT></P>

<P><TT>The Post recounts the story of a 1995 murder trial in which a Virginia County Attorney was confident that she would win a conviction and a death sentence.  But the jury chose life in prison without parole.</TT></P>

<P><TT>More and more juries are doing the same thing, according to the Post: The number of people given the death sentence in Virginia has plummeted since the state began allowing jurors to sentence murderers to life without parole two years ago.</TT></P>

<P><TT>Last year, when Virginia executed eight murderers, more than any other state, there was only one new admission to death row.  </TT></P>

<P><TT>Similar declines also have occurred in Georgia and Indiana, two other states that have introduced life without parole in recent years.  And in Maryland, where life without parole has been a long-standing option, judges and juries show a clear preference for it, over both death and life with the possibility of parole, the Post said.</TT></P>

<P><TT>According to a poll conducted by the Death Penalty Information Center, which opposes capital punishment, support for the death penalty nationwide falls from 77 percent to 41 percent if the alternative is life without parole accompanied by restititution.</TT></P>

<P><TT>&quotJuries in Virginia and elsewhere are clearly uneasy about our system of justice and eager for an alternative to the sentence of death,&quot the ACLU's Rust-Tierney said.  &quotThe ABA's announcement today further reinforces the fact that what the public wants is a safe and just society.&quot
</TT></P>



</BLOCKQUOTE>




