<HEAD>
<TITLE> ACLU News Wire -2/6/97 Vermont Schools to Provide Equal Education </TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">

<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/newshdr.gif">

<P><TT>February 6, 1997: Vermont Schools to Provide Equal Education
</TT></P>

<P></P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/graphics/rbline.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<P><TT>MONTPELIER, VT -- The highest court in Vermont has ruled that the state's reliance on local property taxes to finance public education is unconstitutional and &quotdeprives children of an equal educational opportunity,&quot the Associated Press reports.</TT></P>

<P><TT>In its 5-0 decision, the Vermont Supreme Court said the state Legislature needs to come up with a more equitable way to pay for schools.</TT></P>

<P><TT>The American Civil Liberties Union had sued the state on behalf of 13 schoolchildren, taxpayers and school districts.</TT></P>

<P><TT>ACLU cooperating attorney Robert Gensburg characterized the ruling as a victory that is &quot&quottotal, unequivocal, and complete.&quot</TT></P>

<P><TT>&quotWe are simply unable to fathom a legitimate governmental purpose to justify the gross ineqities in educational opportunities evident from the record,&quot the Justices wrote, adding that &quotit requires no particular constitutional expertise to recognize the capriciousness of such a system.&quot  </TT></P>

<P><TT>According to the Associated Press, the lawsuit claimed that the wide disparity in local property taxes among cities and towns violated that the state Constitution's guarantee to provide every student in the state with equitable educational opportunities.</TT></P>

<P><TT>Vermont lawmakers, like their counterparts in states across the country, have tried for years to reform educational funding to rely less on property taxes. Courts also have tried to even out wide inequities in funding.</TT></P>

<P><TT>&quotThose cases have been brought in more than 30 states over the years,&quot Louis Bograd, a senior staff attorney with the ACLU's Washington office, told the Associated Press. &quotThey've probably been successful more often than not.&quot</TT></P>

<P><TT>By and large, those cases have succeeded in the past two decades in reducing some of the inequities, according to Bograd. &quotThere's definitely been an increase in equity over the last 20 years,&quot he told the AP. &quotYou see fewer and fewer states with the kind of harsh inequities that we saw back in the early '70s.&quot</TT></P>

<P><TT>The decision of the Vermont Supreme Court can be found at <a href="http://dol.state.vt.us/GOPHER_ROOT3/000000/SUPCT/A-E/BRIGHAM_V_STATE.96-502">http://dol.state.vt.us/GOPHER_ROOT3/000000/SUPCT/A-E/BRIGHAM_V_STATE.96-502</a>
</TT></P>



</BLOCKQUOTE>




