<HEAD>
<TITLE> ACLU News Wire -2/5/97 WI Big Brother in Blue to Patrol NYC </TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">

<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/newshdr.gif">

<P><TT>February 5, 1997: Big Brother in Blue to Patrol NYC 
</TT></P>

<P></P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/graphics/rbline.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<P><TT>NEW YORK -- After four years of steep drops in crime, the New York City Police Department has outlined plans to install new video surveillance cameras in some housing projects and subway stations, the New York Times reports.</TT></P>

<P><TT>The proposal brought a swift objection from the New York Civil Liberties Union, which said that even though cameras would be mounted in public spaces, they would give authorities unusual power to pry into New Yorker's private lives.</TT></P>

<P><TT>&quotThe plan is invasive and raises the Orwellian specter of Big Brother government spying on its residents, and compiling a video record of the free movement of individuals as they make their way about the city,&quot Norman Siegel, NYCLU Executive Director, told the Times.</TT></P>

<P><TT>Cameras were tried once before in New York in 1973 when the Police Department installed them in Times Square.  But the plan was abandoned after 22 months and only 10 arrests.</TT></P>

<P><TT>Cities around the country have experimented with video surveillance cameras with mixed crime-fighting results. Some cities have unplugged their cameras, amid protests from civil libertarians and lack of proof that they help to reduce crimes, according to the Times. </TT></P>

<P><TT>On the nation's more ambitious video surveillance programs began in January 1996 in Baltimore, where sixteen cameras are trained in the heart of the city's downtown area.  </TT></P>

<P><TT>Although the city police department have reported a crime drop in those areas, mirroring the nation's overall decline, some worry that the cameras may be altering people's behavior as they walk down the street.</TT></P>

<P><TT>&quotThere may very well have been lovers who did not steal a kiss or pedestrians who did not scratch a place that needed to be scratched, but it is hard to measure these things,&quot Susan Goering, the Executive Director of the ACLU of Maryland, told the Times.
</TT></P>



</BLOCKQUOTE>




<P></P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A></CENTER>
<CENTER>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
