<HEAD>
<TITLE> ACLU News Wire -2/5/97 WI Case Stirs Fears of Pregnancy Police </TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">

<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/newshdr.gif">

<P><TT>February 5, 1997: WI Case Stirs Fears of Pregnancy Police 
</TT></P>

<P></P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/graphics/rbline.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<P><TT>WAUKESHA, WI -- A prickly fetal rights case in this Milwaukee suburb has led anti-choice advocates to quote from Roe v. Wade and pro-choice groups to warn of a pregnancy police.</TT></P>

<P><TT>In the next few months, the Los Angeles Times reports, the Wisconsin Supreme Court is expected to decide whether county officials acted legally when they took custody of an fetus a month before its due date.</TT></P>

<P><TT>According to a local social services agency, the mother-to-be, Angela M.W., was using cocaine and poisoning the developing fetus. The 24-year-old was not charged with any crime or put under arrest.  Instead, her doctors went behind her back and convinced a judge to confine her to a drug treatment program until she gave birth.</TT></P>

<P><TT>As the Supreme Court decided 24 years ago in Roe, women have a constitutional right to choose abortion.  But as the fetus grows, the Court ruled, the state's interest in the pregnancy grows as well.</TT></P>

<P><TT>Now, the Times reports, some anti-abortion groups are arguing that Roe requires the state to intervene on behalf of a fetus if the mother is engaging in potentially dangerous behavior.</TT></P>

<P><TT>This interpretation has pro-choice and public health groups concerned that this would result in a kind of pregnancy police, allowing the state to oversee an expectant's mother's way of life.</TT></P>

<P><TT>&quotIf the lower court's misinterpretation of Roe v. Wade is upheld, pregnant women who smoke, or live with a smoker, or maintain a poor diet, or fail to take medications could be subjected to an order of protective custody to ensure they change their behavior and provide 'a safe environment in the womb' for the fetus,&quot according to a brief filed by a number of pro-choice groups.</TT></P>

<P><TT>Sara Mandelbaum, a lawyer with the ACLU's Women's Rights Project, who is handling the case's appeal, warned that the threat of losing her liberty could keep pregnant woman from seeking prenatal care.</TT></P>

<P><TT>&quotWhich is a greater danger to the fetus,&quot Mandelbaum asked, &quota cocaine user who sees her doctor regularly, or one who avoids physicians out of fear of detention?&quot
</TT></P>



</BLOCKQUOTE>




<P></P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A></CENTER>
<CENTER>
