<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//SQ//DTD HTML 2.0 HoTMetaL + extensions//EN">
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>04/30/96: &quot;School Prayer&quot; Constitutional
Amendments</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/legishdr.gif">
<P></P>
<P>April 30, 1996</P>
<P>To: Interested Persons<BR>Fr:  Daniel E. Katz<BR><B>Re: The &quot;school
prayer&quot; constitutional amendments   An update and talking points against
them</B></P>
<P>
 In late 1995 two different constitutional amendments to the religion clauses of
the First Amendment were introduced in the House of Representatives.  Rep.
Ernest Jim Istook (R-OK) introduced the Religious Liberties Amendment, H.J. Res.
127, and Rep. Henry Hyde (R-IL) introduced the Religious Equality Amendment,
H.J. Res. 121.  In the Senate, Orrin Hatch has introduced an amendment, S.J.
Res. 45, identical to Rep. Hyde's Religious Equality Amendment.</P>
<P>
 In the past few months there has not been much activity surrounding these
constitutional amendments, which were both designed to overturn the religion
clauses of the First Amendment.  This inactivity is most likely the result of
reported negotiations between Reps. Hyde and Istook aimed at developing a single
constitutional amendment.  In the end, it is most likely that this singular
proposal will more closely resemble Rep. Hyde's Religious Equality Amendment
than Rep. Istook's amendment.</P>
<P>
 In a presidential election year, both parties will take up symbolic issues. A
compromise amendment could be put on a fast track because of the desire of the
parties to attract core constituencies (in this case the Christian Coalition,
Traditional Values Coalition, etc.)  The ACLU and other groups in the Coalition
to Preserve Religious Liberty (which includes civil liberties, educational and
religious organizations) strongly oppose both of the proposed constitutional
amendments.  The First Amendment is our nation's &quot;First Freedom&quot; and
should not be overturned by false claims that religion is &quot;under attack&quot;
in our country.   In fact, religion is thriving in this country at a rate that
exceeds any other western industrialized nation.</P>
<P>

<B>The Hyde &quot;Religious Equality&quot; Approach is about Money -- Not
Prayer</B></P>
<P>
 Unlike Rep. Istook's proposal, which focuses primarily on the issue of prayer
in school, the Hyde &quot;Religious Equality&quot; approach seeks to authorize
widespread government funding of religious institutions, including houses of
worship.  Under the &quot;Religious Equality&quot; proposal, the government
could decide to subsidize the religious mission of certain churches, synagogues
or mosques.</P>
<P>
 Currently, the Constitution prohibits the use of taxpayer funds for such
purposes; the Founders knew full well of the dangers of allowing the government
to promote selected religions over others.  Therefore, the Establishment Clause
of the First Amendment prevents the government from advancing religious faiths
or entangling the government in the affairs of religious institutions. These
constitutional safeguards provide religion with a great degree of autonomy from
the influences of government.  This autonomous status has allowed religion to
flourish in our nation. The &quot;Religious Equality&quot; approach would
overrule this fundamental provision of the Bill of Rights.</P>
<P>
 The Hyde proposal contains language that might appear innocuous at first
glance, but would devastate the First Amendment and longtime American principles
if it were passed and ratified.  The &quot;Religious Equality&quot; amendment
would prohibit the Federal government or the states from engaging in &quot;discrimination&quot;
against individuals or groups based on their religious identity.  However, as
explained above, religion enjoys a special autonomous status under the
Constitution, and accordingly, religious institutions are treated differently
from secular institutions out of respect for religion's separation from
government.</P>
<P>
 For example, government is not permitted to excessively entangle itself in the
affairs of religious institutions.  This constitutional principle protects
religion from undue interference or coercion by the government.  These same
principles dictate that the government should not use its &quot;power of the
purse&quot; to favor certain religions over others.  Thus, the Constitution
prohibits the government from funding sectarian institutions in order to further
a particular religious mission. </P>
<P>
 The &quot;Religious Equality&quot; approach would remove religion's special
status under the Constitution and inject the influence of government funds into
our nation's houses of worship.  Of course, the government money will come with
the standard government oversight and restrictions.  Current constitutional
standards prohibiting &quot;excessive entanglement&quot; between church and
state would be overridden, allowing the government to directly regulate the
activity of religious institutions.  Religious groups will then be forced to
behave like government agencies, battling each other for scarce government
funds.  It is also very like that under &quot;Religious Equality,&quot; some
religious groups might change their religious beliefs to make themselves more
palatable to government officials for funding.</P>
<P>
 Additionally, many taxpayers will be offended when they learn that their money
is being used to directly advance religious beliefs with which they disagree
with.  The government should not be allowed, much less required, to use our tax
money to promote religious activities, whether sponsored by Baptists, Jews,
Mormons, Branch Davidians, Buddhists, Catholics or the Nation of Islam.</P>
<P>
 Under &quot;Religious Equality,&quot; a government body could completely hand
over taxpayer-funded social services to a single religious institution. 
Beneficiaries of assistance, in order to receive social services, could be
required to go to a house of worship that would violate their religious
conscience.  Many beneficiaries may choose to forego their benefits altogether
rather than report to an unfamiliar religious institution.  For example, the
state of Pennsylvania could contract with the Archdiocese of Philadelphia to
take over all taxpayer-funded welfare and substance abuse social service
programs in the eastern part of the state.  A beneficiary who is Methodist would
have no choice but to report to a Catholic church for government benefits.  This
is not &quot;Religious Equality,&quot; but rather &quot;Religious Inequality&quot;
for the beneficiary.  (Even if a constitutional amendment does not move in this
Congress, a full scale statutory effort to divert taxpayer funds to houses of
worship is currently under way. See ACLU Interested Persons Memorandum,
Constitutional and Policy Problems with Senator Ashcroft's &quot;Charitable
Choice&quot; Provisions, March 11, 1996.)</P>
<P>
 Such a drastic change to our Constitution is highly unnecessary, as current law
permits a great deal of government funding to religious organizations (indeed,
the ACLU believes that current law improperly tolerates the funding of religious
organizations that should not receive such taxpayer funds under the First
Amendment.)   For example,  religious-affiliated groups, such as Catholic
Charities, receive government aid to perform social services.  However, these
religiously-affiliated nonprofit organizations can only use the government funds
for secular purposes, and cannot use the funds to proselytize or discriminate on
the basis of religion.</P>
<P>
 Additionally, many scholars have noted that the &quot;Religious Equality&quot;
proposal would open the door to school vouchers for redemption at private
parochial schools.  However, the Hyde approach would allow much more than that
-- it would allow the government to directly fund a parochial school's entire
budget -- without even the pretense of vouchers.</P>
<P><B>
 Conclusion</B></P>
<P>
 If any constitutional amendment moves during the remainder of 104th Congress,
it will most likely be a &quot;Religious Equality&quot; amendment that will
focus primarily on government funding of religious institutions.  It is also
possible that the compromise amendment would also reference public school
prayer.  Such an amendment will throw off the delicate balance between religion
and government constructed by the Founders of our great nation.  If enacted, the
amendment would corrupt religion, offend the religious rights of taxpayers, and
destroy the constitutional foundation our nation and houses of worship were
built upon.</P>
<P>
</P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A><P>
    
