<html><head><title>
Judiciary Committee Markup of Crime Proposals
</title>
<!JM 1/4/96>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<body><blockquote><img src="/graphics/legishdr.gif">
<p>
January 27, 1995
<p>
The Honorable Henry Hyde<br>
Chairman <br>
Committee on the Judiciary<br>
House of Representatives<br>

<h4>Re: Judiciary Committee Markup of Crime Proposals</h4>
<p>
Dear Representative Hyde:
<p>
As the House Judiciary Committee begins the consideration of a series of
crime bills taken from the "Taking Back Out Streets Act," we write to express
our grave concern and
opposition to those measures which we believe will significantly curtail the
civil rights and
civil liberties of millions.
<p>
The ACLU opposes all of the following measures of the "Taking Back Our
Streets Act,"
which we understand are now to be considered by the Judiciary Committee as a
series of
separate bills.  None should be enacted into law.  The following summary sets
out our major concerns:
<p>
Habeas/Death Penalty - The Writ of Federal Habeas Corpus is critically
important to
assuring that governments exercise their authority to punish in accordance
with the
mandates of the Constitution.  The habeas proposal which this committee will
be
considering would severely restrict the availability of the writ by placing
rigid time restrictions on prisoners filing habeas corpus petitions without
adequately addressing the serious crisis of representation for indigent
defendants -- particularly those facing capital charges.  At the same time,
the measure tilts the scales of the federal law further in the direction of
death by reducing the jury's discretion to decide whether to recommend the
death penalty or some other punishment.
<p>
Federal Mandatory Minimums for Gun Crimes - This measure would establish
mandatory
minimum sentences of 10, 20, 30 years and life for drug or violent crimes
that involve guns. It would federalize virtually every state crime committed
with a firearm in America, despite no finding that state prosecutions are
lacking.  A similar provision offered last term was heavily condemned, not
only on federalism grounds but because of its prohibitive cost and its
guarantee to wreak havoc on the already overburdened judicial and prison
systems, leaving the federal courts little, if any, time to consider
constitutional civil cases. 
<p>
Mandatory Restitution - Although the ACLU supports the appropriate use of
restitution as
an important component in the administration of justice, these proposed
changes not only
alter the entire nature and purpose of existing restitution statutes, they
violate constitutional due process protections as well.  The measure expands
the court's authority beyond the losses directly caused by the defendant,
allowing the imposition of a penalty for an offense without conviction for
that offense.  The provision also has the potential for discrimination on the
basis of economic status, as those who are unable to comply with the
restitution order could be re-incarcerated.
<p>
Law Enforcement Block Grants - This measure supplants the police, prevention
and drug
court provisions of the recently-enacted crime bill, replacing those sections
with a $10
million authorization which local governments can only use for specified law
enforcement
measures.  Included in the prevention programs which this measure decimated
were funds for intensive prevention services to high crime areas, substance
abuse and job programs, Ounce of Prevention grants, school-based programs for
youth at risk and funding for nighttime sports opportunities for youth.  In
addition this provision would eliminate funding for the Family Unity
Demonstration Project which permits eligible incarcerated parents to live
with their children and serve their sentences in a structured, community
based setting -- aiding both the child and the rehabilitation of the parent.
<p>
Grants for Prison Construction based on "Truth in Sentencing" - This measure
replaces the more flexible prison construction section in the
recently-enacted crime bill, mandating a solely "bricks and mortar" approach
to sanctioning offenders.  It authorizes $10.5 billion to states so they can
build, expand and operate prisons, provided that they either show
significant increases in the percentage of violent offenders sentenced to and
serving time
in prison, or prove that serious violent offenders serve at least 85% of
their sentence.  This
"truth in sentencing" mandate fails to differentiate between those who have
demonstrated
that they are ready to return to society and those who have not, removing all
incentive a
prisoner may have to participate in any rehabilitative programs that might to
offered.  This
provision also will result in increased prison overcrowding, increased costs
to taxpayers,
and a substantial change in the laws of most states.
<p>
Exclusionary Rule - The Exclusionary Rule hold that any evidence discovered
as a result
of improper police action cannot be introduced at trial.  In 1984 the Court
modified the
Exclusionary Rule to permit the introduction of evidence that was obtained in
good faith
reliance on a search warrant that was later found to be invalid.  This
measure expands
current law to allow introduction of evidence obtained during a search or
seizure that was
conducted with the belief that it was conducted legally, regardless of
whether a search
warrant had been granted or even sought.  Enactment of this provision will
have a
devastating effect on the deterrence of police misconduct and provide an
incentive to law
enforcement personnel to circumvent the warrant process, making unreasonable,
warrantless searches of one's person, property and private dwelling
commonplace.
<p>
Prisoner Lawsuits - This proposal permits a judge to dismiss a prisoner's
civil rights claim
if s/he has failed to exhaust prison administrative remedies, allowing the
possibility that a
prisoner will suffer irreparable injury.  This measure also permits judges to
dismiss lawsuits filed by poor prisoners if the lawsuit fails to state a
claim upon which relief may be granted.  Basic fairness dictates that all
prisoners have an opportunity to be heard, not just those who have the funds
to prepay court costs.
<p>
"Stop Turning Out Prisoners Act" - This section, introduced for the first
time this week,
severely limits the power of the federal courts to grant relief in prison
conditions cases;
appears to outlaw settlements in the context of prison conditions litigation;
automatically
terminates decrees and judgments regarding prison conditions after two years
even though constitutional violations continue; requires the termination of
any judgment or decree that was granted if the court made no finding that a
federal right was violated in a prison conditions case (settlements are
typically entered into by defendants with the explicit provision that no
admission is made that a constitutional violation has occurred); requires an
automatic stay of relief after the filing of a motion to modify or terminate
the judgment or decree even when a constitutional violation is ongoing;
usurps the power of the judiciary by limiting the ability of federal courts
to appoint special masters; and limits the ability of plaintiffs' attorneys
to obtain attorney's fees in prison conditions litigation.  As a whole, if
passed, these provisions create a dangerous precedent for the stripping of
constitutional rights from groups of individuals that may fall into disfavor.
<p>
Deportation of "Criminal Aliens" - The most objectionable provisions of this
section include further restrictions on relief to long-term permanent
residents and a blanket bar to
"withholding of deportation" for convicted aggravated felons, subjecting them
to deportation to countries where they would be prosecuted.  This provision
in particular has been previously rejected in conference because of its
harshness.  The measure also greatly expands the list of "aggravated felons"
requiring summary deportation proceedings, reduces the time for taking an
appeal in expedited deportation cases from 30 to 14 days, and limits the
scope of judicial review so dramatically that review would cease to be
meaningful.
<p>
The ACLU has a more detailed analysis of the "Taking Back Our Streets Act"
produced prior to the Act's introduction as HR 3, as well as a separate
analysis of the "Stop Turning Out Prisoners Act," originally submitted two
days ago as HR 445, now subsumed as Title III of HR 667.  We look forward to
working with you and other members of the Committee in fashioning legislation
that does not abrogate constitutional rights.
<p>
Sincerely,
<p>

Ira Glasser<br>
Executive Director
<p>
Laura Murphy Lee<br>
Director, Washington Office
<p>
cc:  Members of the House Judiciary Office
<P>

