</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//SQ//DTD HTML 2.0 + all extensions//EN" "hmpro3.dtd">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>7-9-96 -- The TEAM Act Violations of Free Speech</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/legishdr.gif">
<H1>The TEAM Act Violations of Free Speech </H1>
<P>July 9, 1996</P>
<P>RE: The Teamwork for Employees and Management Act of 1996, S. 295</P>
<P>Dear Senator:</P>
<P>The American Civil Liberties Union urges you to protect the rights of
American workers to free association and free speech as reflected in their free
choice of representation in the workplace by voting against S. 295, the &quot;Teamwork
for Employees and Management Act of 1006,&quot; (sometimes called the TEAM act).
 The Senate began consideration of the bill this afternoon with votes on
amendments and final passage now scheduled for tomorrow afternoon (Wednesday).</P>
<P>This bill would amend the National Labor Relations Act to allow an employer
to establish, for example, a joint employer-employee organization that could
deal with any condition of employment and then name carefully selected employee
&quot;representatives&quot; to that organization, provided only that the
organization does not expressly claim to be the employee representative for
collective bargaining purposes.  Despite this prohibition on claiming to be the
union, company-selected employees would be allowed under the bill to address, on
behalf of other employees who had no role in selecting them, &quot;any matters
of mutual interest&quot; --including those matters that are subject to
collective bargaining.</P>
<P>Company-dominated employee organizations further interfere with the
employees' right to choose their own representative by deceptively giving the
appearance that employees are already represented when in fact the company has
selected the people on both sides of the discussion table (as well as having
decided the topics to be discussed and the resolutions reached).  In fact, &quot;company
unions&quot; have long been identified as a primary source of interference with
genuine employee representation and the collective bargaining process.</P>
<P>I.  The TEAM Act Would Radically Subvert Effective Employee-Management
Relations by Returning to the Era of Company-Selected Employee Representatives</P>
<P>The bill would mark a return to the sham company-dominated employee
representation plans (better known as &quot;company unions&quot;) so widely
discredited that they were outlawed by the national Labor Relations Act (the
Wagner Act).  In fact, these employer-dominated representation schemes were
identified as a principal danger to the effective labor-management relations
that was the aim of collective bargaining.  When he introduced the bill that
became the law named for him, Senator Wagner noted,</P>
<P>Genuine collective bargaining is the only way to attain quality of
bargaining power. . . . The greatest obstacles to collective bargaining are
company-dominated unions, which have multiplied with amazing rapidity . . .
[Only] representatives who are not subservient to the employer with whom they
deal can act freely in the interest of employees. . . .  For these reasons, the
very first step toward genuine collective bargaining is the abolition of the
company-dominated union . . .  78 Cong. Rec. 3443 (1935).</P>
<P>S. 275 would disrupt the balanced approach in the National Labor Relations
Act that, on the one hand, preserves the company's right to select management
representatives while, on the other, provides that employees should have the
right to select their own representatives free from employer domination or undue
influence.  The principle that employee representatives should function
independently is so important that it is also separately protected by the
Landrum-Griffin Act which makes it a federal crime for an employer to provide
financial assistance to a labor organization.</P>
<P>Employer efforts to dominate employee organizations have continued right up
until today.</P>
<P>In Electromation, the Bush Administration Labor Relations Board described
the employer's actions involving:  a situation in which an employer alters
conditions of employment and, as a result, is confronted with a workforce that
is discontented with its new employment environment.  The employer responds to
that discontent by devising and imposing on the employees an organized committee
mechanism composed of managers and employees instructed to &quot;represent&quot;
fellow employees.  The purpose of the Action Committee was, as the record
demonstrates, not to enable management and employees to cooperate to improve &quot;quality&quot;
or &quot;efficiency,&quot; but to create in employees the impression that their
disagreements with management had been resolved bilaterally.  309 NLRB 182
(1992), enforced, Electromation, Inc. v. NLRB, 33 F.3d 1148 (7th Cir. 1994).</P>
<P>This case is actually cited by the supporters of the TEAM Act as one of
three board decisions that demonstrate why the TEAM Act, in their view is
needed.  S. Rep. No. 104-259, 104th Cong., 2d Sess. 9-12 (1995).  The decision,
however, establishes precisely the opposite.  As noted in the excerpt quoted
above, neither Electromation (nor indeed either of the other decided cases)
involved joint quality or efficiency committees, the principal rationale cited
by supporters of S. 295.  Instead the cases ruled that the employers were using
company-controlled sham representation to interfere with the right of employees
to select their own representatives for purposes of collective bargaining.</P>
<P>Permitting company-dominated employee representation schemes was seen as so
damaging to genuine employee empowerment and effective labor-management
cooperation that even the 1947 Congress that enacted the Taft-Hartley Act,
vastly increasing the rights of employers, nonetheless rejected a proposal
similar to S. 275.</P>
<P>From its adoption of the Wagner Act in 1935 to this day, Congress has
consistently recognized that employer-domination of worker representatives is
inherently destructive of genuine cooperation and collective bargaining because
it destroys the employees' exercise of their free association and free speech
rights to select their own representatives.</P>
<P>II.  Employers Are Already Legally Allowed to Establish Employee Teams and
Committees That Do Not Involve Matters Subject to Collective Bargaining</P>
<P>The National Labor Relations Act already gives employers the right t
communicate with their employees about the terms and conditions of employees
(section 8(a)(2)), expressly guarantees the free speech rights of employers
(section 8(c)), and safeguards both the employer's right to respond to
grievances and the employees' right to present, individually or collectively,
grievances to the employer (section 9(a)).</P>
<P>The minority views in the committee report on S. 295 cite decisions of the
National Labor Relations board upholding the right of employers to delegate
significant managerial input and responsibility to employee work teams, even the
right to have employee teams make job assignments, assign job rotation, and
schedule overtime among  team members.  Employee teams have been upheld even
when they strayed from quality control and productivity issues into the
traditionally collective bargaining subjects of wages, hours and terms and
conditions of employment. S. Rep. No. 104-259, 104th Cong., 2d Sess. 27 (1995). 
Thus, so long as management does not demand that it select particular employees
to represent other employees, an employer is already free under current law to
involve employees in the quality assurance, efficiency and productivity programs
that are cited by the supporters of the TEAM Act.</P>
<P>CONCLUSION</P>
<P>Instead of promoting genuine employer-worker cooperation or fostering
employee empowerment, the TEAM Act would make it legal for employers to select
employee &quot;representatives,&quot; determine the topics they discuss and
dictate the &quot;conclusions&quot; they reach. All workers deserve to have
their freedom of association and freedom of speech in the workplace, as
reflected in a genuine freedom of choice in selecting their own representatives,
protected against this kind of violation.  Accordingly, the American Civil
Liberties Union urges you to oppose S. 295, the Teamwork for Employees and
Management Act of 1996.</P>
<P>Sincerely,</P>
<P>Laura W. Murphy, Director, Washington, National Office</P>
<P>Donald Haines, Legislative Counsel</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P></P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
