<HTML><HEAD><TITLE> 4-29-96 -- Immigration Bill -- DeWine/Feingold Amendment
re: National ID</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/legishdr.gif">
<P>
 April 29, 1996</P>
<P>
 Re: DeWine/Feingold Amendment to S. 17\664 on Federalizing Driver's Licenses
and Birth Certificates 
</P>
<P>
 Dear Senator:</P>
<P>

</P>
<P>
 The American Civil Liberties Union urges you to support the DeWine/Feingold
amendment to the immigration bill, S. 1664.  The amendment would eliminate a
burden on the states by striking one of the building blocks in the bill for a
national identification system and national identification document in the
United States.  The ACLU strongly opposes any form of national ID.</P>
<P>
 The DeWine/Feingold amendment would permit states to maintain their existing
practices governing issuance of driver's licenses and birth certificates.  It
would strike a provision of the bill that would require the federal government
to establish requirements the states must follow in issuing driver's licenses
and birth certificates.  Because the bill includes no limitations on what the
federal government may require, the standards issued by the federal government
could transform the driver's license into a de facto identification card for all
Americans.  Federalization of these documents issued by the states would only
pave the way for a single document to be issued by the federal government.</P>
<P>
 The existence of fraudulent driver's licenses and birth certificates cannot
justify the burden the bill would impose on the states to establish
identification and verification systems that meet the approval of the federal
government.  In fact, under the bill, a state would be barred from even
accepting a driver's license for any evidentiary purpose unless the license
followed the form required by the federal government.</P>
<P>
 The provision is a marked departure from the use of the social security number
as a means of tracking payments into the Social Security system.  Under the
bill, states would be required to use the number as an identifier for key
state-issued documents.  A national ID card would infringe on the privacy of all
Americans, and would likely result in an increase in discrimination against
those who &quot;look foreign&quot; or speak with an accent.</P>
<P>
 Just a few months ago, Congress enacted a law to allow the states to set the
speed limits on their own roads.  It would be ironic if Congress today passed a
law that operates to bar drivers from these roads unless they carry a document
containing or tied to a number issued by the federal government.  We urge you to
support the DeWine/Feingold amendment to the immigration bill.</P>
<P>
 Sincerely,</P>
<P>

</P>
<P>
 Laura W. Murphy, Director </P>
<P>
 Gregory T. Nojeim, Legislative Counsel
</P>  
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A><P>
    
</P><H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER>
    
</BLOCKQUOTE></BODY></HTML>
