HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Thursday, 13-Feb-97 14:08:12 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 26-Apr-96 13:42:46 GMT
Content-length: 5155
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>
Document Abuse Provision of Senate Immigration Bill "Discussion Draft"
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<body><blockquote><img src="/graphics/legishdr.gif">
<p>
April 24, 1996
<p>
Dear Senator:
<p>
We understand that an amendment to the immigration bill, S. 269, may be offered on the Senate
floor to deny attorneys' fees to plaintiffs whose civil rights have been violated by unreasonable
government action, simply because the plaintiff is not a citizen or green card holder.  The
proposed amendment would alter the Equal Access to Justice Act (EAJA) to prohibit attorneys'
fees awards to any plaintiff who is not a citizen or legal permanent resident (i.e., "green card"
holder).
<p>
A similar proposal to restrict EAJA was deleted from S. 269 in the Senate Judiciary Committee in
a bipartisan vote of 9-6.  The Committee Members recognized that there is no principled rationale
for limiting EAJA, that current law imposes no significant cost on the INS or other government
agencies, and that the availability of EAJA fees has served the important purpose of curbing
unlawful INS action.
<p>
Under the Equal Access to Justice Act, individuals and small businesses can be awarded
attorneys' fees when they successfully sue the U.S. government for violating the law, provided
they can also show that the government's position was unreasonable.  By definition, the EAJA fee
provision is triggered only when the government itself has violated the law and has done so
without reasonable justification.
<p>
EAJA has allowed civil rights and other groups to bring actions against the Immigration and
Naturalization Service to protect the rights of asylum seekers and others whose civil and
constitutional rights have been violated through unreasonable INS actions.  Aliens are entitled to
certain legal rights under the law regardless of their immigration status.  For example, refugees
are entitled to a fair and non-discriminatory hearing, foreign students are entitled to apply for
work-study jobs and summer employment, and applicants for legal permanent residence are
entitled to a proper and timely determination of their application.  If EAJA were amendment, none
of these individuals would be allowed attorneys' fees no matter how egregious is the INS's illegal
conduct toward them.
<p>
The EAJA amendment is unnecessary.  Even the Clinton Administration has opposed similar
limitations on EAJA fee awards.  A recent GAO study analyzed the amount and number of
attorneys' fees over $10,000 awarded during fiscal years 1993 and 1994.  The total number of
awards against the INS during those two fiscal years was 17.  The total amount of fees awarded
was $1,059,176.  GAO, Selected Attorneys' Fee Awards Against Nine Federal Agencies in 1993
and 1995 (GAO/GGD-96-18, Oct. 1995).
<p>
The proponents of the amendment cannot point to any problems or abuses in the current system
for allowing courts to award fees in the limited number of cases where the government's conduct
is shown to be unreasonable.  EAJA already provides that fees are not available to lawyers
representing immigrants in individual deportation hearings (Ardestani v. INS) and the Board of
Immigration Appeals has ruled that the EAJA fees are not available for administrative appeals.  In
addition, the law already gives courts the authority to deny fees if special circumstances could
make an award unjust.
<p>
The proposed amendment is designed to punish plaintiffs who are refugees, temporary workers or
other non-immigrants whose constitutional or civil rights have been violated by the federal
government.  As Congress recognized when enacted, EAJA (and other civil rights attorneys' fees
statutes such as 42 U.S.C. Section 1988), awarding fees to successful plaintiffs is essential to
finding lawyers who will bring actions to vindicate individual rights and liberties.  Under EAJA,
such fees can be awarded only when the plaintiffs both prevail in their lawsuit and show that their
rights were violated by unreasonable government action.  There is no legitimate rationale for
denying this protection to non-citizens who do not have a green card.  These individuals are
especially vulnerable and should not be singled out and denied the ability to protect their rights.
<p>
The INS is notorious for making mistakes, subjecting individuals to unfair treatment and violating
its own statute and regulations.  Recently, it admitted to having lost 60,000 political asylum
applications.  Judicial oversight is critical to protecting individuals against abuses.  Amending
EAJA could deter lawyers from bringing these actions.  We urge you to oppose any amendment
that would eliminate EAJA fees in actions brought on behalf of plaintiffs who are not citizens or
green card holders.
<p>
Sincerely,
<p>
Laura W. Murphy, Director
<p>
Gregory T. Nojeim, Legislative Counsel
<P>
