<html><head><title>
Proposed Expansion of Wiretapping in the Senate Immigration Bill S.1394
</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<body><blockquote><img src="/graphics/legishdr.gif">
<p>
To:     Interested Persons
<p>
From:  ACLU Washington National Office
<p>
Re:     Wiretapping Bills on Immigration and Terrorism Move to House Votes on March 12-19
<p>        
Date:   February 24, 1996
<p>
     In what could be called the House Wiretapping week, the House of Representatives is
scheduled to consider two bills -- H.R. 2202, the "Immigration in the National Interest Act of 1995,"
and H.R. 2768, the "Effective Death Penalty and Antiterrorism Act of 1995"  -- which would
significantly expand the government's authority to listen in on the private conversations of people in
the United States, invite more illegal wiretaps, and limit the authority of judges to oversee law
enforcement wiretaps.  These bills would dramatically reduce privacy rights by significantly increasing
the number of innocent conversations intercepted by law enforcement officials.  Already, too many
innocent conversations -- nearly two million last year -- are intercepted in law enforcement wiretaps
and in other forms of electronic surveillance.(1)  Congress should look to reduce, not expand,
wiretapping.
<p>
<b>CURRENT WIRETAPPING LAW  </b>
<p>
     Current federal law prohibits the interception of oral,(2)  wire,(3) and electronic
communications,(4) except as specifically authorized.  18 U.S.C. Section 2511.  Electronic
surveillance is a particularly intrusive investigatory technique, subject to the search and seizure
requirements of the Fourth Amendment.  Katz v. United States, 389 U.S. 347 (1967).  In order to
conduct electronic surveillance, the FBI or other law enforcement authority must obtain a court order
based upon probable cause.  Federal law enforcers may obtain a court order for interception of oral
or wire communications only in connection with investigations of certain specified federal offenses. 
See 18 U.S.C. Section 2516.  
<p>
     Eighteen U.S.C. Section 2515 codifies the constitutional requirement that conversations
intercepted by electronic surveillance placed illegally cannot be used as evidence in court, and cannot
be used in any legislative or regulatory proceeding.  The statutory exclusionary rule encourages law
enforcement to secure a court order for a wiretap because it is required, and to refrain from
abrogating the Fourth Amendment protection against arbitrary search and seizure in conducting
electronic surveillance.  Current law also grants judges authority to require law enforcement to justify
periodically the continued need for a wiretap, and to show that the wiretap is collecting, or will
collect, incriminating evidence.  See 18 U.S.C. Section 2518(6).
<p>
<b>WIRETAPPING IN HOUSE IMMIGRATION BILL</b>
<p>
     Section 201 of H.R. 2202 would expand statutory authority to conduct wiretaps and other
forms of electronic surveillance by expanding the list of federal offenses that would support an
electronic surveillance order to include:  
<p><blockquote>
1.  felony violation of 18 U.S.C. Section 1028 (production of false identification documents)(5);
<p>

2.  18 U.S.C. Section 1541 (issuing a false passport);
<p>

3.  18 U.S.C. Section 1542 (knowingly making a false statement to obtain a passport for any person,
or using a passport knowing it was obtained fraudulently);
<p>

4.  18 U.S.C. Section 1543 (falsely altering, counterfeiting or forging a passport with intent that it
may be used, or knowingly using a false, forged or altered passport, or a passport that has become
void because, for example, it has expired);
<p>

5.  18 U.S.C. Section 1544 (knowingly using another person's passport, or knowingly using a
passport in violation of the conditions or restrictions contained in the passport or of the rules
prescribed pursuant to laws regulating the issuance of  passports);
<p>

6.  18 U.S.C. Section 1546 (making or using any false visa, border crossing card, or other document
authorizing entry into or work in the United States, or using any false ID document having reason
to know it was issued illegally for the purpose of showing work authorization);
<p>
7. 8 U.S.C. Section 1324 (knowingly bringing into the United States an undocumented person, or
harboring in any building or attempting to conceal such a person, or transporting such a person in
reckless disregard of the fact the person is present in violation of the law when such transportation
furthers such violation of the law, or encouraging or inducing any alien to come to the United States
in violation of the law);
<p>

8. 8 U.S.C. Section 1327 (knowingly helping an alien excludable as an aggravated felon to enter the
United States illegally); and
<p>

9. 8 U.S.C. Section 1328 (importing an alien for an immoral purpose, including prostitution).(6)
<p>
</blockquote>
     Never before has electronic surveillance been authorized for such crimes.  Investigation of
these crimes would target Americans (not just aliens), include investigation of activities that have
nothing to do with a violation of the nation's immigration laws, and extend wiretap authority to less
serious crimes.  Under this bill, the government could listen in on a conversation involving:  (i) a U.S.
soldier who takes pity on a Bosnian woman whose husband was abducted and killed in ethnic
cleansing and upon the soldier's return from his peacekeeping duties there, induces her by telephone
to come to the United States without authorization for her own protection; (ii) an American who
befriends a person she knows is undocumented and agrees by phone to transport him to a city in
which he might seek employment; (iii) a child who phones her underage friend about a false state
driver's license she secured and is sending through the mails; and (iv) a Lebanese-American who
phones his grandmother in Lebanon and indicates that he intends to visit her in violation of the ban
on use of the U.S. passport to travel to Lebanon.  
<p>

     To extend wiretapping to this type of activity ignores the fact that wiretapping is an extremely
intrusive, almost indiscriminate form of surveillance that should be authorized sparingly and only to
interdict the most serious crimes.  Extensive wiretapping leaves people with the uncomfortable notion
that "Big Brother" is eavesdropping, and they never know when.
<p>

<b>WIRETAPPING IN THE HOUSE TERRORISM BILL</b>
<p>

     Section 305 of the House terrorism bill, H.R. 2768, would invite significantly more illegal
wiretaps by ripping a gaping hole in the statutory exclusionary rule for law enforcement wiretaps. 
Section 305 of H.R. 2768 would allow the in court use of evidence gathered illegally in a wiretap
provided the law enforcement officers who conducted the wiretap illegally were able to convince a
judge that they acted illegally "in good faith."  This is an unconstitutional abandonment of the Fourth
Amendment as it applies to electronic surveillance.    
<p>

     The bill would amend 18 U.S.C. Section 2515 to provide that the requirement that evidence
be excluded would not apply if "any law enforcement officers who intercepted the communication
or gathered the evidence derived therefrom acted with the reasonable objective belief that their
actions were in compliance" with the wiretap law.
<p>

     No explanation has been offered by the FBI to show why it purports to need this new
authority to use illegally obtained evidence.  It certainly cannot have anything to do with the need to
combat terrorism, the ostensible purpose for the terrorism bill, given the paucity of requests for
wiretapping authorization in cases involving crimes commonly associated with terrorism.(7)
<p>

     In the ACLU's view, this section is frightening, unconstitutional, and likely to result in more
illegal wiretaps.  Although the Supreme Court has in recent years announced certain limitations on
the exclusionary rule for evidence obtained in violation of the Fourth Amendment, the blanket
exemption for law enforcement malfeasance found in Section 305 of the House terrorism bill goes
far beyond anything permitted by the Supreme Court.  In United States v. Leon, 468 U.S. 897 (1984),
the Supreme Court permitted the introduction of evidence derived from an unconstitutional search
undertaken in good faith reliance on a defective search warrant.  Similarly, in Arizona v. Evans, 115
S.Ct. 1185, 514 U.S. ___ (1995), the Supreme Court held that the exclusionary rule did not apply
to an unlawful search based upon a reasonable, but mistaken, good faith belief that a warrant was
outstanding.
<p>

     To date, however, the Supreme Court has continued to adhere to the exclusionary rule in
cases involving warrantless searches; yet Section 305 of H.R. 2768 would authorize the admission
of evidence from an unconstitutional search, even if no court authorization had ever been sought. 
Evidence of the circumstances of the unconstitutional search and seizure will inevitably be in the
possession of the officers, and it will be extremely difficult for a defendant to establish that they did
not act in good faith, if they assert that they did.  Thus law enforcement officials will be given an
incentive to operate close to the constitutional margin in conducting wiretaps on the theory that, even
if their actions are unconstitutional, frequently they will nevertheless be able to use the evidence in
court.  This is precisely the reverse of the incentives for conscientious, constitutional behavior that
the exclusionary rule was designed to evoke.  For this reason, we expect that the courts will reject
this provision as unconstitutional. In addition, Section 307 of H.R. 2768 would do away with a
statutory provision that grants judges authority to require law enforcement officials to justify
periodically the continuing need for a wiretap.  Under current law, judges have the authority to put
in an order authorizing a particular wiretap a requirement that reports be made to the judge "at such
intervals as the judge may require" showing what progress has been made toward achievement of the
authorized objective of the wiretap and the need for continued interception.  With this authority,
judges have can oversee a wiretap and ensure that if the wiretap is not turning up incriminating
evidence, and is not likely to turn up incriminating evidence, it will not be left in place.  It gives the
judge a chance to minimize the interception of innocent conversations by ordering as quickly as
possible the discontinuation of non-productive wiretap.  Section 307 would require only one report
to the judge 15 days after interception began.  Judges would be deprived of any other opportunity
to assess whether a wiretap should be discontinued until the government applied to the court for an
extension after each 30-day period for which a wiretap can be placed has expired.  No showing has
been made to justify depriving judges of this authority; no showing has been made that the existing
provision of the law has been abused by judges; and no showing has been made that it is too
expensive for law enforcement to be required to periodically justify to a judge the use of this
extremely intrusive surveillance tool.  To do away with this requirement would virtually ensure the
interception of more innocent conversations in law enforcement wiretaps.
<p>

<b>MORE WIRETAPPING MEANS LESS PRIVACY FOR AMERICANS</b>
<p>

     The ACLU opposes all of these provisions which would dramatically expand the list of crimes
that would support a wiretap application, invite more illegal wiretaps, and strip judges of much of
their statutory authority to oversee law enforcement wiretaps.  Some in Congress believe that an
acceptable response to undocumented immigration or to crimes associated with terrorism is
sacrificing the privacy of Americans.  The ACLU does not share this view, whether it is advanced to
support expansion of wiretap authority or the proposed national ID system in the House immigration
bill (H.R. 2202) or to grant the FBI enhanced access without a criminal predicate to phone and travel
records pertaining to people in the United States in counter-terrorism or counter-intelligence
investigations, as would be authorized in the House terrorism bill (H.R. 2768).  
<p>

     The answer to every challenge to law enforcement -- whether undocumented immigration,
drug use, or terrorism -- is not an expansion in federal wiretap authority.  
<p>

     Wiretapping and other forms of electronic surveillance are invasive, expensive, expanding,
and increasingly inefficient.  Electronic surveillance intercepts are not short-term intrusions.  Using
1994 numbers, each time a federal or state electronic surveillance intercept was installed, it was left
in place not for two or three days, but for an average of 40 days.(8)  Each time an electronic
surveillance intercept is placed, an average of 2,139 conversations are intercepted and an average of
84 persons' conversations are intercepted.(9) Many of these persons are never told that their
conversation was intercepted by a law enforcement official.(10)
<p>

     Wiretapping is expensive.  The average cost of a single federal wiretap in 1994 was
$66,783.(11)  average cost of a single federal roving wiretap for those wiretaps that were terminated
in 1994 was nearly $100,000.(12)
<p>

     Wiretapping is expanding.  The number of federal electronic surveillance intercepts nearly
doubled from 1984 to 1994.(13) The average number of intercepted conversations per installed law
enforcement intercept increased from 1,209 to 2,139 from 1984-1994.(14)  
<p>

     The FBI recently signaled its intention to further expand wiretapping and other forms of
electronic surveillance.  It said that it wants to require the nation's phone companies to alter critical
telephone equipment to enable the Bureau to eavesdrop on one out of every one hundred telephone
conversations occurring at any given time in the nation's largest cites.  60 Fed. Reg. 53643, October
16, 1995.  The FBI is seeking at least $500 million to establish a fund to pay the phone companies
to implement its plan -- a plan that goes significantly beyond even the digital telephony measure
adopted on the last day of the last Congress. 
<p>

     Most importantly, wiretapping is increasingly inefficient.  Each time a federal or state
electronic surveillance intercept is installed, an average of 1,775 innocent ("non-incriminating")
conversations are intercepted.(15)  In 1994, approximately 1,942,600 innocent conversations were
intercepted through law enforcement intercepts.(16)  Over the period from 1984-1994, approximately
11 million innocent conversations were intercepted with such devices.(17)  This is a tremendous
sacrifice of privacy.  From 1984 to 1994, while the number of federal electronic surveillance
intercepts installed nearly doubled, the proportion of incriminating calls from all electronic
surveillance plummeted from 25% to only 17%.(18)  That means, conversely, that each time an
electronic surveillance intercept is placed, 83% of the conversations intercepted will be non-incriminating, or innocent.
<p>

     If only five wiretaps were placed each year under each new wiretap predicate in the House
immigration bill (H.R. 2202), and if those new wiretaps cost only the same, in terms of dollars and
privacy, as other wiretaps, Section 201 of the immigration bill will cost taxpayers more than three
million dollars and "cost" privacy in the U.S. the interception of nearly 80,000 innocent ("non-incriminating") conversations.(19)
<p>

<b>CONCLUSION</b>
<p>

     Bugging and wiretapping are particularly intrusive investigatory techniques that undermine
the personal privacy we all cherish.  For that reason, people do not like wiretapping.  When asked
each year for the last 20 years, "Everything considered, would you say that you approve or
disapprove of wiretapping," approximately 75% of those surveyed said they disapprove of
wiretapping. The government has made no showing of need for this additional authority, let alone a
showing that its need for more wiretaps outweighs the threat to privacy such expanded authority
would pose.  Nor has the government made any showing that judges should be stripped of the
authority to require law enforcement to periodically justify continued application of a wiretap, or that
its need to use in court conversations gathered in an illegal wiretap would justify doing away with the
statutory exclusionary rule.  The provisions that would expand in wiretapping authority in Section
201 of the House immigration bill (H.R. 2202) and in Sections 305 and 307 of the House terrorism
bill (H.R. 2768), should be deleted.  For further information, please contact Gregory T. Nojeim at
the ACLU, 202/544-1681. 
<p>
<b>NOTES</b>
<p>
1 -- Electronic surveillance intercepts include wiretaps, electronic listening devices known as "bugs"
which intercept oral conversations, interception of pager transmissions, cellular phone conversations,
and electronic mail (e-mail), or any combination of the above.  Wiretaps comprise approximately 70%
of law enforcement electronic surveillance intercepts. The term "wiretap" is sometimes used to
include all forms of electronic surveillance.
<p>
2 -- " Oral communication' means any oral communication uttered by a person exhibiting an
expectation that such communication is not subject to interception under circumstances justifying
such expectation," 18 U.S.C. Section 2510(1).
<p>
3 -- A "wire communicatoin" is "any aural transfer made in whole or in part through the use of
facilities for the transmission of communications by the aid of wire, cable, or other like connection,"
Id., Section 2510(2).
<p>
4 -- An "electronic communication" is "any transfer of signs, signals, writing, images, sounds, data,
or intelligence of any nature transmitted in whole or in part by a wire, radio, electromagnetic, photo
electronic or photo optical system," that is not an oral or wire communciation. Id., Section 2510(12).
<p>
5 -- Due to space limitations, parenthetical descriptions of these statutes often do not include or fully
describe all of the activities they prohibit.  Please refer to the actual statute.
<p>
6 -- The Clinton Administration supports the proposed expansion of federal wiretap authority.  Letter
from Kent Markus, Acting Assistant Attorney General to Senator Simpson, June 7, 1995 at 10. 
Section 201 of H.R. 2202 as passed by the House Judiciary Committee would extend federal wiretap
authority to the same crimes with the exceptions of 18 U.S.C. Sections 1425, 1426, and 1427.
<p>
7 -- Administrative Office of the United States Courts, Wiretap Report for the Period January 1, 1994
to December 31, 1994 (April 1995), p. 21. [hereinafter "Wiretap Report] Intercepts stay in place far
longer today than they used to.  In 1970, the average electronic surveillance intercept was in place
for fewer than 20 days.
<p>
8 -- Id., at pp. 5 and 21.  These figures are for 1994.  For the period of 1998401994, an average of
117 persons' calls were intercepted per wiretap.
<p>
9 -- Eighteen U.S.C. Section 2518(8)(d) requires the judge authorizing electronic surveillance to
cause to be served on the subjects of that surveillance notice of the period during which wire or oral
communications were intercepted.  It gives the judge discretion to be exercised "in the interest of
justice" to cause notification to any other party to the intercepted conversations.
<p>
10 -- Wiretap Report at pp. 6 and 16.
<p>
11 -- Id. Pp. A2-A43.
<p>
12 -- Id. At 21.
<p>
13 -- Id. At 21.
<p>
14 -- Id. At pp. 5 and 21.
<p>
15 -- Id. At 21.  Computed by multiplying the difference between the average number of intercepted
conversations and the average number of incriminating intercepted conversations by the number of
wiretaps installed ((2,139-373) x 1,1100).
<p>
16 -- Id. At 21.  Computed in a similar manner.
<p>
17 -- Id. At pp. 5 and 21.
<p>
18 -- Calculated as follows: 5 wiretaps x 12 new statutory wiretap predicates = 60 new wiretaps per
year, at a cost of $66,783 per federal wiretap and with the interception of 1775 innocent ("non-incriminating") conversations per wiretap.
<p>
19 -- U.S. Department of Justice Bureau of Justice Statistics, Sourcebook of Criminal Justice
Statistics -- 1994, table 2.41, p. 173.
