<html><head><title>
Proposed Expansion of Wiretapping in the Senate Immigration Bill S.1394
</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<body><blockquote><img src="/graphics/legishdr.gif">
<p>
To:     Interested Persons
<p>
From:  ACLU Washington National Office
<p>
Re:     Proposed Expansion of Wiretapping in the Senate Immigration Bill S.1394
<p>  
Date:   February 24, 1996
<p>
     Section 121 of the Senate immigration bill, "The Immigration Reform Act of 1995" (S.1394)
as passed by the Senate Subcommittee on Immigration would expand the government's authority to
listen in on the private conversations of people in the United States.  It would dramatically reduce
privacy rights by significantly increasing the number of innocent conversations intercepted by law
enforcement officials.  Already, too many innocent conversations -- nearly two million last year -- are
intercepted in law enforcement wiretaps and in other forms of electronic surveillance.(1)  Congress
should look to reduce, not expand, the circumstances under which a wiretap can be placed.
<p>

<b>CURRENT WIRETAPPING LAW  </b>

<p>
     Current federal law prohibits the interception of oral,(2) wire,(3) and electronic
communications,(4) except as specifically authorized.  18 U.S.C. Section 2511.  Electronic
surveillance is a particularly intrusive investigatory technique, subject to the search and seizure
requirements of the Fourth Amendment.  Katz v. United States, 389 U.S. 347 (1967).  In order to
conduct electronic surveillance, the FBI or other law enforcement authority must obtain a court order
based upon probable cause.  Federal law enforcers may obtain a court order for interception of oral
or wire communications only in connection with investigations of certain specified federal offenses. 
See 18 U.S.C. Section 2516.  
<p>
<b>PROPOSED EXPANSION OF WIRETAPPING</b>
<p>

     Section 121 would expand statutory authority to conduct wiretaps and other forms of
electronic surveillance by expanding the list of criminal statutes that would support an electronic
surveillance order to include:  
<p>
<blockquote>
1.  felony violation of 18 U.S.C. Section 1028 (production of false identification documents)(5);
<p>

2.  18 U.S.C. Section 1425 (obtaining or knowingly copying false naturalization or citizenship and
related documents);
<p>

3.  18 U.S.C. section 1426 (reproducing, forging or altering any certificate of arrival, evidence of
naturalization or citizenship, or knowingly using as true a false, forged or altered affidavit, evidence
of citizenship, etc.);
<p>

4.  18 U.S.C. Section 1427 (sale of documentary evidence of citizenship such as a certificate of
naturalization or citizenship);
<p>

5.  18 U.S.C. Section 1541 (issuing a false passport);
<p>

6.  18 U.S.C. Section 1542 (knowingly making a false statement to obtain a passport for any person,
or using a passport knowing it was obtained fraudulently);
<p>

7.  18 U.S.C. Section 1543 (falsely altering, counterfeiting or forging a passport with intent that it
may be used, or knowingly using a false, forged or altered passport, or a passport that has become
void because, for example, it has expired);
<p>

8.  18 U.S.C. Section 1544 (knowingly using another person's passport, or knowingly using a
passport in violation of the conditions or restrictions contained in the passport or of the rules
prescribed pursuant to laws regulating the issuance of  passports);
<p>

9.  18 U.S.C. Section 1546 (making or using any false visa, border crossing card, or other document
authorizing entry into or work in the United States, or using any false ID document having reason
to know it was not issued lawfully for the purpose of showing work authorization);
<p>

10. 8 U.S.C. Section 1324 (knowingly bringing into the United States an undocumented person, or
harboring in any building or attempting to conceal such a person, or transporting such a person in
reckless disregard of the fact the person is present in violation of the law when such transportation
furthers such violation of the law, or encouraging or inducing any alien to come to the United States
in violation of the law);
<p>

11. 8 U.S.C. Section 1327 (knowingly helping an alien excludable as an aggravated felon to enter the
United States illegally); and
<p>

12. 8 U.S.C. Section 1328 (importing an alien for an immoral purpose, including prostitution).(6)
<p>
</blockquote>
     Never before has electronic surveillance been authorized for such crimes.  Investigation of
these crimes would target Americans (not just aliens), include investigation of activities that have
nothing to do with a violation of the nation's immigration laws, and extend wiretap authority to less
serious crimes.  Under this bill, the government could listen in on a conversation involving:  (i) a U.S.
soldier who takes pity on a Bosnian woman whose husband was abducted and killed in ethnic
cleansing and upon the soldier's return from his peacekeeping there, induces her by telephone to come
to the United States without authorization for her own protection; (ii) an American who befriends
a person she knows is undocumented and agrees by phone to transport him to a city in which he
might seek employment; (iii) a child who phones her underage friend about a false state driver's
license she secured and is sending through the mails; and (iv) a Lebanese-American who phones his
grandmother in Lebanon and indicates that he intends to visit her in violation of the ban on use of the
U.S. passport to travel to Lebanon.  
<p>

     To extend wiretapping to this type of activity ignores the fact that wiretapping is an extremely
intrusive, almost indiscriminate form of surveillance that should be authorized sparingly and only to
interdict very serious crimes.  Extensive wiretapping leaves people with the uncomfortable notion that
"Big Brother" is eavesdropping, and that they never know when.  
<p>

<b>MORE WIRETAPPING MEANS LESS PRIVACY FOR AMERICANS</b>
<p>

     The ACLU opposes all of these provisions which would dramatically expand the list of crimes
that would support a wiretap application.  Some in Congress believe that an acceptable response to
undocumented immigration is sacrificing the privacy of Americans.  The ACLU does not share this
view, whether it is advanced to support expansion of wiretap authority or the proposed national ID
system in the Immigration Reform Act (S.1394) Sections 111-113. 
<p>

     The answer to each challenge to law enforcement -- whether undocumented immigration, drug
use, or crimes associated with terrorism -- is not an expansion in federal wiretap authority.
<p>
     Wiretapping and other forms of electronic surveillance are invasive, expensive, expanding,
and increasingly inefficient.  Electronic surveillance intercepts are not short-term intrusions.  Using
1994 numbers, each time a federal or state electronic surveillance intercept was installed, it was left
in place not for two or three days, but for an average of 40 days.(7)  Each time an electronic
surveillance intercept is placed, an average of 2,139 conversations are intercepted and an average of
84 persons' conversations are intercepted.(8)  Many of these persons are never told that their
conversation was intercepted by a law enforcement official.(9)

<p>  
     Wiretapping is expensive.  The average cost of a single federal wiretap in 1994 was
$66,783.(10)  The average cost of a single federal roving wiretap for those wiretaps that were
terminated in 1994 was nearly $100,000.(11)
<p>

     Wiretapping is expanding.  The number of federal electronic surveillance intercepts nearly
doubled from 1984 to 1994.(12)  The average number of intercepted conversations per installed law
enforcement intercept increased from 1,209 to 2,139 from 1984-1994.(13)  
<p>

     The FBI recently signaled its intent to further expand wiretapping and other forms of
electronic surveillance.  It said that it wants to require the nation's phone companies to alter critical
telephone equipment to enable the Bureau to eavesdrop on one out of every one hundred telephone
conversations occurring at any given time in the nation's largest cites.  60 Fed. Reg. 53643, October
16, 1995.  The FBI is seeking at least $500 million to establish a fund to pay the phone companies
to implement its plan -- a plan that goes significantly beyond even the digital telephony measure
adopted on the last day of the last Congress. 

<p>
     Most importantly, wiretapping is increasingly inefficient.  Each time a federal or state
electronic surveillance intercept is installed, an average of 1,775 innocent ("non-incriminating")
conversations are intercepted.(14)  In 1994, approximately 1,942,600 innocent conversations were
intercepted through law enforcement intercepts.(15)  Over the period from 1984-1994, approximately
11 million innocent conversations were intercepted with such devices.(16)  This is a tremendous
sacrifice of privacy.  From 1984 to 1994, while the number of federal electronic surveillance
intercepts installed nearly doubled, the proportion of incriminating calls from all electronic
surveillance plummeted from 25% to only 17%.(17)  That means, conversely, that each time an
electronic surveillance intercept is placed, 83% of the conversations intercepted will be non-incriminating, or innocent.  

<p>
     If only five wiretaps were placed each year under each new wiretap predicate in Section 121
of the Immigration Reform Act of 1995 (S.1394), and if those new wiretaps cost only the same, in
terms of dollars and privacy, as other wiretaps, Section 121 will cost taxpayers more than four million
dollars and "cost" privacy in the U.S. the interception of 106,000 innocent ("non-incriminating")
conversations.(18)
<p>

<b>CONCLUSION</b>
<p>

     Bugging and wiretapping are particularly intrusive investigatory techniques that undermine
the personal privacy we all cherish.  For that reason, people do not like wiretapping.  When asked
each year for the last 20 years, "Everything considered, would you say that you approve or
disapprove of wiretapping," approximately 75% of those surveyed said they disapprove of
wiretapping.(19)  The government has made no showing of need for this additional authority, let
alone a showing that its need for more wiretaps outweighs the threat to privacy such expanded
authority would pose.  The expansion in federal wiretapping authority envisioned in Section 121
should be rejected and Section 121 should be deleted from the bill.  For further information, please
contact Gregory T. Nojeim at the ACLU, 202/544-1681. 
<p>

<b>NOTES</b>
<p>
1 - Electronic surveillance intercepts include wiretaps, electronic listening devices known as "bugs"
which intercept oral conversations, interception of pager transmissions, cellular phone conversations,
and electronic mail (e-mail), or any combination of the above.  Wiretaps comprise approximately 70%
of the electronic surveillance intercepts installed by law enforcement.  The term "wiretap" is
sometimes used to include all forms of electronic surveillance.
<p>
2 - " Oral communication' means any oral communication uttered by a person exhibiting an
expectation that such communication is not subject to interception under circumstances justifying
such expectation," 18 U.S.C. Section 2510(1).
<p>
3 -- A "wire communication" is "any aural transfer made in whole or in part through the use of
facilities for the transmission of communications by the aid of wire, cable, or other like connection,"
Id., Section 2510(2).
<p>
4 -- An "electronic communication" is "any transfer of signs, signals, writing, images, sounds, data,
or intelligence of any nature transmitted in whole or in part by a wire, radio, electromagnetic, photo
electronic or photo optical system," that is not an oral or wire communication. Id., Section 2510(12).
<p>
5 -- Due to space limitations, parenthetical descriptions of these statutes often do not include or fully
describe all of the activities they prohibit.  Please refer to the actual statute.
<p>
6 -- The Clinton Administration supports the proposed expansion of federal wiretap authority.  Letter
from Kent Markus, Acting Assistant Attorney General to Senator Simpson, June 7, 1995, at 10. 
Section 121 of the Senate immigration bill, the "Immigration Reform Act of 1995" (S.1394) as
reported by the Senate Judiciary Committee subcommittee on Immigration would extend federal
wiretap authority not only to these crimes, but also to: (i) 18 U.S.C. Section 1425 (obtaining or
knowingly copying false naturalization or citizenship and related documents); (ii) 18 U.S.C. section
1426 (reproducing, forging or altering any certificate of arrival, evidence of naturalization or
citizenship, or knowingly using as true a false, forged or altered affidavit, evidence of citizenship,
etc.); and (iii) 18 U.S.C. Section 1427 (sale of documentary evidence of citizenship such as a
certificate of naturalization or citizenship).
<p>
7 -- Law enforcement has not requested a wiretap for crimes of arson, bombings or firearms since
1988.  They constitute less than 0.2% of the wiretaps placed since 1984.
<p>
8 -- Administrative Office of the United States Courts, Wiretap Report for the Period January 1, 1994
to December 31, 1994 (April, 1995), p. 21 [hereinafter "Wiretap Report'] Intercepts stay in place far
longer than they used to.  In 1970, the average electronic surveillance intercept was in place for fewer
than 20 days.
<p>
9 -- Id., at pp. 5 and 21.  These figures are for 1994.  For the period of 1984-1994, an average of 117
persons' calls were intercepted per wiretap.
<p>
10 -- Eighteen U.S.C. Section 2518(8)(d) requires the judge authorizing electronic surveillance to
cause to be served on the subjects of that surveillance notice of the period during which wire or oral
communications were intercepted.  It gives the judge discretion to be exercised "int he interest of
justice" to cause notification to any other party to the intercepted conversations.
<p>
11 -- Wiretap Report at pp. 6 and 16.
<p>
12 -- Id., pp. A2-A43.
<p>
13 -- Id. At 21.
<p>
14 -- Id. At 21.
<p>
15 -- Id., at pp. 5 and 21.
<p>
16 -- Id., at 21.  Computed by multiplying the difference between the average number of intercepted
conversations and the average number of incriminating intercepted conversations by the number of
wiretaps installed ((2,139-373) x 1,100).
<p>
17 -- Id., at 21.  Computed in a similar manner.
<p>
18 -- Id., at pp. 4 and 21.
<p>
19 -- Calculated as follows: 5 wiretaps x 9 new statutory wiretap predicates = 45 new wiretaps per
year, at a cost of $55,783 per federal wiretap and with the interception of 1775 innocent ("non-incriminating") conversations per wiretap = 79,875 non-incriminating conversations.
<p>
20 -- U.S. Department of Justice Bureau of Justice Statistics, Sourcebook of Criminal Justice
Statistics -- 1994, table 2.41, p. 173.
<P>

