</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>
English-Only Letter
</title>
<!JM 1/4/96>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<body><blockquote><img src="/graphics/legishdr.gif">
<p>
December 5, 1995
<p>
Dear Senator:

<p>     Soon you may be asked to consider one of a number of pending bills that
would, in effect, exclude many non-English speakers from many of the benefits
of citizenship in the United States.  The legislation would bar the
government, and its branches, from using any language other than English,
with few exceptions.  Other legislation would amend the Constitution to make
English the official language of the United States.  We encourage you to
oppose such legislation and constitutional amendments.
</p>
<p>     English Only bills are legislation in search of a problem that does not
exist. According to census data,  approximately 3% of the population is not
proficient in English.  The bills falsely presume that today's immigrants are
not learning English and thus threaten the primacy of English as our common
language.  Nothing could be further from the truth.  Studies show that
immigrants today are striving to learn English as quickly as possible, as did
immigrants in prior decades.  Classes in English as a second language are
grossly over-subscribed and have lengthy waiting lists.  Immigrants do not
need a patronizing proclamation declaring English the official language.  If
anything, Congress should consider funding efforts to teach English as a
second language, instead of punitive bills that would in effect bar
non-English speakers from receiving many services to which they are entitled.
</p>
<p>     English Only bills are unnecessary.  For all practical purposes, English
is already the common language in the United States.  A GAO study released on
September 20 reveals that fewer than .06% of over 400,000 federal documents
sampled were in a language other than English.  Most of those documents were
issued by agencies of the federal government -- such as HHS, FDA, NIH, and
SSA -- which must reach people in the United States regardless of their
proficiency in English.  It is simply bad policy to prevent, for example, SSA
from communicating with non-English speakers in Puerto Rico who are entitled
to the benefits of programs administered by SSA.  Likewise, it is absurd to
require the Immigration and Naturalization Service to speak only in English
to people who might not be able to understand it.
</p>
<p>     English Only bills would infringe upon important constitutional rights
and legitimize and encourage discrimination against language-minority
residents.  Such bills could interfere with the right to vote by banning
bilingual ballots, or with the education of the nation's children by
restricting instruction in a language that immigrant children can understand.
In addition, legislation that mandates court and administrative proceedings
in English only would severely jeopardize the ability of non-English speakers
to understand the proceedings.  The impact on our elderly citizens, many of
whom need not learn English as a condition of citizenship and for whom
acquisition of English language proficiency is not a real possibility, cannot
be overstated.  We urge you to oppose English Only legislation.
</p>
<p>Sincerely,
<p>Laura W. Murphy, Director, ACLU
<p>Gregory T. Nojeim, Legislative Counsel
<p>Edward M. Chen, Staff Counsel
<P>

<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT12-B27-79</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA083-000584-B027-108</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.aclu.org:80/congress/welflet.html 204.243.96.55 19970213141048 text/html 27421
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Thursday, 13-Feb-97 14:09:29 GMT
Last-modified: Saturday, 27-Jan-96 17:52:03 GMT
Content-length: 27233
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>ACLU n Congress</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<blockquote><img src="/graphics/legishdr.gif">
<P>
October 25, 1995
<P>

Senator William Roth, Jr.
<BR>104 Hart Senate Office Building
<BR>Washington, D.C. 20515
<P>
Dear Senator Roth:
<P>
     The American Civil Liberties Union vigorously opposes the House and
Senate welfare reform bills.  We write to bring to your attention several
provisions of the bills that raise important civil liberties concerns.  We
oppose both versions of this legislation, as they strip the poor of numerous
fundamental rights.  The bills violate the right to equal protection by
targeting vulnerable groups (such as legal immigrants) for disparate
treatment.  They violate the right to privacy by removing privacy protections
found in existing law and by creating new databases of information in the
name of tracking down parents who fail to pay child support.  The Senate bill
would also violate the religious liberty rights of welfare beneficiaries and
taxpayers by funding pervasively sectarian religious institutions and
programs in violation of the Establishment Clause of the First Amendment.  It
also contains an unconstitutional provision designed to curb the political
advocacy of nonprofit organizations participating in welfare programs.  We
urge you to take the following actions in order to attempt to ameliorate
these serious problems:
<P>
     The conference report should embrace the provisions of each bill that
minimize the extent to which aliens are denied benefits for which they have
paid.  Both the House and Senate welfare bills would deny public benefits to
legal immigrants who have paid for them.  ACLU has since the beginning of the
welfare reform process in this Congress opposed legislation to cut off
benefits to immigrants.  Our position has not changed.  Scapegoating legal
immigrants serves no public policy goal.  Legal immigrants come to the United
States to work, to join close family members, and to escape persecution in
their homelands.  They are the people the United States has invited to come,
and to come permanently.  (Undocumented aliens are already ineligible for
most of the targeted programs.)  To cut off access to benefits for public 
housing, lead poisoning in infants, child care and development block grants,
community health centers and a whole host of other programs does not serve
anyone.  In the view of ACLU, the practice of excluding legal immigrants from
public benefits violates their constitutional right to equal protection. To
target legal immigrants because of their vulnerability is simply public
policy.
<P>
     Each of the bills under consideration would deny different classes of
benefits to different classes of aliens.  We strongly urge the conferees to
abandon this misguided approach to welfare reform, and report a bill that
does not bar immigrants from access to federal programs.  At an absolute
minimum, the conferees are urged to select the provisions of each bill that
will minimize the impact of the legislation on aliens.
<P><DL><DD>
     1.  Immigrants should not be barred from federal programs designed to
assist all people in the United States.  Any bar to participation is
objectionable.  At a minimum, the House should recede to the Senate with
respect to the list of federal programs in which immigrants would be able to
participate, and the Senate bill's five-year bar on receipt of benefits
should be removed.  This change in the law would still render most legal
immigrants ineligible for SSI. Under the Senate bill, immigrants would be
barred from SSI, and from all other federally-funded needs-based programs for
five years after their entry into the United States; under the House bill,
immigrants would be barred from SSI, AFDC, Title XX Block Grants, Medicaid
and Food Stamps.  The five-year prospective bar in the Senate bill should be
eliminated.
<P>
     2.  No immigrant should be barred from a federal program.  At a minimum,
the classes of non-citizens exempted from the bar should be maximized by
combining the lists of exempted classes of non-citizens that appears in each
bill.  The Senate bill and the House bill exempt different classes of
non-citizens from the bar to receipt of benefits.  For example, the Senate
bill exempts veterans and their spouses and dependents from the bar  -- but
not active duty service members (and their spouses and dependents), as would
the House bill.  The Senate bill exempts LPR's over age 75 from the bar; the
House bill does not.  The Senate bill exempts victims of domestic violence
from the bar; the House bill does not.  The House bill exempts LPR's too
disabled to pass the naturalization test; the Senate bill does not.  The
Senate bill exempts people who have obtained political asylum from their
repressive country of nationality; the House bill does not.  These exemptions
to the bar to receipt of benefits serve sound public policy goals.  We
recommend, at a minimum, that the two lists of exemptions be combined in the
conference report.
<P>
     3.  The House should recede to the Senate with respect to the list of
programs for which income of a sponsor would be deemed to the alien for
purposes of determining whether the alien meets the needs test.
Approximately 85% of the family-based aliens who immigrate to the United
States are the beneficiaries of affidavits of support from their sponsor.
Deeming the income of the sponsor to the alien, even when that income is in
fact not available to the alien for support, would have the effect of
disqualifying LPR's from the benefits of the programs for which income of
their sponsor is deemed to them.  The House bill would deem the sponsor's
income for all federal, state and local programs; the Senate bill would
except such programs as emergency Medicaid, Child Nutrition Act Programs
including WIC, short term emergency disaster relief, and under the Senate
bill, the LPR's exempted from the bar to SSI would also be exempted from
deeming.  In addition, other programs that form a critical part of the
nation's safety net should be added to the list of excepted programs:
Medicaid, public health services, student assistance and job training.  
<P>
     4.  A sponsor's income should under no circumstances be deemed to a
person after that person becomes a citizen.  The Senate should recede to the
House with respect to the period for which income is deemed, but deeming
should be cut off altogether once the person has become a citizen, or (as
provided in the Senate bill), worked for 40 "qualifying quarters."  Deeming
of income should in all cases end when an LPR becomes a citizen.  This is the
most important immigration-related provision in the bills from a civil
liberties perspective.  If income is deemed passed citizenship, for the first
time in history, the nation will in effect discriminate between native-born
citizens and naturalized citizens with respect to access to needs-based
federal benefits.  A large proportion of naturalized Americans would be
rendered ineligible to participate in these programs because income of their
sponsor would be deemed to them for years after they became naturalized.
Distinguishing between naturalized and native-born Americans in this manner,
even where each has paid taxes to support the benefits they seek to avail
themselves of, raises grave concerns about equal protection.  Further, it is
divisive, and is simply poor public policy.  The notion that deeming should
be cut off after sponsored immigrant earns enough from working to pay taxes
for 40 qualifying quarters should be borrowed from the Senate bill.
<P>
     5.  The types of programs made accessible to undocumented aliens should
be expanded with an eye toward including all programs designed to protect the
public health, and children born to the undocumented through no fault of
their own.  At a minimum, the Senate should recede to the House with respect
to the types of programs accessible to aliens not lawfully present, and the
House should recede to the Senate with respect to the exceptions to the bar
on accessibility.  Under the House bill, aliens not lawfully present would be
barred from all federal means-tested programs; under the Senate bill, the bar
would apply not just to means-tested programs, but to contracts, grants,
loans, and licenses provided or paid for by the federal government.  The
Senate bill excepts from the bar emergency Medicaid, immunizations, treatment
of communicable diseases, short term emergency disaster relief, school
lunches and child nutrition.  These exceptions serve the sound public policy
of protecting us all, and should be adopted in the conference report.  
<P>
     6.  The Senate should recede to the House with respect to verification
of immigration status of applicants.  The Senate bill would require
verification that every person who applies for a Federal benefit is lawfully
present and eligible.  Providers of exempted services under the Senate bill,
such as immunizations and school lunches would be required to verify
immigration status, even though under the Senate bill, aliens not lawfully
present would be eligible to participate in the excepted program.  The
verification requirement will have the effect of putting even the excepted
programs out of the reach of the undocumented.  The verification scheme in
the benefits context would work an immense burden on providers, just as
employer sanctions in the employment context works an immense burden on
employers.  There is no need to turn providers into immigration cops, as was
done to employers.  
</DL>
<P>
The conference should reject the harsh, punitive child exclusion
provisions adopted by the House. The ACLU opposes all child exclusion
policies, as they punish children and are a misguided attempt to coerce
reproductive choices among welfare recipients.  We are pleased that the
Senate soundly rejected the mandatory child exclusions which the House of
Representatives included in its bill.  That version contains three child
exclusions that prohibit states from providing benefits to children born to
families already receiving AFDC, cut off assistance to children born to
single teenage mothers until the mother turns 18, and penalize individual
families when a child's paternity is not established, whether or not the
child's mother has cooperated to establish paternity.  We are heartened that
these mandatory, harsh, punitive provisions were not included in the Senate
bill (although unfortunately the first two are included as state options.) 
<P>
     We ask you to oppose these mean-spirited measures, which in large part
simply punish children for their parents' actions. Moreover, it is entirely
uncertain whether a family cap policy will attain it purported goal--to
reduce the birth rate among welfare recipients.  So far there has been no
reduction in the birth rate of welfare mothers subject to the family cap,
according to preliminary findings from the study of New Jersey's family cap
policy.
<P>
     In addition, many key state and local government organizations, such as
the National Governors Association, the National Conference of State
Legislators, and the National Association of Counties oppose federal mandates
to institute a family cap.   
<P>
     In short, the conference should adopt the Senate version of the bill in
these three areas.  It should also delete the "illegitimacy ratio" provision
included in both bills.
<P>
     Provisions in the Senate bill concerning religious organizations should
be removed.  Sections 102 and 103 of the Senate bill would explicitly permit
the creation of an unprecedented church/government relationship, in which a
pervasively sectarian religious entity could administer a government-funded
welfare program (by giving out monthly checks, providing counseling, etc.) in
an environment replete with religious symbols and activity. If welfare
programs are implemented in such a manner, recipients will undoubtedly be
subject to religious discrimination and could reasonably interpret this
method of disbursement as government endorsement of religion. To avoid this
unconstitutional entanglement between government and religion, these sections
should be deleted.
<P>
     The Supreme Court has explained that government funding of "pervasively
sectarian" institutions raises "a 'substantial' risk that aid to these
religious institutions would, knowingly or unknowingly, result in religious
indoctrination" and would thus be unconstitutional. Bowen v. Kendrick, 487
U.S. 589, 612 (1988). Rather than providing statutory protection against such
constitutional violations, these sections encourage the funding of
pervasively sectarian religious organizations.
<P>
     Although the legislation contains no prohibition on funding pervasively
sectarian institutions, it prohibits the government from requiring a
religious contractor to remove "religious art, icons, scripture or other
symbols" from areas where welfare services are conducted. The legislation
does not provide beneficiaries with judicial recourse for breaches of their
religious liberty; however it affords a cause of action to religious
organizations whose right to participate in government welfare programs has
been violated by a state agency. Furthermore, beneficiaries are not provided
with any notice of their right to object to a religious provider to whom they
are assigned.

<P>
     Also problematic is a provision that would allow organizations to engage
in employment discrimination against employees working on a federally-funded
welfare program. The legislation would allow the organization to require
welfare workers to "adhere to the religious tenets and teachings of [the
religious] organization." Under the bill, such adherence is explicitly
extended to "rules forbidding the use of drugs or alcohol" on or off the job.
<P>
     Although section 103 of the bill prohibits the use of federal contract
funds for "sectarian worship or instruction," it exempts government welfare
vouchers and certificates from the prohibition. It thus permits the direct
use of government funds for religious worship or instruction for
beneficiaries participating in programs in which they receive vouchers or
other in-kind assistance. Furthermore, section 103 does not prohibit the use
of government funds for "proselytizing" activity.
<P>
     In an effort to address some of the Establishment Clause concerns, the
Senate passed the Cohen Amendment, which struck a provision that would have
prohibited states from requiring that a religious organization form a
separate affiliate organization to participate in welfare programs. Although
we are thankful to Senator Cohen for his effort to provide states with
greater control over the disbursement of funds, the amendment does not
completely remedy the bill's serious First Amendment problems.
<P>
     The inclusion of sections 102 and 103 will lead to widespread
Establishment Clause violations throughout the country. We therefore ask you
to exclude these sections of the Senate bill from the conference report.
<P>
     A provision in the Senate bill designed to discourage nonprofit welfare
providers from engaging in political advocacy should be removed.  Section 110
of the Senate bill would require nonprofit organizations that disburse
federal welfare funds to publish a disclaimer on a wide range of the
organization's written and broadcast expression. The disclaimer would state:
"This was prepared and paid for by an organization that accepts taxpayer
dollars." This provision would unconstitutionally chill the protected
expression of, and would impose an unconstitutional condition upon, nonprofit
organizations that participate in welfare programs under the bill.
<P>
     The provision would apply only to section 501(c) organizations. Under
the legislation, the disclaimer must be attached to "any communication that
in any way intends to promote public support or opposition to any policy of a
Federal, State, or local government" through direct mailing, newspaper or
magazine advertising, outdoor advertising, broadcast expression or "any other
type of general public advertising." Any organization engaging in such
expression without including the disclaimer would be declared ineligible to
receive Federal welfare funds for services or disbursement to welfare
recipients.
<P>
     The provision would regulate the majority, if not all, of a nonprofit
organization's expression to its own members and the general public,
including expression activity for restriction, but rather regulates an
organization completely unrelated to the organization's welfare work. The
bill does not merely single out lobbying's expression that "in any way"
promotes public support or opposition to any government policy. 
<P>
     A government-required disclaimer would infringe the constitutional right
to free expression in the form of compelled speech. As the Supreme Court has
explained, the First Amendment protects "both the right to speak freely and
the right to refrain from speaking at all." Wooley v. Maynard, 430 U.S. 705,
714 (1977). Thus, the protections of the First Amendment encompass the
decision of both what to say and what not to say.
<P>
          As in the case of the "Silence America" or Istook Amendment
currently being debated in Congress, this provision will have the effect of
discouraging nonprofit organizations from participating in government
programs. At a time when Congress is seeking to shift many welfare services
to the private sector, it would be unwise to enact disincentives to such
participation by private nonprofit groups.
<P>
     Furthermore, similar to the Istook Amendment, the provision
unconstitutionally regulates expression outside the scope of the federal
program. The government cannot condition the receipt of federal funds on a
private group's agreement to relinquish constitutional rights - especially
the sacred right to free expression.
<P>

     For these reasons we ask that section 110 of the Senate bill not be
included in the conference report.
<P>
     The House should recede to the Senate provisions concerning child
welfare programs. The Senate bill shows great sensitivity to the needs of
abused and neglected children by retaining current federal law governing
children in foster care and those in need of adoption assistance.  The bill
would retain current federal statutes in these areas, (and reauthorizes
CAPTA, the Child Abuse and Prevention Treatment Act) thus leaving intact a
critical safety net for vulnerable children.  Unlike the House approach in
H.R. 4, which repealed important enforceable federal protections for children
in the Adoption Assistance Act and awarded federal funds for these children
in limited block grant amounts, the Senate bill preserves the current
assurances in federal law that guarantee that federal funds are available to
children needing foster care and adoption assistance.  
<P>
     The Senate approach is the correct one.  At a time when Congress
envisions dramatic changes in programs involving AFDC, food stamps, SSI, and
benefits for immigrants, it is dangerous to consider major changes in the
federal programs that serve children at risk.  It is likely that this
population will need additional assistance from child welfare agencies, if
these proposals are enacted, and a block grant scheme will make it less
likely that these abused and neglected children receive the services they
need.
<P>
     The legislation passed by the House would eliminate appropriate
safeguards and accountability in child welfare systems.  The House repealed
the current provisions in the federal Adoption Assistance Act that set basic
standards for child welfare services without proscribing how a state should
meet those standards.  These standards are neither overly prescriptive, nor
are they utopian.  They permit advocates to seek protection for children when
a state does not even develop its own reasonable approach.  Without such
standards, and the right to enforce those standards, children are entirely
without protection.
<P>
     Standards that are enforceable by both HHS and the federal courts are
essential to ensure that children in our child welfare systems remain safe
and receive quality care.  Such standards are also important to make sure
that children do not linger in "foster care drift," that their families
receive necessary services, and that they move expeditiously towards adoption
when appropriate.
<P>
     In addition, the House bill as it is currently drafted calls for states
to receive their child welfare funds as a proportion of a block grant that
equals the federal funds it received for these programs in fiscal year 1993.
We believe that this will result in a marked decrease in federal funds for
many, if not most states and that those states will be forced to spend a high
percentage of block grant funds on foster care maintenance payments for the
ever increasing number of children who are entering our child welfare
systems.  The states will have far fewer dollars to spend on preventing
children from entering foster care and on moving children out of foster care
into permanent placements.  The net result will be that thousands of our
nation's children will linger in foster care for years.
<P>
     Under the current federal statute, states are provided foster care funds
to pay for activities such as social worker training, recruitment of foster
parents, and for the monitoring of foster and group homes.  All of these
essential activities enable states to ensure that children in government
custody are in safe placements, and facilitate the ability of state agencies
to provide permanent placements for these children.  We are fearful that if
these critical components are curtailed because of fiscal constraints, the
due process rights of children in government custody will more likely be
violated, because they will become warehoused in the foster care system and
will be more likely to be placed in unmonitored, and thus potentially unsafe,
placements.

<P>
     This combination of reduced funding and no federal accountability and
standards for children in foster care would put them at grave risk.  
<P>

     The provision in both House and Senate bills that create "Big Brother"
and violate everyone's privacy should be removed. The House bill constitutes
the single greatest movement toward a Big Brother national ID system in
recent years (possibly excepting only the various worker verification
schemes).  While the Senate bill adds certain privacy protections, they
unfortunately are less effective than current law.  Even worse, the Senate
proposal retains the House's anti-privacy provisions.  
<P>
     Both House and Senate bills would still strip states of their discretion
to refuse to use the Social Security Number on drivers licenses (some 40
states now either use another number exclusively or allow an individual to
substitute another number).  The bill would also still require states to use
the Social Security Number for marriage licenses, professional and
occupational licenses, and paternity and child support proceedings.
<P>
     Thus, the bills would have the significant backdoor effect of making the
Social Security Number a universal ID number, something both the American
people and the Congress have long opposed.  The bills would also require all
employers to report the hiring of all new employees to a central registry,
thereby creating a database in each state that would also significantly
encroach on the privacy of all who work.  The Senate bill adds a national
registry of new hires to the state registries. 
<P>
     The National Federation of Independent Business (NFIB) has attacked the
proposal for new-hire registries.  "While the Absent Parent New Hire Director
may sound like good public policy, please recognize this is a new UNFUNDED
federal mandate on small business." (Emphasis in original.)  
<P>
     The bills would also require states to furnish information about
participants' locations to law enforcement agencies, many of which are
notorious for their inability to protect the confidentiality of even their
own criminal justice records.  This failure by government agencies to protect
the confidentiality of their records -- even when required do so by statute
-- is just one reason why the bills' privacy provision, mandating that state
plans must include safeguards against unauthorized disclosure of confidential
information, will inevitably prove inadequate.  Effective privacy protection
lies in not changing the law to increase outsider access to confidential
information.
<P>
      Victims of domestic violence -- who often have to flee into anonymity
in order to escape their abusers -- are among those put at risk by any such
national identification scheme. History demonstrates that the creation of a
database will all but inevitably lead to abuse of the information in it.  The
Senate bill recognizes the importance of protecting this vulnerable
population and added a prohibition against releasing sensitive location
information.  Unfortunately, it is predictable that this protection will
prove inadequate to safeguard against inevitable abuse.  Again, the
development and imposition of the database sets the stage for its eventual
abuse.  Privacy protection lies in not creating an unnecessary database in
the first place.
<P>
     Both House and Senate bills also reduce privacy protections under the
Fair Credit Reporting Act 15 U.S.C. 1681(1970), and the Right to Financial
Privacy Act 12 U.S.C. 3401(1978), and eliminate privacy protections for
participants in the programs, including for example the restriction that
information gathered under the act be used only for purposes connected to
administration of the program.  Once again, the Senate bill makes some
improvement over the House version in some areas, but both the bills still
lack the specific guarantees found in current law against improper use of
information and includes many provisions antithetical to the privacy of both
program participants and all Americans. These privacy concerns, together with
specific recommendations, are addressed at greater length in a joint letter
on privacy being sent to your office from the ACLU and other privacy
advocates.
<P>
     In conclusion, we ask that you help to preserve the fundamental rights
of welfare recipients by taking the actions outlined above.             
<P>
Sincerely,

<P>
Laura W. Murphy, Director
<BR>
Elizabeth Symonds, Legislative Counsel
</blockquote>
<P>
<P>

</center>

<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
