<html><head><title>

</title>
<!JM 1/4/96>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<body>
<blockquote><img src="/graphics/legishdr.gif"><P><P>

Dear Senator:
<P>
The Senate will shortly consider H.R. 2076 the Commerce, Justice, State and
the Judiciary Appropriations bill for FY 1996.  The American Civil Liberties
Union urges you  to oppose measures which taken together will have a
devastating impact on civil liberties.  The following measures are now
included in this appropriations bill.
<P>
<b>Eliminating Affirmative Action to Remedy Past Discrimination</b>
<br>
The ACLU does not believe that this bill is the appropriate vehicle to enact
legislation that would roll back affirmative action even where past
discrimination has been established.  No hearings have been held and no
thorough committee consideration has been given to this legislation.  The
Commerce, Justice, State and Judiciary Appropriations bill contains a
legislative rider that, if enacted, would severely damage Executive Order
11246 on Affirmative Action and wipe out the civil rights policies of the
past seven Republican and Democratic presidents. 
<P>
This amendment would jeopardize equal employment, educational and federal
contracting  opportunities for millions of women and people of color. We urge
you to support efforts to remove this measure from the bill.
<P>
<b>Eliminating Funding for Indigent Prisoners Facing Execution</b>
<br>
On July 26th, the House voted to eliminate all federal funding for
Post-Conviction Defender Organizations (PCDOs).  The PCDOs, formerly known as
Death Penalty Resource Centers, were established by Congress in 1988 to
ensure that adequate legal representation would be provided to indigent death
row inmates for their habeas corpus petitions.  These organizations, which
are now in 20 of the 38 states with the death penalty, are dependent on
federal funding for their continued existence.  The PCDOs currently represent
about half of the nation's 3000 death row prisoners.  Their client base is
ever-increasing as more crimes become death-eligible, and more
constitutionally-suspect convictions are obtained.
<P>
The Senate Appropriations Committee also voted to eliminate funding for the
PCDOs. If the full Senate votes to eliminate funding for the PCDOs, the risk
of executing innocent persons will dramatically increase.  The PCDOs have
played a critical role in uncovering evidence of innocence that was obscured
by constitutional error at trial. Without the assistance of PCDO lawyers and
those they recruit and train, many innocent men and women who are alive today
might be dead. 

It is unrealistic to expect that private law firms or non-profits will be
able to fill the void left by the PCDOs if they are eliminated. First, PCDOs
play a crucial role in recruiting private lawyers for these complex and
difficult cases. Second, once recruited, private lawyers must depend on the
PCDOs for training and expertise. 
<P>
Without the PCDOs, we will again return to the days described by the late
Supreme Court Justice Thurgood Marshall in a 1986 speech at a Federal
Judiciary conference.  Justice Marshall noted that "death row prisoners are
forced into a wild scramble to secure counsel to challenge an execution that
may be no more than a month away.  Enormous time pressure on counsel, in
turn, leads to hastily prepared claims and frantic appeals."
<P>
We must all agree that this situation can not pass for justice consistent
with the ideals embodied in the Constitution. Finally, there has been much
discussion in this Congress about "reforming" the Writ of Habeas Corpus.
Despite differing views in this debate, there was some agreed upon
recognition, that central to the problems perceived on either side is the
problem of inadequate and incompetent counsel.  In this regard, this
appropriations bill takes an enormous step backwards.
<P>
We understand that there may be an attempt to save the Post Conviction
Representation Centers. We urge you to support it.
<P>
<b>Funding to Force the Private Sector to Change Technology to Facilitate
Eavesdropping</b><br>

The ACLU strongly opposes any provision to implement a
big-government-dictated digital telephony program.  The private sector has
installed the switching technology it selected to give its customers
state-of-the-art service.  The digital telephony program would compel the
private sector to change its chosen technology --  solely to make the
potential possibility of spying on its customers easier for federal agents.
This federal disruption of the private sector is unnecessary because, despite
the frequent references to needing this program to fight terrorism, the
government's own statistics reveal that the last known request for a wiretap
in a case of arson, bombing or firearms violation was made in 1988.  This
absence of wiretap requests, despite a rise in the number of such incidents,
shows that law enforcement agencies themselves have in effect "voted with
their feet" in favor of non-wiretap investigative techniques for such crimes
because non-wiretap techniques are more effective.
<P>
The House appropriations bill provided, under FBI salaries and expenses, that
$50,000,000 for expenses related to digital telephony would be available for
obligation "only upon enactment of authorization legislation."  The Senate
Committee amendments strike this requirement and instead appropriates the
funds out of the Violent Crimes Trust Fund without any requirement that
authorization legislation in fact be enacted.  (Page 15, lines 14-19.) 
<P>
The ACLU urges the Senate to reject all funding for expenses related to
digital telephony.  There are many pressing needs, even within the criminal
justice area itself for the $50,000,000, which is itself only a down payment
on a program scheduled to cost at least a half billion dollars.  At a
minimum, the Senate Committee's amendment providing the funds without
requiring enactment of authorization legislation for this controversial
program should be rejected, and the House language requiring authorization
should be reinstated. 
<P><B>
Restricting the Legal Services Program 
</b><BR>
The ACLU has long maintained that the promise of equal protection under the
law cannot be fully realized without a federally funded legal services
program.  Therefore, the ACLU strongly opposes the approach regarding Legal
Services Corporation (LSC) taken by the Senate Appropriations Committee.  The
LSC performs an absolutely indispensable function by increasing access to
quality legal representation for low-income people.  The drastic cuts in
funding and new restrictions placed on the delivery of services  greatly
hampers the ability of low income people to enjoy the benefits of full and
equal access to our legal system.
<P>
Beyond the funding questions, the Senate Appropriations Committee also
reported out a bill that would create categories of speech and litigation
that unfairly discriminate against LSC employees and their clients. The bill
prohibits recipients of legal services funds from handling any cases or
matters that are not on the list of  "qualified legal services" regardless of
the source of the funds. This  places unconstitutional conditions on the
receipt of federal funds and would render legal representation inaccessible
to many poor Americans. It is a well-established principle in First Amendment
jurisprudence that the federal government may not infringe on
constitutionally protected rights beyond the portions of the program which
directly subsist on federal money. In so far as the restrictions on political
expression in the Act affect expenditures of non-federal funds, the
restrictions violate the fundamental rights guaranteed under the First
Amendment. By applying the restrictions unilaterally to all activities the
prohibition goes beyond any compelling government interest and is not the
narrowest way of achieving the stated government purpose.  Without access to
lawyers there is no access to the law itself.  Under this proposal our system
of rules, though purportedly available to all, would in fact be unavailable
to the poor, and therefore profoundly unfair. We call on you to reject these
restrictions in the bill and restore the LSC funding to levels which
accomplish the goal of "minimum access" to legal services for the poor.
<P><B>
Denying Access to the Federal Courts
</b><BR>
Senator Gramm (R-TX) added an amendment to the Commerce, Justice and State
appropriations bill which would greatly restrict the power of state officials
and federal courts to address prison conditions of confinement cases. The
so-called "STOP" bill,  misnamed the "Stop Turning Out Prisoner's Act," would
prevent states from settling prison condition litigation and instead require
a full-blown trial on the merits in every case. It calls for the immediate
termination of all existing settlement agreements. It prevents courts from
issuing  emergency relief in life threatening circumstances, prevents courts
from appointing special masters to assist the court, and calls for post-trial
orders affecting prison conditions to terminate two years after being issued
regardless of whether constitutional violations persist. It also severely
limits the fees that attorneys can recover from work performed while
representing a class of prisoners.
<P>
In addition to being opposed by a broad spectrum of civil rights, civil
liberties, religious and human rights organizations, this measure is opposed
by many experienced corrections officials.  They have said that this proposed
legislation  is an egregious intrusion on the power of state officials to
manage their own affairs. They state further that "STOP" would have a
devastating effect on state official's ability to manage correctional
litigation.
<P>
Senator Hatch or Senator Dole will be offering a substitute but the
substitute will be unsatisfactory as long as it limits access to the federal
courts for classes of litigants.
<P>
There may be efforts to remove the "STOP" measure from the final bill. We
urge you to support those efforts.
<P><B>
Denying Federal Prisoners Reproductive Choice
</B><BR>
The Appropriations Committee also adopted a measure that would deny federal
prisoners reproductive choice. The measure adopted by the Committee would
prevent federal funds from being used to provide abortion services to women
incarcerated in federal prisons.
In 1993, Congress lifted the funding restrictions that for many years had
prohibited the use of federal funds to provide abortion services to women
prisoners except under severely limited circumstances. Unfortunately, when
the House considered its Commerce, Justice and State appropriations bill, it
voted to reinstate the ban, with harsh ramifications for the thousands of
women who are incarcerated in Bureau of Prison facilities.
<P>
Federal prisoners are totally dependent on the Bureau of Prisons for all of
their medical care. Further, these prisoners are not free to work at
remunerative jobs that would enable them to pay for abortion services.
Consequently, this restriction on federal funding for abortions forecloses
the only avenue many women prisoners have for receiving such services.
However, childbirth is not always an easy option. Women prisoners often
receive inadequate prenatal care and are isolated from their family and
community support services. Moreover, they must suffer the devastating loss
of their child who is removed from them shortly after birth.
<P>
When the Senate considers the FY 96 Appropriations bill for Commerce,
Justice, State, we ask you to support the motion to strike this funding ban.
<P><b>
Funding for the Information Infrastructure Matching-Grant Program
</B><BR>
The Committee bill effectively eliminates funding for the Telecommunications
and Information Infrastructure Assistance Program (NTIIAP) of the National
Telecommunications and Information Administration.  Through the NTIIAP
program, government funds are used as seed money to secure matching private
contributions in order to make advanced telecommunications available to
people who do not otherwise have the ability to access the important
information available through such technology.  
<P>
The NTIIAP program has spurred the development of crucial programs for rural
areas, small towns, and low-income populations.  NTIIAP has made possible
programs in high schools, community colleges and universities, public
libraries, and nonprofit community services.  A key First Amendment issue is
whether the emerging world of cyberspace and the Internet, with its wealth of
information resources, will effectively be restricted to a few affluent users
or be at least as broadly accessible as earlier First Amendment media have
been.  The NTIIA program is a small but essential component of current
efforts to provide more widespread access to advanced telecommunications.
This is not a big-government program; every dollar is matched by private
contributions.
<P>
We understand that Senator Kerrey will offer an amendment to restore $18.9
million of the FY96 funding for the NTIIAP program.  We urge you to support
the Kerrey amendment in order to continue this important program.
<B><P>
Other anti-civil liberties measures
</b><BR>
We understand that in addition to the provisions described above, there may
be additional efforts to curtail or turn-back the clock on civil liberties
through the adoption of so-called "anti-crime" proposals. Of particular
concern are proposals that would maintain the unconscionable 100 to 1
disparity in sentencing for crack and powder cocaine which, because of a
disproportionate focus on prosecutions of African-Americans, has a shockingly
disparate impact. Frankly, enough is enough. 
<P>
This appropriations bill has already become a civil liberties nightmare that
should be rejected. If any of these additional measures are adopted, it would
only compound the excess that is so readily apparent.
<P>
In closing, we urge you to correct the civil liberties abuses described above
and to work toward a bill that supports and encourages civil rights and civil
liberties. If these anti-civil liberties measures remain, we ask that you
vote against the entire bill.  
<P>
Sincerely,
<P>
Laura W. Murphy
<BR>Director
</blockquote>
<P>


