<center><h1><i>COMPLAINT</i></h1>

<br>

<b>UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT<BR>
     EASTERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK</b>

<pre><P>                                            
ARMEN ALEGRIA, DINORAH COTO,     
ROBERT DiFILIPPO, MICHAEL DeSANTIS,
             and ROSE MADDEN,              
Plaintiffs,   
 
 v. 

RONALD J. D'ANGELO, Commissioner, 
PAUL  MEJIAS, President, FREDERIC  
M. UMANE, Secretary, WEYMAN A.     
CAREY, Commissioner, DOUGLAS A.    
KELLNER, Commissioner, FERDINAND   
C. MARCHI, Commissioner, SEYMOUR      
SHELDON, Commissioner, GERTRUDE    
STROHM, Commissioner, VINCENT      
J. VILELLA, Commissioner, KATHLEEN
M. WAGNER, Commissioner, and the   
                   NEW YORK CITY BOARD OF ELECTIONS,                       
   Defendants.     
                        
</pre>

<P>
<img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width=95%>
<blockquote>

<h3>                      PRELIMINARY STATEMENT</h3>
</center>
<P>
<pre>
    1.   Plaintiffs bring this civil-rights action to
     challenge conduct of the defendants that has infringed
     and continues to infringe the plaintiffs' constitutional
     rights of free association and free speech.  On January
     4, 1996, the New York City Board of Elections informed
     each plaintiff that their employment as clerks with the
     Board of Elections was being terminated.  The plaintiffs
     lost their jobs solely because they were supporters of
     Senator Robert DiCarlo, the Bay Ridge Republican State
     Senator, and did not support Arthur Bramwell, the Chair
     of the Republican Party in Brooklyn, and Robert J.
     D'Angelo, who became a Commissioner on the Board of
     Elections on or about January 1, 1996.  The defendants'
     actions violated and continue to violate the plaintiffs'
     rights under the First and Fourteenth Amendments to the
     United States Constitution and under Article I, Section 8
     of the Constitution of the State of New York.
     
     
                          JURISDICTION AND VENUE
     
     
          2.   This Court has subject matter jurisdiction over
     the federal claims pursuant to 28 U.S.C.  1331, 1343
     (3-4).  This suit is authorized pursuant to 42 U.S.C.
      1983.  Supplemental jurisdiction is asserted over
     claims arising under Article 1, section 8, of the Consti-
     tution of the State of New York pursuant to 28 U.S.C.
      1367.

          3.   Venue is proper pursuant to 28 U.S.C.  1391(b)
     in that plaintiffs' claim arose in the Eastern District
     of New York

          4.   Jurisdiction to grant declaratory judgment is
     conferred by 28 U.S.C.  2201, 2202.  Injunctive relief
     is authorized by Rule 65 of the Federal Rules of Civil
     Procedure.  An award of costs and attorneys fees is
     authorized pursuant to 42 U.S.C.  1988.
     
     
                              PARTIES
     
     
          5.   Plaintiff Carmen Alegria is a citizen of the
     United States residing in Brooklyn, New York.

          6.   Plaintiff Dinorah Coto is a citizen of the
     United States residing in Brooklyn, New York.

          7.   Plaintiff Robert DiFilippo is a citizen of the
     United States residing in Brooklyn, New York.

          8.   Plaintiff Michael DeSantis is a citizen of the
     United States residing in Brooklyn, New York.

          9.   Plaintiff Rose Madden is a citizen of the
     United States residing in Brooklyn, New York.

          10.  Defendant Ronald J. D'Angelo is a Commissioner
     of the New York City Board of Elections.  His office is
     located at 32 Broadway, New York, New York 10004.  He is
     sued in his official capacity.

          11.  Defendant Paul Mejias is a Commissioner of the
     New York City Board of Elections.  His office is located
     at 32 Broadway, New York, New York 10004.  He is sued in
     his official capacity.

          12.  Defendant Frederic M. Umane is a Commissioner
     of the New York City Board of Elections.  His office is
     located at 32 Broadway, New York, New York 10004.  He is
     sued in his official capacity.

          13.  Defendant Weyman A. Carey is a Commissioner of
     the New York City Board of Elections.  His office is
     located at 32 Broadway, New York, New York 10004.  He is
     sued in his official capacity.

          14.  Defendant Douglas A. Kellner is a Commissioner
     of the New York City Board of Elections.  His office is
     located at 32 Broadway, New York, New York 10004.  He is
     sued in his official capacity.

         15.  Defendant Ferdinand C. Marchi is a Commissioner
     of the New York City Board of Elections.  His office is
     located at 32 Broadway, New York, New York 10004.  He is
     sued in his official capacity.

          16.  Defendant Seymour Sheldon is a Commissioner of
     the New York City Board of Elections.  His office is
     located at 32 Broadway, New York, New York 10004.  He is
     sued in his official capacity.

          17.  Defendant Gertrude Strohm is a Commissioner of
     the New York City Board of Elections.  Her office is
     located at 32 Broadway, New York, New York 10004.  She is
     sued in her official capacity.

          18.  Defendant Vincent J. Vilella is a Commissioner
     of the New York City Board of Elections.  His office is
     located at 32 Broadway, New York, New York 10004.  He is
     sued in his official capacity.

          19.  Defendant Kathleen M. Wagner is a Commissioner
     of the Board of Elections.  Her office is located at 32
     Broadway, New York, New York 10004.  She is sued in her
     official capacity.

          20.  Defendant New York City Board of Elections is
     and at all times relevant to this complaint was an agency
     of the City of New York.
     
     
                          FACTUAL ALLEGATIONS
     
     
          21.  Plaintiff Carmen Alegria commenced employment
     with the Board of Elections on May 11, 1995, as a clerk
     in the Cancellation Department.  In this position, Ms.
     Alegria had responsibility for updating the voter regis-
     tration rolls for Kings County.  She also performed other
     clerical tasks, such as answering the switchboard, on an
     as-needed basis.  As such, Ms. Alegria was neither a
     policymaker nor a confidential employee with the Board of
     Elections.

          22.  Plaintiff Dinorah Coto commenced employment
     with the Board of Elections on August 14, 1995, as a
     clerk in the Cancellation Department.  In this position,
     Ms. Coto had responsibility for the coding and filing of
     newly registered voters for Kings County onto microfilm. 
     She also performed other clerical tasks on an as-needed
     basis.  As such, Ms. Coto was neither a policymaker nor a
     confidential employee with the Board of Elections.

          23.  Plaintiff Robert DiFilippo commenced employment
     with the Board of Elections on July 7, 1995, as a Voting
     Machine Technician.  In this position, Mr. DiFilippo had
     responsibility for the maintenance and repair of voting
     machines that were operated by the Board of Elections. 
     He also performed other clerical tasks on an as-needed
     basis.  As such, Mr. DiFilippo was neither a policymaker
     nor a confidential employee with the Board of Elections.

          24.  Plaintiff Michael DeSantis commenced employment
     with the Board of Elections on July 17, 1995, as a clerk
     in the Registration Department.  In this position, Mr.
     DeSantis had responsibility for processing voter regis-
     trations, change of address and party affiliation, and
     proofing the voter registration rolls for Kings County. 
     He also performed other clerical tasks on an as-needed
     basis.  As such, Mr. DeSantis was neither a policymaker
     nor a confidential employee with the Board of Elections.

          25.  Plaintiff Rose Madden commenced employment with
     the Board of Elections on March 27, 1995, as a clerk in
     the Registration Department.  In this position, her
     primary responsibilities were processing voter registra-
     tions, change of address and party affiliation, and
     proofing the voter registration rolls for Kings County. 
     On November 1, 1995, she was transferred to Election Day
     Operations, where her primary responsibilities were coor-
     dinating the scheduling of election-day inspectors,
     processing applications for temporary election-day em-
     ployees, payroll for election-day workers, and performing
     other administrative tasks associated with election day. 
     Throughout her employment with the Board of Elections she
     also performed other clerical tasks on an as-needed
    basis.  As such, Ms. Madden was neither a policymaker nor
     a confidential employee with the Board of Elections.

          26.  The Board of Elections is made up of ten com-
     missioners, two from each of the five counties that make
     up the City of New York.  For each county, one of the
     commissioners is appointed by the Democratic Party and
     the other is appointed by the Republican Party.

          27.  As of the fall of 1995, George Spanakos was
     serving as the Brooklyn Republican Commissioner of the
     Board of Elections.  Mr. Spanakos was an ally of Robert
     J. DiCarlo, a Republican who is a New York State Senator.

          28.  Each plaintiff is a supporter of Mr. DiCarlo.

          29.  On or about October 5, 1995, Mr. Spanakos was
     unseated as a Board of Elections Commissioner by Arthur
     Bramwell, the Chair of the Republican Party in Brooklyn. 
     Mr. Bramwell then arranged for the appointment of defen-
     dant Ronald D'Angelo as the Brooklyn Republican Commis-
     sioner to the Board of Elections

          30.  On approximately ten to twelve occasions from
     the time plaintiff Michael DeSantis started working at
     the Board of Elections in July 1995 until December 1995,
     Katherine Human, another clerk at the Board of Elections
     and a supporter of Mr. Bramwell, approached Mr. DeSantis
     and asked him to switch his political support from Mr.
     DiCarlo to Mr. D'Angelo and Mr. Bramwell.  She suggested
     that Mr. DeSantis's employment with the Board of Elec-
     tions might be at risk if he refused to switch allegiance.

          31.  In or about July 1995 Katherine Human also ap-
     proached plaintiff Rose Madden and asked her to switch
     her political support from Mr. DiCarlo to Mr. D'Angelo
     and Mr. Bramwell.  Ms. Human suggested that Ms. Madden's
     employment with the Board of Elections might be at risk
     if she refused to switch allegiance.  Ms. Human again
     approached Ms. Madden at least once after July 1995 to
     ask her to switch her political allegiance.

          32.  On or around November of 1995, defendant Ronald
     D'Angelo approached plaintiff Mr. DeSantis and asked Mr.
     DeSantis to stop supporting Mr. DiCarlo and to start
     supporting Mr. D'Angelo and Mr. Bramwell.  Mr. DeSantis
     refused.  Mr. D'Angelo then said, "This could mean your
     job."  Mr. DeSantis persisted in his refusal and reaf-
     firmed his support of Mr. DiCarlo.  At this point, Mr.
     D'Angelo turned and walked away, saying under his breath,
     "You're outta here then."

          33.  In September 1995 Michael C. DiFilippo, the
     father of plaintiff Robert DiFilippo, ran against defen-
     dant Ronald J. D'Angelo to become the Kings County Repub-
     lican Party District Leader for District 47.  In and
     around August or September 1995 an unknown individual
     telephoned the elder Mr. DiFilippo and threatened that if
     he did not drop his challenge to Mr. D'Angelo for the
     leadership of District 47, plaintiff Robert DiFilippo
     would lose his job at the Board of Elections.

          34.  On or about January 1, 1996, Mr. D'Angelo
     assumed his position as a Commissioner on the Board of
     Elections.

          35.  On January 4, 1996, each plaintiff received a
     letter dated January 5, 1996, from Daniel DeFrancesco,
     Executive Director of the Board of Elections, informing
     them that the Board was terminating their employment
     effective January 19, 1996.  Mr. DeFrancesco's letter
     stated in relevant part, "I have been directed by the
     Commissioners of the New York City Board of Elections to
     inform you that by unanimous vote, they have terminated
     your employment as a probationary employee, effective
     January 19, 1996."

          36.  During the tenure of their employment each
     plaintiff had been performing his or her job for the
     Board of Elections in a satisfactory manner, and none of
     the plaintiffs had ever received an unsatisfactory em-
     ployment performance rating.

          37.  On January 17, 1996, plaintiff Carmen Alegria
     received a letter dated January 17, 1996, from Leo A.
     Barile, the Chief Clerk of the Board of Elections in
     response to her earlier request for a letter of recommen-
     dation.  Mr. Barile's letter stated in relevant part
     that, "due to a decision by the Commissioner's [sic], Ms.
     Alegria's position has been terminated."  On information
     and belief, Ms. Alegria's position in fact has been
     filled by a new employee.

          38.  After she received the letter notifying her of
     her termination, plaintiff Dinorah Coto also received a
     letter from Leo Barrile, the Chief Clerk of the Board of
     Elections, in response to her request for a letter of
     reference.  In relevant part, Mr. Berrile's letter stat-
     ed, "Unfortunately, due to circumstances beyond her
     control [Mr. Coto's] employment has been terminated." 
     The letter went on to state, "Ms. Coto was a very compe-
     tent and reliable employee." 

          39.  Upon information and belief, the sole reason
     for each of these terminations was the fact that each
     plaintiff supported Mr. DiCarlo and did not support Mr.
     D'Angelo or Mr. Bramwell.

          40.  Plaintiff Carmen Alegria has been unemployed
     since her termination on January 19, 1996.  This has
     caused her financial hardship, and she is finding it
     increasingly difficult to pay for essentials such as
     food, rent, and utilities.  Her termination is also
     injuring her employment reputation and prevents her from
     associating with her former colleagues at work.  Finally,
     her termination is causing her emotional harm due to the
     limitation on her freedom of speech and freedom of asso-
     ciation, loss of income, loss of medical coverage, and
     the uncertainty of her future employment.

          41.  Plaintiff Carmen Alegria wishes to return to
     her former position at the Board of Elections, but she
     has not reapplied for employment because she believes
     that her support for Mr. DiCarlo will prevent her from
     being reemployed.

          42.  Plaintiff Robert DiFilippo has been unemployed
     since his termination on January 19, 1996.  This has
     caused him financial hardship, and he is finding it
     increasingly difficult to pay for essentials such as
     food, rent, and utilities.  His termination is also
     injuring his employment reputation and prevents him from
     associating with his former colleagues at work.  Finally,
    his termination is causing him emotional harm due to the
     limitation on his freedom of speech and freedom of asso-
     ciation, loss of income, loss of medical coverage, and
     the uncertainty of future employment.

          43.  Plaintiff Robert DiFilippo wishes to return to
     his former position at the Board of Elections, but he has
     not reapplied for employment because he believes that his
     support for Mr. DiCarlo will prevent him from being reem-
     ployed.

          44.  Plaintiff Michael DeSantis has been unemployed
     since his termination on January 19, 1996.  This has
     caused him financial hardship, and he is finding it
     increasingly difficult to pay for essentials such as
     food, rent, and utilities.  His termination is also
     injuring his employment reputation and prevents him from
     associating with his former colleagues at work.  Finally,
     his termination is causing him emotional harm due to the
     limitation on his freedom of speech and freedom of asso-
     ciation, loss of income, loss of medical coverage, and
     the uncertainty of future employment.

          45.  Plaintiff Michael DeSantis wishes to return to
     his former position at the Board of Elections, but he has
     not reapplied for employment because he believes that his
     support for Mr. DiCarlo will prevent him from being reem-
     ployed.

         46.  Plaintiff Rose Madden has been unemployed since
     her termination on January 19, 1996.  This has caused her
     financial hardship, and she is finding it increasingly
     difficult to pay for essentials such as food, rent, and
     utilities.  Her termination is also injuring her employ-
     ment reputation and prevents her from associating with
    her former colleagues at work.  Finally, her termination
     is causing her emotional harm due to the limitation on
     her freedom of speech and freedom of association, loss of
     income, loss of medical coverage, and the uncertainty of
     her future employment.

         47.  Plaintiff Rose Madden wishes to return to her
     former position at the Board of Elections, but she has
     not reapplied for employment because she believes that
     her support for Mr. DiCarlo will prevent her from being
     reemployed.

          48.  Plaintiff Dinorah Coto was unemployed from
     January 19, 1996, until February 20, 1996.  This caused
     her financial hardship, injured her employment reputa-
     tion, and prevented her from associating with her former
     colleagues at work.  Finally, her termination caused her
     emotional harm due to the limitation on her freedom of
     speech and freedom of association, loss of income, and
     the uncertainty of her future employment.
     
     
                    FIRST CAUSE OF ACTION
     
     
          49.  The defendants' retaliatory termination of
     plaintiff Carmen Alegria violated and continues to vio-
     late her rights to freedom of speech and association as
     guaranteed by the First and Fourteenth Amendments to the
     United States Constitution, 42 U.S.C.  1983.
     
      
                    SECOND CAUSE OF ACTION
     
     
          50.  The defendants' retaliatory termination of
     plaintiff Carmen Alegria violated and continues to vio-
     late her rights to freedom of speech and association as
     guaranteed by Article 1, section 8 of the New York State
     Constitution.
     
     
                     THIRD CAUSE OF ACTION
     
     
          51.  The defendants' retaliatory termination of
     plaintiff Robert DiFilippo violated and continues to vio-
     late his rights to freedom of speech and association as
     guaranteed by the First and Fourteenth Amendments to the
     United States Constitution, 42 U.S.C.  1983.
     
     
                     FOURTH CAUSE OF ACTION
     
     
          52.  The defendants' retaliatory termination of
     plaintiff Robert DiFilippo violated and continues to vio-
     late his rights to freedom of speech and association as
     guaranteed by Article 1, section 8 of the New York State
     Constitution.
     
     
                    FIFTH CAUSE OF ACTION
     
     
          53.  The defendants' retaliatory termination of
     plaintiff Michael DeSantis violated and continues to vio-
     late his rights to freedom of speech and association as
     guaranteed by the First and Fourteenth Amendments to the
     United States Constitution, 42 U.S.C.  1983.
      
                     SIXTH CAUSE OF ACTION
      
     
          54.  The defendants' retaliatory termination of
     plaintiff Michael DeSantis violated and continues to vio-
     late his rights to freedom of speech and association as
     guaranteed by Article 1, section 8 of the New York State
     Constitution.
     
     
                     SEVENTH CAUSE OF ACTION
     
     
          55.  The defendants' retaliatory termination of
     plaintiff Rose Madden violated and continues to violate
     her rights to freedom of speech and association as guar-
     anteed by the First and Fourteenth Amendments to the
     United States Constitution, 42 U.S.C.  1983.
     
     
                      EIGHTH CAUSE OF ACTION
     
     
          56.  The defendants' retaliatory termination of
     plaintiff Rose Madden violated and continues to violate
     her rights to freedom of speech and association as guar-
     anteed by Article 1, section 8 of the New York State
     Constitution.
     
     
                     NINTH CAUSE OF ACTION
     
     
          57.  The defendants' retaliatory termination of
     plaintiff Dinorah Coto violated her rights to freedom of
     speech and association as guaranteed by the First and
     Fourteenth Amendments to the United States Constitution,
     42 U.S.C.  1983.
     
     
                    TENTH CAUSE OF ACTION
     
     
          58.  The defendants' retaliatory termination of
     plaintiff Dinorah Coto violated her rights to freedom of
     speech and association as guaranteed by Article 1, sec-
     tion 8 of the New York State Constitution.
     
          WHEREFORE, the plaintiffs request that this Court:
     
     
     (1)  Assume jurisdiction over this action;

     (2)  Issue a preliminary injunction on behalf of plain-
               tiffs Carmen Alegria, Robert DiFilippo, Michael
               DeSantis, and Rose Madden directing the defendants
               and their successors, their agents, and employees
               and all persons acting in concert with them who
               obtain notice of the order:

          a)   to cease any policy or practice that interferes
                    with these plaintiffs' First Amendment rights
                    of free speech and association;

          b)   to restore these plaintiffs to their respective
                    positions with the Board of Elections pending
                    the determination of the constitutionality of
                    the defendants' actions;

          c)   to restore to these plaintiffs all accrued wag-
                    es, benefits and compensatory time he or she
                    has lost and will continue to lose as a result
                    of the defendants' actions;

          d)   to take no retaliatory actions on account of
                    plaintiffs' exercise of their rights of free
                    speech and association.

     (3)  Enter a declaratory judgment declaring that defen-
               dants' policies and practices have violated and
               continue to violate plaintiffs' rights under the
               First and Fourteenth Amendments to the Constitution
               of the United States, and Article I,  8 of the
               Constitution of the State of New York;

     (4)  Issue a permanent injunction on behalf of all the
               plaintiffs directing the defendants and their suc-
               cessors, their agents, and employees and all persons
               acting in concerting with them who obtain notice of
               the order:

          a)   to cease any policy or practice that interferes
                    with the plaintiffs' exercise of their rights
                    of free speech and association;

          b)   to expunge from each plaintiff's personnel
                    records any mention of the termination;

          c)   to take no retaliatory actions on account of
                    plaintiffs' exercise of their rights of free
                    speech and association.

     (5)  Award plaintiff compensatory and punitive damages
               against defendants.

     (6)  Grant plaintiff costs and reasonable attorneys fees
               pursuant to 42 U.S.C.  1988.

     (7)  Grant such other and further relief as this Court
               deems just and proper.
     
     
                              Respectfully submitted,
     
     
                         NEW YORK CIVIL LIBERTIES
                           UNION FOUNDATION
     
     
                         By: ___________________________
                             WAYNE OUTTEN (WO-0638)
                             Lankenau, Kovner & Kurtz
                             1740 Broadway - 25th Floor
                             New York, New York  10019
                             (212) 489-8230
     
                             NORMAN SIEGEL (NS-6850)
                             132 West 43rd Street
                             New York, New York  10036
                             (212) 382-0557
                             Attorneys for Plaintiffs
     
     
     

Dated March 5, 1996


</blockquote>
