<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -- 06/03/96: Mississippi Mother Wins School Prayer
Challenge Before U.S. Judge</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">Mississippi Mother Wins School Prayer Challenge Before U.S.
Judge</H2>
<P><B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>Monday, June 3, 1996</B></P>
<P>OXFORD, Miss. -- In a closely-watched school prayer case, a federal judge
today ruled that a Mississippi public school system had violated the First
Amendment rights of a mother whose children had to sit through religious
teachings in the classrooms. </P>
<P>U.S. District Court Judge Neal B. Biggers, Jr. ruled that Pontotoc County
public schools had violated the separation between church and state by
broadcasting devotionals over the intercom system and conducting Bible studies
classes for students in grades K through 8.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;The Bill of Rights was created to protect the minority from tyranny of
the majority,&quot; said Judge Biggers, responding to the school's argument that
the prayers should continue because a majority of students and parents are in
favor of the practice.  &quot;To say that the majority should prevail simply

because of its numbers is to forget the purpose of the Bill of Rights.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The American Civil Liberties Union of Mississippi, which brought the case
with People For the American Way, said the ruling was a sound affirmation of the
Establishment Clause, which protects religious liberty while prohibiting the
government from imposing a particular religion.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;Public schools have no business using taxpayer's dollars to force a
particular religion on its students,&quot; said David Ingebretsen, Executive
Director of the ACLU of Mississippi.  &quot;This ruling reaffirms the long-
standing principle of separating church and state.  School officials should heed
the ruling and respect the religious freedom of their students.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The plaintiff in the case, Lisa Herdahl, was equally insistent: &quot;Parents
and kids should be able to decide for themselves if they want to go to Sunday
school, or what church or synagogue they want to attend.  They shouldn't have to
battle that out in court.&quot;</P>
<P>Herdahl brought suit in December 1994 after school officials at the North
Pontotoc Attendance Center refused her request to discontinue the coercive
religious practices.  When news of her request got out, she and her five school
children, ages 5 to 15, were harassed and ostracized in their small town of
Ecru, Miss. </P>
<P>In the classroom, a teacher put headphones over the ears of Herdahl's
7-year-old son, Jason, to block out the morning prayers on the public address
system, which led to even more taunting and teasing.  Her son David, 11, was
branded a &quot;devil worshipper&quot; by fellow students after a teacher told
the class that David didn't participate in Bible class because he &quot;doesn't
believe in God.&quot;</P>
<P>In April 1995, Judge Biggers issued a preliminary injunction ordering school
officials to halt the morning devotionals and Bible classes.  The case went to a
three-day trial in March of this year , where witnesses also testified that a
group of local Protestant churches recommended and paid for instructors to teach
the Bible classes.</P>
<P>Today's ruling makes the injunction against the school permanent.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;This decision upholds the principle that government should not
interfere in matters of people's religion, but that it should be left up to the
children, their parents, their churches and their God,&quot; said Rob McDuff,
one of the attorneys for the Herdahls. &quot;As we have argued all along,
children are free to pray in school, but they should not have certain prayers or
religious views forced on them while they are a captive audience.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;If religious liberty means anything, it means that public schools
should not dictate the religious beliefs of students,&quot; said the ACLU's
Ingebretsen.  &quot;Religious liberty should not be suspended simply because a
majority of people in a school district adhere to one religion.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
