<HEAD>
<TITLE> ACLU News Wire -2/3/97 Fired Colorado Teacher Wins Appeal</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">

<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/newshdr.gif">

<P><TT>February 3, 1997: Fired Colorado Teacher Wins Appeal
</TT></P>

<P></P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/graphics/rbline.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<P><TT>DENVER -- A teacher who was fired partly for showing his students a controversial film by Italian director Bernardo Bertolucci has been ordered reinstated by the Colorado Court of Appeals.</TT></P>

<P><TT>According to a report in the Denver Post, the court said that the Jefferson County School District did not give teacher Al Wilder clear prior notice of policies he was to follow in showing such films, so that the firing violated his First Amendment right to to choose how to teach his course, a senior Debate and Logic class.</TT></P>

<P><TT>The court said that it wasn't extending &quotblanket constitutional protection&quot to teachers to choose any materials they like, the Post said. &quotSchool officials may properly exercise control over school-sponsored expression as long as their actions are reasonably related to legitimate pedagogical concerns,&quot wrote Appeals Judge Daniel M. Taubman in a 3-to-0 decision.</TT></P>

<P><TT>But school boards cannot regulate the showing movies such as 1900 &quotin the absence of clear prior notice that such action is prohibited,&quot and Wilder did not get that, the court said.</TT></P>

<P><TT>Commenting on the decision, ACLU of Colorado Legal Director Mark Silverstein said the court &quotflatly rejected the school board's argument that high school teachers had no First Amendment rights whatsoever.&quot</TT></P>

<P><TT>&quotBy restoring Al Wilder's job and rejecting the school board's extremist position, the court delivered an encouraging victory for academic freedom and the First Amendment,&quot Silverstein said.</TT></P>

<P><TT>During an eight-day administrative hearing in the Spring of 1996, an ACLU cooperating attorney served as co-counsel for Wilder along with an attorney from the Colorado Education Association. The ACLU filed an amicus brief in the appellate court.
</TT></P>



</BLOCKQUOTE>




<P></P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A></CENTER>
