<HEAD>
<TITLE> ACLU News Wire -2/3/97 Divided California High Court
Allows Injunctions to Restrict Gangs</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">

<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/newshdr.gif">

<P><TT>February 3, 1997: Divided California High Court
Allows Injunctions to Restrict Gangs
</TT></P>

<P></P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/graphics/rbline.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<P><TT>SAN FRANCISCO -- The California Supreme Court has ruled that cities can prohibit suspected gang members from engaging in legal activities such as associating on street corners or annoying residents.</TT></P>

<P><TT>In a decision that the Los Angeles Times said divided the justices and sparked flaming rhetoric, the state high court said cities may continue to use public nuisance laws to obtain injunctions that prevent suspected gang members from engaging in otherwise legal activities.</TT></P>

<P><TT>The ruling, overturning a Court of Appeal decision, upheld a San Jose injunction that barred 38 suspected Latino gang members from &quotstanding, sitting, walking, driving, gathering, or appearing anywhere in public view&quot with each other in a four-block neighborhood, the Times said.</TT></P>

<P><TT>Writing for the court, Justice Janice Rogers Brown said that &quotLiberty unrestrained is an invitation to anarchy. Freedom and responsibility are joined at the hip.&quot</TT></P>

<P><TT>Justice Stanley Mosk, writing in dissent, chastised the court for depriving &quotsimple rights to a group of Latino youth who have not been convicted of a crime.&quot</TT></P>

<P><TT>The case arose, the Times said, after the San Jose city attorney's office filed a lawsuit under a public nuisance law and obtained a court injunction in 1993 prohibiting alleged gang members from associating in a neighborhood that said it had been terrorized by a Latino gang.</TT></P>

<P><TT>The ACLU of Northern California challenged the injunction on behalf of 11 of the alleged gang members, and the state Court of Appeal in San Jose struck down all portions that prohibited legal activities.</TT></P>

<P><TT>ACLU cooperating lawyer Amitai Schwartz, who argued the case against the injunctions, told the Times that Justice Brown injected &quother political philosophy&quot into the opinion.</TT></P>

<P><TT>&quotWhat this court really did was give short shift to any constitutional restraints at all,&quot Schwartz said. &quotIt is sort of a green light for making the courts into an adjunct of the police.&quot</TT></P>

<P><TT>He told the Times that the ruling would prompt a proliferation of efforts to use public nuisance laws to ban all sorts of conduct, even outside the gang context.</TT></P>

<P><TT>&quotWhat struck me was the lack of restraint,&quot Schwartz said, adding that the ACLU is considering appealing the ruling to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</TT></P>



</BLOCKQUOTE>




<P></P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A></CENTER>
