<HEAD>
<TITLE> ACLU News Wire -2/7/97 Pittsburgh Public Defenders Under Fire </TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">

<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/newshdr.gif">

<P><TT>February 7, 1997: Pittsburgh Public Defenders Under Fire
</TT></P>

<P></P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/graphics/rbline.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<P><TT>PITTSBURGH -- David Franklin Holmes III is, as the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette put it, no saint. His criminal record includes a five-year stint in federal prison for receiving stolen property.</TT></P>

<P><TT>But Holmes paid an unexpectedly stiff penalty for a suspected drunken driving incident last year. Facing a possible two-day jail sentence if convicted, he spent 82 days behind bars because of a series of apparent foul-ups and inaction by the Allegheny County public defender's office.</TT></P>

<P><TT>Now, the Post-Gazette says, Holmes is being added as a plaintiff in a class-action lawsuit filed against the county by the ACLU of Pittsburgh. The suit, filed in September, alleges that inadequate staffing and equipment left the public defender's office unable to fuilfill its constitutional mandate of providing legal representation to poor people.</TT></P>

<P><TT>&quotThe system is a mess, an absolute mess,&quot Vic Walczak, Executive Director of the ACLU's Pittsburgh chapter, told the Post-Gazette.</TT></P>

The many mistakes made by the Public Defenders office with Holmes, Walczak said, was an extreme example of the problems plaguing the agency. But, he added, it is commonplace for public defenders to meet their clients only minutes before their trials, and to go in poorly prepared.</TT></P>

<P><TT>The public defenders office's budget has been trimmed by more than $400,000 since 1994, the Post-Gazette said.</TT></P>

<P><TT>&quotIt's not that they are bad lawyers,&quot Walczak told the paper. &quotThey are so neutered that it is impossible for them to practice constitutionally adequate criminal law.&quot 
</TT></P>



</BLOCKQUOTE>




<P></P>
