<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Spring 1995 - "Going Forward" by Ira Glasser </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<blockquote>
<img src="/graphics/libraryhdr.gif">
<b><h1>Going Forward</h1></b>
<i>by Ira Glasser</i><br>
<font size=-1>Executive Director of the ACLU</font>
<br>
<hr>
<br>
     On the threshold of a new century, the ACLU finds itself in an era of explosive technological advancement and economic restructuring.  The breathtaking pace of change has triggered dramatic economic dislocations and produced a volatile social climate that, unfortunately, is far more hospitable to the ACLU's enemies than to civil libertarians.  This climate promises to test us severely.
<P>
     The nations of the Western world have seen such tumultuous and unstable times before.  Throughout the 1800s, as the industrial revolution rolled inexorably across, first, Europe and then the United States, the everyday lives of millions were upended.  And before the comforts, conveniences and prosperity generated by industrialization had the effect of raising nearly everyone's standard of living, untold numbers of people suffered, resisted, rioted against, and struggled to adapt to, economic marginalization, abject poverty, long hours in factories, brutal working conditions and gross social inequities.  This turbulence gave rise to a mean-spirited and punitive climate, in which repressive, anti-libertarian measures directed against working people and the poor were not only tolerated but welcomed.
<P>
     Today, as yesterday, the mood of ordinary Americans is troubled, and understandably so. During the 1960s, a time of relative affluence, most American parents fully expected their children's economic prospects to be far better than their own.  The natural companion of this optimism about the future was a generosity of spirit that could at least accommodate, and even applaud, both the expansion of civil liberties and programs aimed at reducing poverty.
<P>
     During the past 20 years, however, the nation has seen a sharp rise in wage inequality. In 1979, white men with a college education earned 30 percent more than white men without a college degree.  By 1989, that disparity had increased to 74 percent.  At the same time, manufacturing jobs declined sharply, while service jobs -- often requiring considerable technological education and skills -- increased.  Many people fell by the wayside of a labor market that no longer needed them.  Two wage earners became necessary for a family to earn what only one person had earned in the past.  Underemployment and temporary employment became fixtures on the landscape, with the result that many families, despite their dual income efforts, found they could not afford health care or higher education for their children.  Public opinion surveys began to register the public's growing belief that children would be worse off than their parents.
<P>
     The fear, anger and despair engendered by these conditions of economic insecurity and anxiety about the future have rendered many vulnerable to the influence of political pandering that scapegoats poor people, immigrants, people of color and feminists as the major sources of economic and moral adversity in American life.  Others, seeing limited choices and the gains to be gotten from an illicit marketplace enabled by drug prohibition, have opted for lives of crime.  And, of course, as criminal violence becomes more random and unpredictable, the public's fear and rage grow.
<P>
     Talk-radio demagogues, identifying with the fear and rage, have converted it into nostalgia for a past when female and black and gay people were excluded from the competition for finite resources.  As for our political leaders, instead of confronting grass roots concerns squarely and pursuing real solutions to real problems, they have let the problems fester, the better to exploit them for their own electoral ends.
<P>
     Most ominous for civil libertarians is the fact that some of our leaders have seized upon the American people's current temper as a mandate to downsize the Constitution.  Using public anxiety and anger as a scalpel to excise rights they never supported, these neo-authoritarian backlashers are bent on erasing the achievements of civil liberties' golden age -- that 20-year period between 1954,  when the U.S. Supreme Court ruled in the historic case of Brown v. Board of Education, and 1973  when it handed down Roe v. Wade.      The New Authoritarians have not been subtle.  They have called for constitutional amendments that would permit governmental sponsorship of religion and punishment of people who disrespect the flag.  They have called for laws that would permit and encourage warrantless searches and seizures; end affirmative action remedies for race and gender discrimination; deny women the right to choose abortion; deny people whose rights have been violated effective access to court remedies, and punish the children of unemployed parents without addressing the lack of jobs, education and job training.
<P>
     The ACLU has heard the message loud and clear.  The very essence of American liberty is at risk from reactionary forces, whose strategy is to exploit, for their own dubious purposes, the very real pain and travail experienced by millions of Americans.  The difficult challenge before us for the forseeable future is to shepherd the original "Contract With America" -- the Billof Rights -- through this latest trial by fire, making sure that it is not consumed, making sure that when this trial has passed the Constitution still stands, proud and enduring.  To that end, we pledge our commitment to pursuing litigation, legislative and public education initiatives that will keep the flame of liberty burning into the next millenium.
<p>
<hr>
</blockquote>
<center>
<A HREF="/library/newltr.html">Newsletter Index</A>
