<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT12-B27-109</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA083-000584-B026-272</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.aclu.org:80/congress/firstamend.html 204.243.96.55 19970213140844 text/html 11075
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Thursday, 13-Feb-97 14:07:28 GMT
Last-modified: Saturday, 27-Jan-96 17:52:03 GMT
Content-length: 10887
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head><title>First Amendment Threats</title>
<!JM 1/4/95>
</head>
<body bgcolor=#FFFFFF>
<center>
<img src="/graphics/legishdr.gif">
<font color="#ff0033"><h1>First Amendment Threats</h1></font>
<P>
</center>
<P>
<P><blockquote>
<a href="#issue"><h3>Issue Introduction</a></h3>
<a href="#threats"><h3>Specific Concerns</a></h3>
<h3><a href="#points">Talking Points</a></h3>

<P>
<a name="issue">
<P></blockquote><img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width="100%"><blockquote><P><h3>Introduction</h3></a>
<P>
The First Amendment to the United States Constitution is often characterized
as a first among equals.  Its protections guaranteeing free speech, free
press and free association, and its twin guarantees of religious liberty and
church-state separation are the cornerstones of American society.  Without
the First Amendment, we would not enjoy the other liberties and freedoms
guaranteed by the Bill of Rights.
<P>
Yet this bedrock of American tradition is under siege as perhaps never
before.  The 104th Congress is expected to consider two proposals that would,
if adopted, rewrite the interpretation of the First Amendment as we've come
to know it and forever rend the fabric of our nation.  One proposal would
shred the religious liberty provision and Establishment Clause of the First
Amendment. Both may well pass.  A second one, already introduced in both
Houses of Congress, would outlaw "desecration" of the flag.  Both must be
defeated.
<P>
Other legislation (statutory proposals as compared to constitutional
amendments) has been introduced this year that would also, if passed,
significantly damage First Amendment rights.  This legislation includes a
school voucher proposal that would let federal funds be used to pay the
tuition of eligible students at private sectarian schools.  In addition, a
Democratic Senator from Nebraska is pushing legislation that would
criminalize certain First Amendment-protected communications deemed
"lascivious" or "indecent" even when made in private between consenting
adults (even between spouses).

<a name="threats">
<P></blockquote><img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width="100%"><blockquote><P>
<h3>Specific Concerns</h3>
<a name="pray"><P>
<b><i>1. Organized Prayer Amendments</i></b>     
<P>
There are now several proposals that reopen yet another emotionally charged
issue: organized public school prayer.  Our bottom line remains the same:
there is no need to amend the Constitution.  The First Amendment strikes the
proper balance between protecting religious liberty in the face of tremendous
religious diversity, and maintaining the separation of church and state.  It
would be dangerous and unwise to disturb this delicate balance.
<P>
No one who truly cares about religious liberty would ever want the
government, including public school officials, to tell our children when,
where, with whom and how they should pray.  By ending the constitutional
separation between church and state, a school prayer amendment would turn our
schools into arenas of religious rivalries.  Getting the government involved
in establishing the ground rules for selecting Baptist prayers, Catholic
rituals or Muslim prayers is a prescription for conflict.  Either religion
will be drained of all meaning in an attempt to avoid conflict, or
divisiveness will be inevitable.  Either way, it will be bad for religion and
bad for religious freedom.  Most Americans who favor prayer in public schools
imagine their own form of prayer.  But will they be happy if their children
are forced to submit to forms of prayer that are not their own?  
<P>
<a name="school">
<P><center><img src="../graphics/redline.gif"></center><P>
<b><I>2. School Vouchers</b></i>
<P>

The Christian Coalition's Contract with the American Family endorses S.618,
the Low-Income School Choice Demonstration Act, which would allow use of
federal funds to pay tuition and expenses of low-income children at private
schools, including parochial schools.  Additionally, in the House, an
"Education Reform" block grant bill will likely be introduced later this
month that would allow an undetermined amount of federal dollars to go to
religious schools through state-initiated voucher plans.  The ACLU vehemently
opposes all such school voucher proposals, because aid to religious schools
invariably advances the institutions' religious mission, thereby violating
the principles of separation of church and state and government neutrality
toward religion, as set forth in the Establishment Clause of the First
Amendment.
<P>
It is ironic that the same Congress that is intent on slashing funding for
worthy programs and on downsizing government is considering spending $30
million a year to subsidize private parochial schools.  Rather than proffer
simplistic solutions such as private school vouchers, Congress should address
the substantial disparity in educational resources and assure equal
educational opportunity to low-income communities.

<a name="flag">
<P><center><img src="../graphics/redline.gif"></center><P>

<b><i>3.  Flag "Desecration"</b></i>   
<P>
This proposed Constitutional amendment would outlaw burning or otherwise
harming the flag as part of political protest.  This is not a conservative or
liberal issue.  It goes to the heart of what this country and the flag stand
for.  When the Supreme Court upheld the First Amendment right to burn the
flag as a form of political protest, the majority included conservatives,
like Justices Scalia and Kennedy, as well as liberals.  They understood that
the First Amendment is indivisible and that the flag stands for freedom --
including the freedom to burn it.
<P>
A poignant example: 25 years ago, after James Meredith was shot during a
civil rights march in the South, a black man named Sidney Street burned a
flag on a street corner in Harlem in protest.  If Meredith could be shot
while marching for racial equality, he said, we did not need the flag;
America's ideals had gone up in smoke.  If Street had used only words to
communicate his message, few would have heard him.  But because he spoke
symbolically, by burning the flag, his protest was captured on television and
his message reached millions. 
<P>
Today many in Congress and among the electorate would criminalize Street's
message.  They seek to honor the flag.  But in proposing to begin unraveling
the First Amendment, they desecrate what the flag represents, and what
hundreds of thousands of Americans have heroically died to defend.

<a name="tv">
<P><center><img src="../graphics/redline.gif"></center><P>
<b><i>4.  Television Violence</b></i>
<P>
Both the House and Senate telecommunication bills include amendments
mandating the installation of automatic blocking technology, or a "V-chip,"
in new televisions.  Once activated, the V-chip would automatically block
programs from reception based on an encoded rating transmitted along with the
television program.  The ACLU opposes the V-chip initiatives, partly because
both versions of the legislation would authorize a government role in setting
the guidelines for the rating of content.
<P>
In early August, 1995, the Senate Commerce Committee approved a bill
introduced by Senator Ernest F. Hollings of South Carolina that would
prohibit the transmission of "violent video programming" on broadcast and
cable television during hours when children are likely in the viewing
audience.  The legislation assigns  to the Federal Communication Commission
the task of defining both violence and the appropriate times for the ban.
<P>
Although the ACLU supports the rights of private, non-industry individuals
and associations to advise parents about television content, government
rating systems and government-controlled bans on expression would violate the
First Amendment.  Violent expression enjoys the highest degree of
constitutional protection, and the decision as to what violent expression is
appropriate for children should be made by parents, not the federal
government.
<a name="political">
<P><center><img src="../graphics/redline.gif"></center><P>
<b><i>5. Political Advocacy</b></i>
<P>
An amendment added to the House Labor, Health and Human Services, Education
Appropriations Bill by Representative Jim Istook of Oklahoma would set a cap
on the amount of "political advocacy" a nonprofit organization receiving
federal grants could engage in.  The definition of "political advocacy" under
the legislation includes not simply lobbying, but also participation in
political campaigns, the carrying on of "propaganda," and participation in
agency proceedings or litigation in which the government is a party.  More
serious restrictions were also placed in the appropriations bill funding the
Legal Services Corporation.
<P>
The ACLU strongly opposes these attempts to condition the receipt of federal
funds on the relinquishment of constitutional rights.  Such legislation would
impose severe restrictions on a nonprofit organization's entire First
Amendment activity, rather than on its the implementation of a specific,
federally-funded program.
<P>
<a name="points">
<P></blockquote><img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width="100%"><blockquote><P>
<h3>Talking Points</h3> 
<DL>
<DD>
<LI>Students and teachers already have the right to pray individually in school;
the First Amendment grants this right.  

<P><LI>
Congress must, once again, reject the proposed amendment on flag
"desecration."  We recognize that this will not be easy.  Opinion polls
suggest that the American public widely supports the amendment, and
Representatives and Senators are likely to fear that they will be hurt
politically if they don't fall in line.  But we must remind our legislators
that this is a time for leadership and courage.  As Tom Paine might have
reminded us, true patriotism is refreshed by references to its first
principles.

<P><LI>
To realize the liberating potential of the information superhighway, Congress
must ensure that interactive technologies enhance rather than stifle
democratic values like freedom of speech. To do anything less would be to
thwart the tradition of robust debate in this country.

<P><LI>
Parents, not the federal government, should decide what television
programming is appropriate for their children.
<P><LI>
Restrictions on the political advocacy activity of nonprofit organizations
would remove important voices from the political debate -- the voices of
common people with concerns about key issues.
</DL></blockquote>

<P>
<img src="../graphics/redline.gif" width="100%">
<P>



<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
