HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Thursday, 13-Feb-97 14:19:24 GMT
Last-modified: Saturday, 27-Jan-96 17:52:03 GMT
Content-length: 6116
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head><title>Counterrorism</title>
<!JM 1/4/95>
</head>

<body bgcolor=#FFFFFF>
<center>
<img src="/graphics/legishdr.gif">
<font color="#ff0033"><h1>Counterterrorism</h1></font>
<P>
</center>

<P>
<P><blockquote>
<a href="#issue"><h3>Issue Introduction</a></h3>
<a href="#threats"><h3>Specific Concerns</a></h3>
<a href="#points"><h3>Talking Points</a></h3>
<a href="terract2.html"><h3>Executive Summary of House Terrorism Bill</a></h3>
<a href="terract.html"><h3>Civil Liberties Implications of Anti-Terrorism Act</a></h3>

<P>
<a name="issue">
<P></blockquote><img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width="100%"><blockquote><P>
<h3>Introduction</h3></a>
<P>
In April the ACLU distributed a background briefing on an important, though
low-profile, Clinton Administration proposal that we feared would slip
through Congress without much public attention. That proposal, the Omnibus
Counter terrorism Act of 1995, would, we said, eviscerate key elements of the
Constitution and the Bill of Rights.
<P>
The tragic bombing of the federal building in Oklahoma City, of course, drew
the attention of lawmakers, the media, and the American people to that and
other proposals to fight terrorism, and to the proposals' civil liberties
implications. Suddenly, much of Washington focused its attention on what
steps the government should take to prevent further terrorist attacks in this
country. Suddenly, the American public was being told that Congress needed to
approve an extensive list of measures that would facilitate FBI infiltration
and eavesdropping on any domestic group by lowering the threshold of evidence
needed to justify such invasive measures. 
<P>
The President urged Congress to
move speedily, and on June 7, the Senate passed a bill that would allow the
government to deport aliens who have been convicted of no crime, based on
information known only to the government; allow the Executive to declare any
foreign group a "terrorist" organization; bar its members from coming to the
United States; prohibit contributions to the legal, non-violent and
charitable activities of the organization, and bar effective judicial review
of such proclamations.  Importantly, the Senate bill contains a draconian
provision couched as "reform" of habeas corpus that would severely impair a
prisoner's ability to secure federal court review of a the constitutional
infirmities upon which a conviction may be based.

<a name="threats">
<P></blockquote><img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width="100%"><blockquote><P>
<h3>Specific Concerns</h3>
<P>
The House is considering legislation similar to that passed by the Senate.
The House version has been held up by freshmen and libertarian Republicans
concerned that the bill would concentrate too much power in the hands of
federal law enforcement officials, leading to selective prosecution on
account of political beliefs.  They are also concerned with the bill's
wiretapping provisions, the manner in which it gives the FBI broad access to
consumer information even when it has no evidence of criminality, and the
extent to which the bill would federalize state law. 

Liberal Democrats also oppose the bill because of these concerns, and the
general threat the bill poses to civil liberties.  Because of this unusual
alignment of conservative Republicans and liberal Democrats, we have a real
chance of either defeating the bill, or forcing substantial changes in the
legislation.

<a name="groups">
<P><center><img src="../graphics/redline.gif"></center><P>
The ACLU is particularly concerned about the way this bill allows the
Executive to designate groups as "terrorist."  The federal judiciary has
rarely, if ever, rejected such an executive determination.  And once an
organization was so designated as terrorist, its representatives would be
barred from entering the United States, and American citizens who contribute
to peaceful activities of such groups -- such as helping fund an African
National Congress speaking tour by Nelson Mandela (assuming the ANC were so
designated) -- would be subject to felony prosecution and lengthy prison
sentences.

In addition, aliens accused of raising funds for the legal, charitable
activities of such designated organizations but convicted of no crime could
be deported based on secret information they could not challenge.
<P>
<a name="FBI">

<P><center><img src="../graphics/redline.gif"></center><P>
Finally, after Oklahoma City, we saw many Members of Congress calling for the
expansion of FBI investigative authority.  FBI officials said they planned to
"reinterpret" the Attorney General's guidelines on investigations into
domestic terrorism.  We have yet to see this reinterpretation, but remain
deeply concerned that any changes in the Attorney General's guidelines could
lead to law enforcement authorities investigating individuals or
organizations without any reasonable criminal predicate. 
<P>
<a name="points">
<P></blockquote><img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width="100%"><blockquote><P>
<h3>Talking Points</h3> 
<DL>
<DD>
<LI>

Many elements of the President's proposals do not threaten civil liberties.
If Congress were to decide, for example, that the FBI needs 1,000 additional
agents, the ACLU would not object.  If Congress were to make it easier to
trace dangerous chemicals by requiring manufacturers and importers to tag
their materials, the ACLU would not object.
<P><LI>
The ACLU pledges to remain ever-vigilant against giving the President or
domestic law enforcement authorities powers that could lead -- as they have
in the past -- to investigations solely based on speech or political
association. We urge Congress and the President to take the steps necessary
to make us safer, but to avoid, at all costs, those that will make us less
free.
</DL></blockquote>

<P>
<img src="../graphics/redline.gif" width="100%">
<P>



<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER>
