<html>
<head><title>Welfare Reform</title>
<!JM 1/4/95>
</head>
<body bgcolor=#FFFFFF>

<center>
<img src="/graphics/legishdr.gif">
<font color="#ff0033"><h1>Welfare Reform</h1></font>
<P>
</center>

<P>
<P><blockquote>
<a href="#issue"><h3>Issue Introduction</a></h3>
<a href="#threats"><h3>Specific Concerns</a></h3>
<a href="#points"><h3>Talking Points</a></h3>
<a href="welflet.html"><h3>ACLU Letter Opposing Welfare Reform Bills</h3></a>
<P>
<a name="issue">
<P></blockquote><img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width="100%"><blockquote><P>
<h3>Introduction</h3></a>
<P>The ACLU does not believe there is a constitutional entitlement to public
assistance; Congress has the right to eliminate welfare if it so chooses.
However, once such a massive federal program has been established, the
government has the obligation to ensure that the benefits are provided in a
manner that comports with civil and constitutional rights.  The legislation
that passed the House in March of 1995 does precisely the opposite: it strips
the poor of numerous rights.  By directing public anger toward the economic
burden "created" by the poor, immigrants, racial minorities, etc., Congress
has created an environment that "justifies" the denial of rights.  The ACLU's
concern is that under the guise of reducing economic dependency, welfare
reform legislation will set a precedent for eliminating civil liberties for
large classes of people in our nation merely because they receive some form
of public assistance.
<P>
Provisions of the House bill violate the right to privacy by dictating the
reproductive decisions of poor women and creating new databases of
information in the name of tracking down so-called "deadbeat dads."  They
violate the right to equal protection by targeting vulnerable groups (such as
indigent children and legal immigrants) for disparate treatment, the right to
travel by penalizing poor families who choose to move, and the rights of
children at risk for abuse and neglect by dismantling federal protections for
individuals in the country's child welfare systems. We also oppose the Senate
version of this bill, which contains most of these provisions.
<a name="threats">
<P></blockquote><img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width="100%"><blockquote><P>
<h3>Specific Concerns</h3>
<P>
It is imperative that the Senate remove from the House-backed welfare reform
bill the provisions that would do the most damage to civil liberties. These
specific provisions include:
<a name="child">
<P>
<b><i>1. Child Exclusion Provisions</b></i>
<P>

The House bill contains three child exclusion provisions that each raise
constitutional problems:
<DL><P><DD>
<b>Children born to families already receiving AFDC are excluded from
receiving subsistence aid</b>
<BR>
This provision targets children simply for being
born into poor families, violating the longstanding constitutional
prohibition on punishing children for their parents' behavior.  In addition,
this provision violates the right to privacy by coercing women in their
childbearing decisions.

<P><B>Children born to single teenage mothers are excluded from receiving aid
until their mothers turn 18</b><BR>  This provision violates the equal protection
guarantees of the Constitution by depriving children of assistance because of
the marital status of their parents.  Once again, this provision will cause
great hardship for countless children because of behavior over which they
have no control.

<P><B>The bill includes a "penalty" (a reduction in aid) for children whose
paternity has not been established by the state</b><BR>  This provision is
particularly unfair because it conditions the level of the child's benefits
on the ability of state bureaucrats to establish paternity.  Often paternity
is not immediately established because the father either contests paternity
or refuses to cooperate.  Yet this penalty falls on the child and -- by
stretching meager family resources -- the mother.
</DL><P>
The Senate resoundingly defeated amendments to impose mandatory family caps
and cutoffs of benefits to teen mothers.  These issues will need to be
resolved in conference.
<a name="illegitimacy">

<P><center><img src="../graphics/redline.gif"></center><P>
<b><i>2. "Illegitimacy Ratio"</b></i>
<P>
We strongly oppose the language in the House bill establishing an
"illegitimacy ratio" (the proportion of all births in a state that are
out-of-wedlock) that would be the basis of an increase in block grant funds
to the states.  This proposal would not even meet its purported goals and, in
addition, would dangerously threaten women's reproductive rights.
<P>
The ratio is irrelevant in the welfare debate because it includes the
out-of-wedlock births for mothers who are not on welfare.  While we strongly
oppose use of this ratio when it is based on the birthrate of any group of
women, it is even more irrelevant in "welfare reform" legislation to target
births by women not on welfare.
<P>
Moreover, "illegitimacy ratio"-based incentives could very well fail to
reduce out-of-wedlock births, because if married families have more children
while unmarried mothers do not, the percentage of all births that are
out-of-wedlock automatically decreases. On the other hand, if married couples
have fewer children, the ratio could go up. In that instance the state would
not receive its bonus, even though the number of out-of-wedlock births had
not increased.
<P>
We also oppose use of the ratio because it could very well result in
curtailing women's reproductive freedom.  The bill's language states that an
increase in abortions is considered part of the ratio.  States will therefore
face extraordinary financial pressure to reduce abortions, which will push
states to discourage women from exercising their constitutional right to
abortion.  States may choose to do so by failing to protect abortion clinics
that are the subject of violent attacks, imposing harsh licensing and zoning
restrictions on providers, and passing laws that restrict women's access to
this procedure.
<P>
The Senate version of the welfare bill contains a similar provision.  An
effort to strike it was defeated by the full Senate.
<a name="child">

<P><center><img src="../graphics/redline.gif"></center><P>
<b><i>3. Child Welfare Programs</b></i>
<P>
We are also deeply concerned about the provisions in the House bill that
would eliminate appropriate safeguards and accountability in child welfare
systems.  Current provisions in the federal Adoption Assistance Act set basic
standards for child welfare services without prescribing how a state should
meet those standards.  They permit child welfare advocates to seek protection
for children when a state fails to do so.  If child welfare systems are free
of such standards, and advocates are denied the right to enforce standards,
children are entirely without protection.
<P>
In addition, the bill as passed by the House calls for states to receive
their child welfare funds as a proportion of a block grant.  Over a five-year
period, federal funds for child protection will decline by $3.5 billion. This
will result in a marked decrease in federal funds for most, if not all
states, which will be forced to spend a high percentage of block grant funds
on foster care maintenance payments for the ever-increasing number of
children entering our child welfare systems. These states will then have far
fewer dollars to spend on preventing children from entering foster care and
on moving children out of foster care into permanent placements.  As a
result, thousands of our nation's children will remain in "foster care drift"
for years.
<P>
The House block grant approach also eviscerates the federal guarantee of
funding for abused and neglected children in need of foster care.  It could
result in the tragic scenario of a child welfare agency being unable to
provide a safe, foster care placement for a child who is abused because child
welfare funds from the block grant have dried up. Furthermore, under the
current federal statute, states are provided foster care funds to pay for
activities such as social worker training, recruitment of foster parents, and
the monitoring of foster and group homes.  These essential activities enable
states to ensure that children in government custody are in safe placements,
and help state agencies provide permanent placements for these children.  We
fear that if these critical components are curtailed because of fiscal
constraints, the due process rights of children in government custody will
more likely be violated, because they will linger in foster care and more
likely be placed in unmonitored, and thus potentially unsafe, situations.
<P>
The Senate declined to block-grant any child welfare programs, leaving the
entitlements intact.  This issue will be resolved in conference.
<a name="noncitizen">

<P><center><img src="../graphics/redline.gif"></center><P>
<b><i>4. Non-Citizen Exclusions</b></i>
<P>
One of the most troubling aspects of the welfare reform bill approved by the
House is the proposal to deny benefits to legal immigrants who have paid for
them.  Under the rubric of "welfare reform," the House bill would put SSI,
Medicaid, food stamps, and AFDC out of the reach of almost all legal
immigrants.  The proposal would deny benefits to people who have legally
lived in the United States for years, paying federal taxes to support the
programs; to children; and to parents whose children are American citizens.
<P>
As of September 18, similar legislation is on the floor of the Senate.  The
Senate bill would deny many naturalized citizens access to many "safety net"
programs, creating for the first time in this area a distinction between
naturalized and native-born citizens. It would accomplish this by "deeming"
income of an immigrant's sponsor to the immigrant for five years, even after
the immigrant becomes a citizen.
<P>
Legal immigrants come to the United States to escape persecution in their
homelands, and most are hardworking members of society.  (Undocumented aliens
are already ineligible for the targeted programs).  To cut off access to
benefits serves no one, will unacceptably shift costs to states with large
immigrant populations, threaten public health, and unjustifiably discriminate
against lawful residents and native-born citizens.  Excluding legal
immigrants from public benefits violates notions of equal protection, is
socially divisive, and is simply poor public policy.
<P><a name="establish">
<P><center><img src="../graphics/redline.gif"></center><P>
<b><i>5.  Establishment Clause concerns</b></i>
<P>
At the last minute, Sen. John Ashcroft (R-MO) added troubling provisions to
the welfare bill that raise great concerns regarding the First Amendment's
Establishment Clause.  The measure explicitly permits some of the federal
block grant funds to go to religious organizations.  The government may not
require the organization to remove religious art or icons while providing
services to welfare beneficiaries.  We believe this legislation will
encourage states to funnel federal taxpayer dollars to pervasively sectarian
religious institutions, in violation of the Establishment Clause.  We
succeeded in our efforts to pass Senator William Cohen's (R-ME) amendment,
which improves the language pertaining to financial audits of religious
groups.  We will need to work hard to make additional improvements in
conference.
<a name="points">
</blockquote>
<P></blockquote><img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width="100%"><blockquote><P>
<h3>Talking Points</h3> 
Welfare reform must respect the rights of welfare recipients, protect
children and strengthen families.  Unfortunately, the bill approved by the
House and some of the proposals under serious consideration by Senators fail
on all three counts. We must not allow Congress to overhaul our welfare
system at the expense of fundamental rights and civil liberties.
</DL></blockquote>

<P>
<img src="../graphics/redline.gif" width="100%">
<P>



<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER>
