<html>
<head><title>Immigration</title>
<!JM 1/5/96>
</head>
<body bgcolor=#FFFFFF>
<center>
<img src="/graphics/legishdr.gif">
<font color="#ff0033"><h1>Immigration</h1></font>
<P>
</center>

<P>
<P><blockquote>
<a href="#issue"><h3>Issue Introduction</a></h3>
<a href="#threats"><h3>Specific Concerns</a></h3>
<h3><a href="#points">Talking Points</a></h3>

<P>
<a name="issue">
<P></blockquote><img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width="100%"><blockquote><P>
<h3>Introduction</h3></a>
<P>
Major immigration bills with substantial civil liberties implications are
pending in both the House and Senate.  The bills would re-write the nation's
immigration laws, and are being considered in one of the most anti-immigrant
climates this century.
<P>
<a name="threats">
<P></blockquote><img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width="100%"><blockquote><P>
<h3>Specific Concerns:</h3>
<P><a name="smith">
In the House, Lamar Smith's H.R. 2202 would establish a national
identification system by the year 1999.  The system, established to verify
eligibility to work in the United States and discourage illegal immigration,
would collect data on every person in the country, including citizens, and
would lead inevitably to a national ID card.  It would lead to a card because
the person examining a prospective worker's employment eligibility by virtue
of his/her immigration status would have to be able to match the Social
Security Number offered by the prospective worker to the worker
himself/herself.  
<P>
For the first time, the government would have in place a computerized system,
based on Social Security numbers, through which detailed information about
everyone could be cross- referenced.  Uses for the national ID system beyond
work authorization are already being considered (including identification of
those eligible to receive needs-based benefits and tracking down dead-beat
dads).  How long would it be before such a system was made generally
available for law enforcement purposes, and then for keeping tabs on
political dissidents? 
<P>
Like the terrorism bill now pending in the House, the House immigration bill
would also allow the government to remove aliens on the basis of information
kept secret from them, make mere membership in an organization deemed
"terrorist" a basis for barring admission to the United States, allow for the
summary removal of refugees who come to the U.S. with inadequate or
fraudulent documents and seek political asylum (and bar meaningful judicial
review of summary removal orders), and attempt to strip aliens who enter the
United States without being formally admitted of certain due process rights.
Like the welfare reform bill pending in the Senate, the House bill would also
limit immigrants' access to needs-based public benefit programs by "deeming"
the income of the sponsor of the immigrant to the immigrant.  (However, in
the House bill, deeming would end at citizenship.)  The bill has over 100
co-sponsors, was approved by the House Immigration Subcommittee in July, and
mark-up on the bill will begin in the House Judiciary Committee on September
19.
<P><a name="simpson">
<P><center><img src="../graphics/redline.gif"></center><P>
This fall the Senate Judiciary Committee will take up Senator Simpson's S.269
on illegal immigration.  Like the House immigration bill, it would create a
national identification system leading to a national ID card, provide for
summary exclusion of asylum seekers, and limit immigrants' access to public
benefits.  Mark-up of the Senate illegal immigration bill could occur late
this month, or early next month.
<a name="points">
<P></blockquote><img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width="100%"><blockquote><P>
<h3>Talking Points</h3> 
<DL>
<DD>
<LI>
The problem of illegal immigration has been exaggerated.  According to the
INS, there are 4 million undocumented aliens in the United States -- less
than 2% of the population.  To chase this 2%, a national ID system would
threaten the privacy interests of 100% of the prospective workers.  Other,
less intrusive measures to deal with illegal immigration should be tried
first.  For example, better enforcement of the wage and hour laws would
reduce the opportunities for unscrupulous employers to hire undocumented
workers at unfair wages.  There is a "job magnet" for aliens in part because
employers are not obeying the laws already on the books.
<P><LI>
A national ID system will not work, and will be exceedingly expensive.
Unscrupulous employers who do not now verify an applicant's work
authorization will not do so under the new system. Moreover, the INS and
Social Security Administration data bases that would be used to verify work
authorization have error rates of 28% and 17%, respectively.  It would cost
billions of dollars to reduce the error rate.  And with 65 million people in
the United States entering the work force or changing jobs each year, even a
1% error rate would mean 650,000 people annually denied an opportunity to
work while errors in the system are fixed.
<P><LI>
Exercising a constitutionally-protected right, like joining a group, should
never be a basis for barring admission to the United States.  People should
be barred as "terrorists" because of their activities, not because of
membership in a group designated as "terrorist."
<P><LI>
Workers including aliens are required to pay income taxes to support
needs-based programs.  They should be able to benefit from those programs in
part because they paid for them.  Discriminating against non-citizens will
tear at the fabric of ours, or any, society based on tolerance.
<P><LI>
Aliens who claim political asylum should have an adequate opportunity to make
out their asylum case, even if their travel documents are inadequate.  In
fact, it is often the most traumatized legitimate refugees who are unable to
obtain travel documents from their persecutors, and cannot make out their
political asylum claim in the airport immediately upon arrival.  
</DL></blockquote>

<P>
<img src="../graphics/redline.gif" width="100%">
<P>



<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER>
</BODY></HTML>
