</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head><title>Reproductive Rights</title>
<!JM 1/4/95>
</head>

<body bgcolor=#FFFFFF>
<center>
<img src="/graphics/legishdr.gif">
<font color="#ff0033"><h1>Reproductive Rights</h1></font>
<P>
</center>

<P>
<P><blockquote>
<a href="#issue"><h3>Issue Introduction</a></h3>
<a href="#threats"><h3>Specific Concerns</a></h3>
<h3><a href="#points">Talking Points</a></h3>


<h3><a href="janet.html">A Message from Janet Gallagher,<br> Director of the Reproductive Freedom Project</a></h3>

<h3><a href="104thrr.html">The 104th Congress's Assault on Reproductive Rights</a></h3>


<P>
<a name="issue">
<P></blockquote><img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width="100%"><blockquote><P>
<h3>Introduction</h3></a>
<P>
Supporters of reproductive freedom face formidable challenges in the 104th
Congress, where there are 218 staunchly anti-choice Members of the House and
45 in the Senate. We anticipate an unprecedented attack this year on the
right to choose, and fear there will be a concerted attempt to roll back the
victories that pro-choice advocates achieved in the 103rd Congress.
<a name="threats">
<P></blockquote><img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width="100%"><blockquote><P>
<h3>Specific Concerns</h3>
<P>
The inequity caused by funding restrictions for abortion is almost as old as
the constitutional right to abortion itself.  Three years after Roe v. Wade
was decided, Congress passed the first Hyde Amendment to the fiscal 1977
Medicaid appropriation.  
<P>
The Amendment barred the use of federal Medicaid funds for abortion except
when the life of the woman would be endangered by carrying the pregnancy to
term.  Although the Hyde Amendment has been reenacted every year since 1976,
the exceptions to the funding ban have varied over the years.  After
hard-fought battles in Congress, the fiscal 1978 Hyde Amendment contained new
exceptions for rape and incest victims and women whose health would be
severely damaged by carrying a pregnancy to term. However, from the second
half of fiscal 1981 through fiscal 1993 the Hyde Amendment contained only a
single exception for life endangerment.  In fiscal 1994 and 1995, the Hyde
Amendment again contained exceptions for rape and incest victims.
<P><center><img src="../graphics/redline.gif"></center><P>


This exception is now vulnerable.  Earlier this year, the House removed the
rape and incest exception when it passed the Labor-HHS appropriations bill
(which contains Medicaid funding).  This was accomplished under the guise of
"states' rights," in an amendment that permits states to opt out of their
obligation to provide rape and incest funding.  The Senate will take up the
Labor-HHS bill within the next couple of weeks, and we fully expect an
amendment abolishing the rape and incest exception.
<P><center><img src="../graphics/redline.gif"></center><P>


Federal restrictions on public funding for abortion now affect many
populations in addition to Medicaid recipients.  By the early 1980s, Congress
had added restrictions similar to the Hyde Amendment to other federal
programs on which an estimated 50 million people rely for their health care
or insurance. Today Native American women, federal employees and their
dependents, Peace Corps volunteers, low-income residents of Washington, D.C.,
military personnel and their dependents, and federal prisoners have all been
denied abortion coverage in their health care.  Only in the last Congress was
there some easing of these restrictions.  In the last two fiscal years,
Congress has restored abortion funding for federal employees and federal
prisoners and permitted the District of Columbia to use local revenues to
fund abortions for poor women.
<P><center><img src="../graphics/redline.gif"></center><P>


We have properly anticipated vigorous attempts to eviscerate these
achievements as well.  Already this session Congress has severely limited the
ability of federal employees to receive abortion services as part of their
health care coverage.  The House has voted overwhelmingly to reinstate the
ban on funds for abortions for federal prisoners.  It has also twice voted to
refuse military women overseas the use of military hospitals for abortion
services, even when paid for with their own private funds.  And this week,
the D.C. appropriations subcommittee will, in all likelihood, revisit the
issue of whether the District of Columbia may use its own local tax dollars
to pay for abortions.
<P><center><img src="../graphics/redline.gif"></center><P>


Congress will also decide the fate of the Title X federal family planning
program.  Title X is in jeopardy because authorization legislation has not
been enacted for the program, and some Members of Congress have threatened to
withhold funding of unauthorized programs.  Title X is also susceptible to
anti-choice amendments, such as a requirement that minors receiving family
planning do so only with parental consent.  In a stunning victory, the House
voted to fully fund the Title X program, but we expect troubling amendments
when the Senate considers the issue this month as part of the Labor-HHS
Appropriations bill.   We must urge Members to award full funding to the
Title X program, which is the federal government's only program devoted
exclusively to family planning services.  
<P>
<a name="points">
<P></blockquote><img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width="100%"><blockquote><P>
<h3>Talking Points</h3> 

<DL>

<DD>
<LI>
To deny poor women the ability to have an abortion if they have been raped or
victims of incest is to victimize them yet again. Congress finally recognized
this stark fact last year.  We must not allow the new anti-choice majority to
reverse that humane decision.
<LI>
Title X, as the only federal family planning program that has been shown to
work,  should receive full funding.  Ending it would be extremely detrimental
to low-income women and families.</DL></blockquote>

<P>
<img src="../graphics/redline.gif" width="100%">
<P>



<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER>
</BODY></HTML>
