Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head><title>Cyberliberties</title>
<!JM 1/5/96>
</head>
<body bgcolor=#FFFFFF>
<center>
<img src="/graphics/legishdr.gif">
<font color="#ff0033"><h1>Cyberliberties</h1></font>
<P>
</center>

<P>
<P><blockquote>
<a href="#issue"><h3>Issue Introduction</a></h3>
<a href="#threats"><h3>Specific Concerns</a></h3>
<h3><a href="#points">Talking Points</a></h3>

<P>
<a name="issue">
<P></blockquote><img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width="100%"><blockquote><P>
<h3>Introduction</h3></a>
<P>
The term "information superhighway" is used generically to refer to the
system of communication by computer networks and telephone modems.  Included
in this term are electronic mail within a corporation or university as well
as the entire panoply of information sources that have come to be embraced,
albeit imprecisely, by the term "the Internet."
<P>
This makes the information superhighway the first genuinely "mass
communications" medium in history, because for the first time many speakers
can communicate at the same time to many others (as distinct from one speaker
addressing the masses in the older print and broadcasting media).  The
tremendous expansion of free speech made possible by the information
superhighway is under severe attack from those who seek to impose government
control over the content of messages carried on the superhighway.
<P>
<a name="threats">
<P></blockquote><img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width="100%"><blockquote><P>
<h3>Specific Concerns:</h3>
<a name="censor">
<b><i>1. Censorship and Anti-Privacy Legislation</b></i>
<P>
Both the Senate and the House have passed telecommunications deregulation
bills that contain censorship provisions that violate the First Amendment
rights and invade the privacy of those who communicate on the information
superhighway.
<P>
The Senate bill would make it a crime to engage in so-called harassing or
annoying communications, so-called indecent communications to anyone under 18
years old, or in obscene communications.  The Senate bill applies to
telephone calls, voice mail, private email, as well as to general
communications in chat rooms, newsgroups, bulletin board services, and other
information superhighway facilities.
<P>
The Senate bill provides certain defenses to liability for commercial online
service providers (i.e., not universities, libraries or nonprofit bulletin
boards) but so circumscribes the defenses as to make them largely
inapplicable.
<P>
The House bill would make it a crime even to receive by computer materials
that are obscene or indecent and would impose liability on service providers
who merely transmit the communication. 
<P>
Other bills have been filed in both houses that would also impose criminal
penalties for speech crimes on the info superhighway.
<P>
<a name="filter">
<P><center><img src="../graphics/redline.gif"></center><P>
<b><i>2. Letting the Private Sector Put Users in Control</b></i>
<P>
The House telecommunications deregulation bill also contains a provision, the
Cox/Widen amendment, that would bar FCC censorship of the info superhighway
and generally foster private sector initiatives to empower users (including
parents concerned about their children) to determine what material is
accessed from their computers.  This provision needs to be improved, but its
private-sector, user-control approach is far preferable to the big-government
controls of the would-be computer censorship cops.
<a name="wiretap">
<P><center><img src="../graphics/redline.gif"></center><P>
<b><i>3. Digital Wiretap Legislation</b></i>
<P>
Last year, Congress approved legislation requiring the telephone industry to
retrofit its telecommunication systems, which of course are also used for the
information superhighway, to make it easier for the FBI to wiretap.  This is
analogous to requiring home builders to insert electronic listening devices
into the walls of every new house to make it easier for the government, under
the guise of fighting crime, to eavesdrop on personal conversations.  
<P>
Some Senators and Representatives (and the Administration) have been using
the Oklahoma City bombing as the reason to fund the digital wiretap program.
Interestingly, however, while the number of wiretap intercepts rose to an
all-time high in 1994, the FBI does not use its existing wiretap authority to
investigate violent activity. Since 1988, there have been no requests for
wiretap surveillance in which the agents have cited arson, explosives or
weapons violations to justify the tap.
<a name="points">
<P></blockquote><img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width="100%"><blockquote><P>
<h3>Talking Points</h3> 

<DL>
<DD>
<LI>
The common thread among many congressional actions is a profound disregard
for free speech, privacy and the unique characteristics of the information
superhighway.  Parents and other users already have the power to control what
is accessed by their computers through software technology and services from
their providers that exist today.  
<P><LI>
New censorship laws are not needed and will not achieve their objective. Some
40 percent of the sources of information on the superhighway come from
outside the United States, and they are not likely to feel bound by any U.S.
censorship regime.  The laws will, however, stifle protected speech.
<P><LI>
Users of the information superhighway should get full federal protection for
their free speech and privacy rights.  These new media already give users
unparalleled control over what is accessed from their computers, and the
private sector is busily expanding the number and variety of techniques for
user control.  Rather than attempting to impose a big-government, censorship
police approach, the government should foster and support private sector
developments to create an information superhighway that provides maximun
protection for free speech and privacy.
<P><LI>
Over the last decade, electronic surveillance has played virtually no role in
rooting out domestic terrorism, because law enforcement agents choose other,
effective investigative techniques.  Fighting terrorism provides no excuse to
waste a half billion dollars ($50 million this year) imposing a
big-government requirement on private industry to change its state-of-the-art
technology to enable wiretaps that are never sought.
</DL></blockquote>

<P>
<img src="../graphics/redline.gif" width="100%">
<P>



<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER>
</BODY></HTML>
