</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head><title>Legal Sevices</title>
<!JM 1/5/96>
</head>

<center>
<img src="/graphics/legishdr.gif">
<P>
<font color="#ff0033"><h1>Legal Services Corporation</h1></font>
<P>
</center>

<P>
<P><blockquote>
<a href="#issue"><h3>Issue Introduction</a></h3>
<a href="#threats"><h3>Specific Concerns</a></h3>
<h3><a href="#points">Talking Points</a></h3>

<P>
<a name="issue">
<P></blockquote><img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width="100%"><blockquote><P><h3>Introduction</h3></a>

<P>
A two-tiered system of justice exists in the United States; those who cannot
	afford justice go without. Legal services for the poor help ensure equal
access to justice for all.  In 1974, President Nixon created the Legal
Services Corporation (LSC) -- an independent, non-profit corporation to
provide funding for legal aid for the poor. As the number of Americans living
below the poverty line swells, legal services for the poor becomes more
essential.
<P>
More people live in poverty in the United States today than at any time in
the past 30 years.  In 1993 alone, one million additional Americans slipped
below the poverty line. Low income people often must negotiate a maze of
rules relating to disability, social security, Medicaid, Medicare, child
support, housing and more.
<P>
If the LSC is abolished or underfunded, those already at a severe
socioeconomic disadvantage will be exploited by those with greater access to
legal representation.  Worse still, such persons utterly lacking in leverage
in their day-to-day dealings will lose faith and respect for the legal
system.  Having lost respect for a system that does not provide equal access
to justice, such persons may resort to desperate action to vindicate their
rights or needs.
<P>
Currently, the LSC provides funds to 323 programs operating over 1200
neighborhood law offices.  The LSC provides for special programs to serve
Native American communities and migrant farm workers.  Programs funded by the
LSC serve more than 1.7 million clients a year, benefitting approximately 5
million individuals, the majority of them children living in poverty. 
<P>
The LSC is a model of administrative efficiency.  In FY95, only 3% of the LSC
budget was spent on centralized grantmaking and administrative tasks, while
97% was spent on providing legal services to the poor.
<P>
Our recent trend of fiscal austerity, combined with an increase in partisan
machinations, has resulted in proposed legislation which would severely
curtail the functioning of the LSC.  Two types of proposals are currently in
Congress: one that abolishes the LSC entirely and provides block grants
directly to the states and another that slashes funding for the LSC by 33%.
Whether  eliminating or  eviscerating the LSC, these proposals threaten
access to justice and contain restrictions which implicate fundamental
constitutional rights.
<P>
<a name="threats">
<P></blockquote><img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width="100%"><blockquote><P>

<h3>Specific Concerns:</h3>

<a name="abolish">
<P>
<b><i>1.   Proposed legislation that abolishes the Legal Services Corporation and provides block grants to the states:</b></i>
<DL><DT><P>
The ACLU strongly opposes the proposals to abolish the Legal Services
Corporation.  Provision of block grants to the states would hinder equal
access to justice.  Specifically, the ACLU has the following concerns with
this proposal:
<P><DD>
<b>No effective federal oversight</b>
<br>Elimination of the federal program would
remove effective federal oversight over the expenditure of federal funds.
State control would render legal services funding captive to state politics,
and result in a lack of national uniformity in the availability of legal
services.  Therefore, low-income people in some states may not have access to
any federally supported legal services.
<P>
<b>Creation of inefficient bureaucracies</b>i
<br> State agencies without any prior
experience would be responsible for bidding out legal services to individual
lawyers.  A new level of bureaucracy would arise in each state -- incurring
much higher costs then the current highly efficient program.
<P>
<b>Elimination of aid to Native Americans and migrant farm workers</b><br>
Programs serving Native Americans and migrant farm workers would be
eliminated.
<P>
<b>Less pro bono representation</b><br>
 The comprehensive effort to increase the
involvement of private attorneys would be destroyed and the more than 130,000
lawyers providing pro bono services would have no effective means of
continuing such representation.
<P>
<b>Balkanization of services</b><br>
 The locally based, integrated and specialized
system of neighborhood law offices with experienced attorneys trained to meet
local legal needs would be replaced by a hodgepodge of individual lawyers
with no expertise in poverty law, who would not be coordinated with each
other and not integrated into a system of support and training.  Providers
would be balkanized, services fragmented and lawyers untrained.  Years of
institutional knowledge and expertise would be destroyed.
<p>
<b>No attorney-client privilege or work-product protection</b><br>
In order to
receive legal services, clients would be required to jettison attorney-client
privilege and work product protection. Legal service funds would be
prohibited from use in divorce or separation matters.  In fact, the funding
would be restricted to 10 causes of action selected without regard for the
legal needs of low-income people generally or local needs specifically.     
<P>
</DL>
<a name="cut">
<P><center><img src="../graphics/redline.gif"></center><P>
<b><i>2.   Proposed legislation to cut LSC funding by 33%</i></b>
<P>
Equal access to justice in America means providing legal services to the
poor.  The $400 million provided for the LSC in FY95 represents less than
half of what would be necessary to accomplish the goal of "minimum" access to
justice,  defined as two attorneys for every 10,000 poor people.  This is in
stark contrast to the availability of attorneys to the general population,
which stands at one attorney for every 321 people.  Cutting the LSC by 33%
would contravene basic American principles of justice. 
<P>
<a name="censor">

<P><center><img src="../graphics/redline.gif"></center><P>
<b><i>3.   Government Censorship of Funding Recipients</i></b>
<P>
We are deeply concerned with the Constitutional implications of the
Congressional proposals to eliminate or eviscerate the LSC.  The restrictions
placed on  the recipients of federal funds (under both types of proposals)
implicate the fundamental right of free speech protected under the First
Amendment.  The restrictions are unconstitutionally overbroad in that they
restrict political expression of recipients, regardless of their funding
source.  Thus, a recipient of federal funding cannot devote any of its time
to advocacy relating to abortion, lobbying, administrative rulemaking, and
redistricting activities. 

<P>
<a name="points">
<P></blockquote><img src="../graphics/rbline.gif" width="100%"><blockquote><P>
<h3>Talking Points</h3> 
<DL>
<DD>
<LI>
Equal access to justice is fundamental to democracy.  Because low-income
Americans are deprived of a point of access to justice in America, legal
services for the poor help to remedy this disparity. Legal Services
Corporation has proved to be indispensable in providing legal services to the
poor in an efficient and effective manner. In order to ensure equal access to
justice across the nation, Legal Services Corporation should not be
abolished.  A program of block grants for the states would result in an
uneven, inefficient and unaccountable expenditure of federal funds.
<P><LI>
Funding for Legal Services Corporation should be increased, not decreased.  A
million more Americans fell below the poverty line in 1993 alone.  With the
burgeoning poverty in this country, the role of organizations such as LSC
becomes increasingly important.
</DL></blockquote>

<P>
<img src="../graphics/redline.gif" width="100%">
<P>





<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER>
</BODY></HTML>
