<TITLE>Civil Liberties Newsletter Fall 1996</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/libraryhdr.gif">
<H3><IMG SRC="/graphics/newshead.gif" ALIGN="LEFT">       FALL 1996</H3>
<H1>Civil Liberties -- The American Civil Liberties Union National Newsletter</H1>
<H3>Contents</H3>
<P><A HREF="#letter"><FONT SIZE="+2">A Letter to ACLU Members</FONT></A><BR><I>by
Nadine Strossen</I><BR>How ACLU members can help protect civil liberties --
right at home</P>
<P><A HREF="#court"><FONT SIZE="+2">In the Court</FONT></A><BR>A look at
some of the ACLU's most significant litigation activity in 1996</P>
<P><A HREF="#policy"><FONT SIZE="+2">Shaping Policy Inside the Beltway</FONT></A><BR>Our
Washington, D.C. lobbying staff discuss how their work influences Congress</P>
<P><A HREF="#hill"><FONT SIZE="+2">On the Hill</FONT></A><BR>Some of the key
decisions affecting civil liberties voted upon by the House and Senate.</P>
<P><A HREF="#glasser"><FONT SIZE="+2">Privacy and Progress</FONT></A><BR><I>by
Ira Glasser</I><BR>How civil libertarians can work to keep Big Brother at bay</P>
<P><A HREF="#membership"><FONT SIZE="+2">Membership</FONT></A><FONT SIZE="+2">&amp;</FONT><A
HREF="#development"><FONT SIZE="+2">Development</FONT></A>
<FONT SIZE="+2">News</FONT></P>
<HR>
<H2><A NAME="letter"></A>A letter to ACLU Members</H2>
<P>During this election season, you -- and your commitment to the nonpartisan
defense of fundamental freedoms for all people in America -- are more important
than ever.</P>
<P>The ACLU does not take sides in partisan elections because antagonism toward
civil liberties exists in all major political parties. Too many politicians,
across the ideological spectrum, scapegoat civil liberties in an effort to
pander to the most vocal segment of the electorate.</P>
<P>But although the ACLU is strictly nonpartisan, we are not apolitical.</P>
<P>We dedicate substantial energy and resources to influencing the legislative
process to protect individual rights, both in Washington and in state capitals
across the country. And we are convinced that we must become potent in our
legislative efforts if basic rights are to prevail.</P>
<P>It is no secret that proponents of anti-liberty measures have developed
sophisticated and modern grassroots networks designed to push their agenda in
Congress with a force far out of proportion to their numbers. And, as you know,
they are having significant success with government officials in both major
parties, including both presidential contenders.</P>
<P>To cite just a few recent examples:</P>
<UL>
<LI>Both Bill Clinton and Bob Dole championed the Communications Decency Act,
which imposes a straitjacket on what should be our freest communications medium:
the Internet. After the ACLU's recent victory in ACLU v. Reno, our
constitutional challenge to the CDA, the Clinton Administration asked the
Supreme Court to overturn the lower court's unanimous, ringing endorsement of
free speech.
<P></P></LI>
<LI>Bill Clinton and Bob Dole both aggressively supported  the &quot;Antiterrorism
and Effective Death Penalty Act,&quot; which will not be effective in fighting
terrorism, but which guts the time-honored writ of habeas corpus and infringes
on the rights of immigrants, political activists, and other people not even
suspected of being terrorists.
<P></P></LI>
<LI>Both Bill Clinton and Bob Dole are supporting teen curfew laws, although no

credible study has ever demonstrated that curfews reduce crime.  Instead, they
put all young people, most of whom are not suspected of any wrongdoing, under
virtual house arrest.
<P></P></LI>
<LI>Both Bill Clinton and Bob Dole supported the so-called Defense of Marriage
Act, which defines marriage as &quot;a legal union between one man and one woman
as husband and wife,&quot; thus denigrating the rights of lesbians and gay men.</LI></UL>
<P>The anti-liberties <I>dishonor roll</I> could go on and on. The
scapegoating of civil liberties by our presidential candidates, as well as other
actual or &quot;wannabe&quot; officeholders, is based not on principle, but on
politics. Washington Post columnist Richard Cohen recently condemned the
phenomenon in an appropriately blistering piece whose title says it all: &quot;Civil
Liberties: Campaign Casualty.&quot; Maintaining that the legacy of Clinton's
four years in office is that &quot;the civil liberties of Americans were
diminished,&quot; Cohen concludes, &quot;When it comes to political courage,
Clinton has mastered only half the concept.&quot; And neither Bob Dole's past

record -- including his long standing opposition to a woman's right to choose,
affirmative action, and a rational criminal justice policy -- nor his campaign
promises bode any better for civil liberties.</P>
<P>How can the ACLU protect civil liberties in this hostile environment? Our
national office in Washington, D.C. has for many years won praise for the
effectiveness of its legislative advocacy: producing well-researched and timely
analyses, building strong relationships with members of Congress and their
staffs, and working creatively in coalition with organizations from the right,
left, and center on particular issues of mutual concern.</P>
<P>In the past, however, we have been less successful at convincing members of
Congress that the ACLU also has the political clout in their states and
districts to back up our expert analysis. No matter how persuasive the arguments
of the ACLU's Washington office, they will largely be ignored if members of
Congress don't think their constituents back home will hold them accountable for
their votes.</P>
<P>That is why the ACLU staff, taking advantage of the ease and
costeffectiveness of new information technology, is working hard to create a
more effective grassroots field program. We've established a communications unit
in our Washington office and expanded our presence in cyberspace with the launch
of the ACLU's Freedom Network on the World Wide Web, through which our members
and supporters can send instant e-mail letters and faxes to representatives in
Congress.</P>
<P>This publication and its Internet-based companion -- the ACLU
<A HREF="/vote-guide">Online Voter's Guide</A> -- is a major step in the
evolution of our grassroots field program. The Voter's Guide, located in the In
Congress section of the Freedom Network, includes the voting records of all
members of Congress on key civil liberties votes, and in-depth analyses of a
wide range of legislative issues. And if you're not online, you can get the
ACLU's compilation of Congressional voting records by calling 202-675-2325 and
leaving a message with your name and address. A copy will be mailed to you.</P>
<P>At times such as these, when politically motivated scapegoating of
constitutional freedoms is &quot;business as usual,&quot; the ACLU's vigilance
and hard work are more important than ever. Recognizing that so many elected
officials and candidates trim their political sails to fit the shifting winds of
voter sentiment, we civil libertarian voters have to raise our voices.</P>
<HR>
<H2><A NAME="hill"></A>On the hill</H2>
<P>The 104th Congress presented the ACLU's Washington Office with its most
formidable challenge ever, as Gingrich &amp; Co. introduced a relentless stream
of anti-civil liberties proposals, and in far too many cases, the Clinton
Administration and Democratic minority either capitulated, or came up with bad
proposals of their own. By dint of careful legal analysis, hard work, and
coalition building -- both with natural allies and strange bedfellows -- the
ACLU legislative staff was able to block passage of some of Congress' worst
excesses. Other bills passed and were signed into law only to be challenged by
the ACLU in court. And, as we go to print, (October 1996) some of the battles
are still being fought.</P>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">October 1995</FONT><BR><B>The U.S. Sentencing Commission</B>
agrees with the ACLU that the enormous disparity between the sentence for
possession or sale of crack cocaine as opposed to powder cocaine should be
eliminated.  The 100-1 sentencing disparity has led to disproportionately long
sentences for African American drug offenders who are most often arrested on
crack charges.</P>
<P>For the first time in the history of the Sentencing Commission, Congress and
President Clinton reject a Commission recommendation.</P>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">December 1995</FONT><BR><B>The Flag Amendment</B> passes
the House by an overwhelming 312 to 120, but fails in the Senate by only 3 votes
amidst determined lobbying by the ACLU. The Amendment would have prohibited &quot;flag
desecration,&quot; essentially nullifying the speech protections in the First
Amendment.</P>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">January 1996</FONT><BR>Both Houses approve the National
Defense Authorization Act, including an amendment requiring the <B>discharge of
all HIV-positive service members</B>.</P>
<P>The ACLU urges President Clinton to veto the bill, but he signs it into law,
promising he will put the full weight of his office behind an effort to repeal
the amendment. In April, Congress repeals a law it adopted three months earlier.</P>

<P><FONT SIZE="+1">February 1996</FONT><BR>Ignoring the ACLU's fierce
opposition and threat of litigation, Congress passes telecommunications
legislation that includes the <B>Communications Decency Act</B> -- by a vote of
91 to 5 in the Senate, and 414 to 16 in the House -- opening up the Internet to
blatant government censorship. Citing grave free speech and privacy concerns,
the ACLU announces it will file a lawsuit challenging the act's
constitutionality. President Clinton signs the Act into law on February 8th, and
the ACLU files suit that afternoon. ( See &quot;In the Court,&quot; ACLU v.
Reno)</P>
<P>Congress debates new <B>immigration proposals</B>, which the ACLU denounces
as &quot;unconstitutional, unwise, and un-American.&quot; Provisions range from
the establishment of a national computer registry of every single worker in the
U.S., to the deportation of people on the basis of secret evidence. As of this
writing, the legislation is still pending, although pieces of it have been
passed as part of welfare and so-called counterterrorism legislation. </P>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">March 1996</FONT><BR>The House debates and passes the
<B>Antiterrorism and Effective Death Penalty Act</B> by a vote of 229 to 191.
The ACLU lobbied furiously against the bill, which would curtail habeas corpus
and expand the government's wiretapping powers. The ACLU and its unlikely allies
(including the NRA) succeed in removing the wiretapping provisions, but in
April, President Clinton signs into law a deeply flawed bill that undermines
habeas protection, endorses a form of guilt by association, and authorizes the
use of secret evidence in deportation proceedings.</P>
<P>Congress debates <B>school voucher legislation</B> -- one of the top items
on the religious right's agenda. The legislation would provide federal funds to
religious (and other private) schools in the District of Columbia through cash
vouchers to students, in violation of the First Amendment's Establishment
Clause. The House votes for the plan, but the ACLU and its allies are able to
block it in the Senate and the bill fails.</P>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">April 1996</FONT><BR>President Clinton vetoes the
so-called <B>Partial Birth Abortion Ban Act</B>, passed overwhelmingly by both
Houses of Congress in the face of massive opposition from the ACLU and other
pro-choice organizations. The act marked the first time Congress voted to ban a
type of abortion since the Supreme Court's 1973 decision in Roe v. Wade.</P>
<P>Both Houses of Congress pass the <B>Prison Litigation Reform Act</B> as a
footnote to a massive appropriations bill, with so little Congressional
resistance that no separate vote on the act was ever taken. The ACLU opposes the
bill which strips the federal courts of much of their power to correct even the
most egregious prison conditions. The constitutionality of the act is being
litigated and will inevitably receive Supreme Court review.</P>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">May 1996</FONT><BR>The ACLU denounces both Congress and
President Clinton for supporting the euphemistically called <B>Defense of
Marriage Act</B>, (DOMA) drafted by radical conservative groups and introduced
into the House in an effort to prevent the states from recognizing same-sex
marriages. DOMA passes the House in July and is passed by an 84 to 15 vote by
the Senate.  At press time, President Clinton has said he would sign.</P>
<P>The <B>American Community Renewal Act</B> is introduced in the House. The
bill would mandate school voucher programs in up to 100 cities, gag the
political expression of nonprofit charities and require social service
beneficiaries to engage in sectarian prayer. Speaker Gingrich promises a floor
vote on the bill in July. However, after the ACLU organizes the opposition of
over 70 groups, the bill is placed on hiatus.</P>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">June 1996</FONT><BR>The so-called <B>Violent Youth
Predator Act</B> is introduced in the House. The act would mandate the
prosecution of children as young as 13 as adults, and allow juveniles to be
jailed with adult prisoners. The ACLU spearheads a broad effort to block the
act, and in September, Congress abandons efforts to pass it.</P>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">July 1996</FONT><BR>The ACLU assails a provision of the
House appropriations bill that authorizes stealth funding for <B>digital
telephony wiretapping</B>. The Administration-sponsored national digital
telephony plan would require the entire telephone industry to change all of its
digital equipment to make it more wiretap-ready. At press time, Congress has not
authorized the funding.</P>
<P>The House holds hearings on the <B>Religious Freedom Constitutional
Amendment</B>, allowing government funding of religious institutions and
permitting organized prayer in public schools. The ACLU condemns the amendment
as a direct attack on the Bill of Rights and the principle of separation of
church and state. As we go to press, no vote has yet taken place in either
chamber, but Speaker Gingrich has promised a vote in the House to placate the
Christian Coalition.</P>
<P>The ACLU intensifies its lobbying efforts against <B>new welfare
legislation</B> banning legal immigrants from receiving government benefits
including food stamps and Medicaid. The legislation also establishes a national
I.D. system and undermines the separation of church and state by forcing state
governments to contract with religious institutions to provide taxpayerfunded
social services -- even if the services are delivered in a proselytizing
environment. The bill was approved by a large majority in both houses and signed
by the President in August.</P>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">August 1996</FONT><BR>The House passes the so-called
<B>English Language Empowerment Act</B>, barring the federal government with
few exceptions from using any language but English, by a vote of 259 to 169. The
ACLU, in lobbying against the bill, points out it would repeal provisions of the
Voting Rights Act designed to help members of language-minority groups, and
would even prevent the Social Security Administration from communicating in
Spanish with non-English speakers in Puerto Rico. At press time the act has not
been brought up in the Senate.</P>
<P>The ACLU lobbies against the <B>&quot;administrative simplification&quot;
provision</B> buried deep in the Health Care Reform Bill. This deceptively
labeled provision authorizes the creation of a vast computerized medical records
database, includes a new national I.D. number for all patients, and makes
confidential information accessible not only to government, but to corporations
and credit reporting agencies without an individual's knowledge or consent.</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER" CELLPADDING="30" WIDTH="300">
<TR>
<TD ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE">
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">Did you know that only 20% of the American Adult Population
Voted in the 1992 election?<BR><BR>Make Your Voice Heard!</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<HR>
<H2><A NAME="court"></A>In the Court</H2>
<P>1996 will be remembered as a year in which the courts confirmed many
time-honored, fundamental constitutional rights and established new precedents
in areas never before tested. As ever, the ACLU tried cases and argued appeals
in federal and state courts with the single goal of protecting the civil
liberties of all Americans. Following is a sampling of our most significant
victories.</P>
<H3>Providing Equal Educational Opportunities for Women</H3>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">United States v. Virginia</FONT><BR>In its 157-year
history, the prestigious Virginia Military Institute has produced more than a &quot;few
good men.&quot; But this state-supported military college has also long violated
the Equal Protection Clause by excluding all women from admission. In June, the
U.S. Supreme Court ruled that the State of Virginia had failed to show the
constitutionally required &quot;exceedingly persuasive justification&quot; for
its male-only admissions policy. The ACLU participated as a friend of the court.
Writing for the majority, Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg, the founding director of
the ACLU's Women's Rights Project, opined, &quot;Inherent differences between
men and women, we have come to appreciate, remain cause for celebration, but not
for denigration of the members of either sex or for artificial constraints on an
individual's opportunity.&quot;</P>
<P>In this major victory for women's rights, the Court and the nation took a
historic step towards ending all sex discrimination in public education. The
Citadel, the South Carolina military college sued by Shannon Faulkner in 1993,
responded to the Supreme Court's decision immediately by initiating plans to
integrate women into the academy.</P>
<P>After deyfing the Court order all summer, the Board of VMI finally yielded
to the law in late September, agreeing to integrate women.</P>
<H3>Saying Yes to Equal Rights for Lesbians and Gay Men</H3>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">Romer v. Evans</FONT><BR>When Colorado's controversial
Amendment 2 was passed in 1992, it was met with cries of outrage from lesbians
and gay men across the nation, a high-profile boycott of the Aspen and Vail

resorts by Hollywood and sports glitterati -- and a challenge to eradicate it.
With co-counsel, the ACLU argued that by repealing all state and local laws
protecting gay men and lesbians from discrimination, and prohibiting the future
enactment of such laws, the Colorado Legislature had violated the Equal
Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment.</P>
<P>The U.S. Supreme Court agreed, and in a short but eloquent opinion authored
by Justice Anthony Kennedy, the Court struck down Amendment 2 in June 1996 and
held, for the first time, that government may not treat lesbian and gay men
differently from other people solely on the basis of animus: &quot;We must
conclude that Amendment 2 classifies homosexuals not to further a proper
legislative end but to make them unequal to everyone else. This Colorado cannot
do. A State cannot so deem a class of persons a stranger to its laws.&quot; This
landmark decision reaffirmed the principle that laws singling out a group of
Americans as second-class citizens violate the most basic Constitutional
guarantees.</P>
<H3>Ensuring Equal Educational Opportunity</H3>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">Sheff v. O'Neill</FONT><BR>The public schools in Hartford,
Connecticut are like those in many American cities -- racially and ethnically
segregated, lacking in educational resources, and serving a student population
that is disproportionately poor.</P>
<P>In July 1996, the state supreme court rendered a landmark decision: the
racial isolation of Hartford's public school children deprived them of &quot;an
adequate education,&quot; and violated their rights guaranteed by the state
constitution: &quot;The public elementary and high school students in Hartford
suffer daily from the devastating effects that racial and ethnic isolation, as
well as poverty, have had on their education.... We hold today that the needy
schoolchildren of Hartford have waited long enough.&quot;</P>
<P>This decision was the culmination of a seven-year legal battle, and sets the
stage for a significant process of educational reform in Connecticut.</P>
<H3>Upholding Freedom of Speech and Association</H3>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">O'Hare Truck Service Inc. v. City of Northlake</FONT><BR>When
the owner of a suburban Chicago trucking company openly supported the incumbent
mayor's political opponent, his company's longstanding contract with the town
was precipitously cancelled. The ACLU lost the first round of its constitutional
challenge to the town's action when the lower federal court ruled that companies
contracting with the government did not enjoy First Amendment protection against
reprisals based on political patronage.</P>
<P>The ACLU's position, however, was vindicated by the Supreme Court which
ruled that independent government contractors -- like government employees --
cannot be punished for expressing their views, without a showing of some &quot;compelling
interest&quot; justifying patronage practices.</P>
<P>&quot;We cannot accept the proposition,&quot; the Court ruled, &quot;that
those who perform the government's work outside the formal employment
relationship are subject to what we conclude is the direct and specific
abridgment of First Amendment rights.&quot;</P>
<H3>Protecting Free Speech in Cyberspace</H3>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">ACLU v. Reno</FONT><BR>The Internet, accurately described
by a federal judge as &quot;the most participatory form of mass speech yet
developed,&quot; was targeted for censorship when Congress passed the
Communications Decency Act (&quot;CDA&quot;) on February 8, 1996. The next day,

the ACLU filed a challenge in federal court, charging that the law, which
criminalized constitutionally protected speech online, ran afoul of the First
Amendment.</P>
<P>The ACLU was both lead counsel and lead plaintiff in the case. Other
plaintiffs included Planned Parenthood, Human Rights Watch, and Critical Path
AIDS Project -- all of whom provide information on the Internet which could,
under the CDA's vague and overbroad definitions, be prosecuted as &quot;indecent&quot;
or &quot;patently offensive.&quot;</P>
<P>On June 12th, the trial strategy of educating the judges on the Internet's
technology and real world use paid off. The three-judge panel unanimously struck
down the CDA: &quot;The bottom line is that the First Amendment should not be
interpreted to require us to entrust the protection it affords to the judgment
of prosecutors. Prosecutors come and go. The First Amendment remains to give
protection to future generations as well.&quot; The government has appealed, and
the most important First Amendment case of the information age is headed to the
Supreme Court.</P>
<H3>Preserving the Separation of Church and State</H3>
<P>This year, the ACLU brought victorious challenges to several attempts to
undermine the separation of church and state, from school prayer to state
funding for religious schools.</P>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">Ingebretsen v. Jackson Public School District</FONT><BR>A
federal court in Mississippi ruled that one public school system's practices of
broadcasting devotional exercises over the intercom system, conducting Bible
study classes for students, and recruiting teachers on the basis of their
fundamentalist beliefs were blatantly unconstitutional. Herdahl v. Pontotoc
School District</P>
<P>The Eleventh Circuit Court of Appeals invalidated a law passed by the
Mississippi legislature that allowed &quot;student-initiated&quot; prayer in
public school classrooms.</P>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">ACLU and Ed Ross v. Black Horse Pike Regional School
District</FONT><BR>&quot;Student-initiated&quot; prayers at public school
graduation ceremonies were ruled to be unconstitutional by the Third Circuit
Court of Appeals in a New Jersey case.</P>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">Ohio: Simmons-Harris v. Goff; Wisconsin: Jackson v. Benson</FONT><BR>In
addition, the ACLU is also involved in two landmark cases challenging education
voucher laws in both Wisconsin and Ohio on the grounds that public tax dollars
would be used for tuition to parochial schools in violation of the Establishment
Clause.</P>
<HR WIDTH="50%" ALIGN="CENTER" NOSHADE="NOSHADE">
<P>Unfortunately, 1996 will also be remembered as a year of substantial
setbacks in the areas of voting rights and the rights of criminal defendants and
prisoners. This year, civil rights remedies and due process rights took a
beating from the Supreme Court in several significant cases. </P>
<H3>Crippling the Voting Rights Act</H3>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">Bush v. Vera; Shaw v. Hunt</FONT><BR>The Supreme Court
continued the destructive process it began in its 1993 Shaw v. Reno decision:
dismantling the Voting Rights Act of 1965. Four more majority minority voting
districts were struck down as unconstitutional _ three in Texas and one in North
Carolina. These districts, redrawn in the early 1990's to ensure that minority
voters had the opportunity to vote candidates of their choice into office,
produced the largest percentage of minority representatives in Congress since
Reconstruction. Unfortunately, many are now likely to lose office as a result of
the Court's decisions. As the nation's population is becoming even more diverse,
Congress is heading in the opposite direction again, as a result of the Court's
decisions.</P>
<P>Justice John Paul Stevens, writing in dissent, pointed out the central irony
of the Court's redistricting rulings: &quot;I do not see how our constitutional
tradition can countenance the suggestion that a state may draw unsightly lines
to favor farmers or city dwellers, but not to create districts that benefit the
very group whose history inspired the Amendment that the Voting Rights Act was
designed to implement.&quot;</P>
<H3>Perpetuating Selective Prosecution</H3>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">U.S. v. Armstrong</FONT><BR>The Court refused to address
an insidious racial bias problem in the criminal justice system in a Los Angeles
case. Twenty-four black defendants, all charged under federal law with crack
offenses, cited strong statistical evidence suggesting racial bias: Between 1990
and 1992, over 200 white crack dealers were prosecuted by state authorities
while none were prosecuted by federal authorities, and federal penalties for
crack offenses are far more severe than state penalties. When the trial, court
ordered the government reveal its criteria for deciding whether to prosecute
under state or federal law, the government refused.</P>
<P>On appeal, the Supreme Court declined to order the government to reveal its
criteria, thus obstructing the defendants' ability to prove racial bias. The
decision has implications far beyond L.A.: According to a recent U.S. Sentencing
Commission study, only minorities were prosecuted under federal law for crack in
17 states and many cities.</P>
<H3>Eroding the Fourth Amendment -- Again!</H3>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">Whren v. U.S. </FONT><BR>The Court carved out yet another
exception to the Fourth Amendment's prohibition against warrantless searches,
holding that the police can stop a car for a traffic violation and search for
drugs even though the stop was entirely motivated by the police's desire to
search for drugs -- without probable cause -- and the traffic violation was
merely a pretext for doing so.</P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="membership"></A>Membership News</H3>

<P>The ACLU defrays the cost of our new member recruitment by renting our list
to other non-profit organizations and publications, but never to partisan
political groups or to groups whose programs are incompatible with ACLU
policies.</P>
<P>All lists are rented or exchanged according to strict privacy procedures
recommended by the U.S. Privacy Study Commission. We never give our list
directly to any organization. Instead, we send the list to a letter shop that
prepares the mailing for the organization that is participating in the rental or
exchange. That organization never sees our list and never knows what names are
on it unless an individual responds to the organization's mailing.</P>
<P>The ACLU always honors a member's request not to make his or her name
available. If you do not wish to receive materials from other organizations,
write to the ACLU Membership Department, and we will omit your name from list
rental and exchange.</P>
<P>Thank you for your understanding.</P>
<ADDRESS>-- The ACLU Membership Department</ADDRESS>
<HR>

<H3><A NAME="development"></A>Development News</H3>
<P>The DeSilver Society is a special group of supporters who have included the
ACLU Foundation in their wills or other estate plans. Named after founding
member Albert DeSilver (1888-1924), the first person to leave the ACLU a
financial legacy, The DeSilver Society currently recognizes over 1,000 charter
members, and their ranks are growing every day. By becoming a member of The
DeSilver Society, you can extend your commitment to the future defense of civil
liberties far beyond your own lifetime.</P>
<P>Through your will, trust or other type of planned gift, you can make gifts
to the ACLU Foundation that are substantially larger than you ever thought
possible. You may choose from a number of options to find a planned giving
arrangement best suited to your wishes and individual financial situation. You
may even establish a gift that provides you or your loved one with income for
life or a term of years. In any case, you will be taking an important step to
help secure an intact Bill of Rights for future generations.</P>
<P>To learn more about becoming a member of The DeSilver Society and the many
tax and financial benefits of making a legacy gift to the ACLU Foundation,
please complete and return this coupon, or call one of our knowledgeable staff
at (212) 944-9800, ext. 463.</P>
<P>Let us hear from you. We want you, like Albert DeSilver, to always be part
of the ACLU.</P>
