<H2><A NAME="policy"></A>Shaping Policy INSIDE the Beltway</H2>
<P>The ACLU takes its First Amendment right to petition the government very
seriously. Its small but dedicated staff of lobbyists is known both inside and
outside the Beltway for its passionate and well-informed advocacy on behalf of
civil liberties.</P>
<P>The magnitude of each lobbyist's work is daunting. Hundreds of legislative
proposals must be tracked. Novel issues must be researched and analyzed.
Testimony must be written. Meetings with Congressional staff must arranged and
attended. Coalitions must be organized and maintained. Op-ed articles must be
written, reporters must be brought up to speed, and TV and radio appearances
must be made. Most of all, ACLU lobbyists must be constantly on their toes when
Congress is in session for sudden and unexpected developments.</P>
<P>Today, more than ever before, ACLU members can provide critical grassroots
support. As ACLU President Nadine Strossen writes in her Letter to Members, the
ACLU Freedom Network, our Internet website, makes it possible for members to
send instant fax messages to their elected representatives on the civil
liberties issues of the day.</P>
<P>Please join us in our efforts to preserve and protect the Bill of Rights for
all Americans!</P>
<H3>Our Legislative Counselors</H3>
<P><B>Dan Katz</B> lobbies for free expression and religious liberty. &quot;It's
been a busy year,&quot; he says. &quot;We've been able to stop legislation that
would have imposed school vouchers in Washington, D.C. -- a major victory for
the separation of church and state. Unfortunately, we were not able to get
Congress to remove provisions in the welfare legislation that allows government
funding of houses of worship.&quot; Nevertheless, Dan believes the ACLU's
lobbying is a crucial tool for preserving our rights. &quot;In many cases, it's
the only time members of Congress stop to think about the civil liberties
implications of the legislation they're voting on.&quot;</P>
<P>In addition to fighting capital punishment for the ACLU, chief legislative
counsel <B>Diann Rust-Tierney</B> serves as associate director for the
Washington office, working closely with Laura Murphy in coordinating the ACLU's
entire legislative agenda. &quot;One of our key successes this year was the
defeat of a measure that would have done violence to the First Amendment by
prohibiting speech in the form of &quot;flag desecration.&quot; The ACLU, Diann
adds, occupies a unique space in the legislative arena. &quot;We stand on core
principles protecting individual rights -- principles that have stood us in good
stead for many years. At times, it puts us at odds with organizations that seek

to accomplish often laudable goals by taking civil liberties shortcuts.&quot;</P>
<P><B>Mark Kappelhoff</B> specializes in lobbying on issues relating to the
criminal justice system, including the hotly debated issues of juvenile justice,
national drug policy, and racial disparities in sentencing. While he is
particularly proud of how the ACLU blocked proposed juvenile justice
legislation, &quot;the most extreme and counterproductive that I have ever seen,&quot;
Mark is quick to point out that there are a lot of difficult battles ahead on
the Hill for civil libertarians. His issues, in particular, face sustained
attacks from politicians who seek short term political gain at the expense of
long term public safety.</P>
<P>Immigration, national security, English-only legislation, and federal law
enforcement abuse have kept <B>Greg Nojeim</B> spinning during the 104th
Congress. While legislators have repeatedly squashed civil liberties in many of
these areas, Greg says ACLU lobbying efforts will continue to forge ahead. &quot;If,
through lobbying, we can defeat or `fix' an unconstitutional provision of a
bill, rights are preserved without having to go to court,&quot; he says. &quot;We've
had measurable success getting so many members of Congress to talk the `civil
liberties talk,' he adds. &quot;We have to keep working on getting them to `walk
the walk' &quot;</P>
<P>Lobbying on privacy, free speech in cyberspace, civil liberties in the
workplace and Native American issues, <B>Don Haines</B> points out that the
ACLU plays a critical role not only in influencing Congress, but also by
educating other activist organizations because provisions harmful to civil
liberties are often &quot;buried&quot; within complicated legislative packages. &quot;Lobbying
is an ongoing process,&quot; he adds. &quot;The first step is educating and
persuading members of Congress about the issues. But equally important is having
each member know that civil liberties are also important concerns of people back
home.&quot;</P>
<P>Although <B>Laura Murphy</B>, Director of the ACLU's National Washington
office, supervises the work of the ACLU's legislative counsel, she is also a
lobbyist herself -- focusing on affirmative action, campaign finance, and
lobbying disclosure. Recognizing lobbying's unique ability to educate elected
officials and their constituents on the potential and impact of legislative
proposals, she acknowledges that the life of an ACLU lobbyist is full of
surprises. &quot;I've been cheered on talk radio by militias and the NRA, and
one hour later, hailed by coalition members from the Leadership Conference on
Civil Rights,&quot; she says. In this photo, Laura meets the media to denounce
federal law officers for ignoring constitutional rights and using unjustified
deadly force. Citing bloody shootouts at Waco and Ruby Ridge as evidence of
abuse of power, the ACLU joined forces with gun-rights groups and defense
lawyers on this issue -- proving once again that civil liberties issues often
transcend partisan ideology.</P>
<HR>
<H2><A NAME="glasser"></A>Privacy &amp; Progress: Hi-Tech Government
Surveillance Hurts Us All</H2>
<P><I>by Ira Glasser</I></P>
<P>Back in Prohibition days, when the telephone was still of relatively recent
invention, federal agents hired &quot;a lineman of long experience&quot; to
wiretap the phone of one Roy Olmstead, a bootlegger of some renown. Not
bothering to obtain a search warrant, the agents heard enough to get Olmstead
and 74 others tried and convicted of conspiracy to violate the Volstead Act.
</P>
<P>The case eventually went to the Supreme Court, where nine justices, all of
them born during or just after the Civil War, decided that wiretapping was not a
search and seizure and need not be limited by the Fourth Amendment.</P>
<P>The Olmstead case did not make good law, and would not be overturned for
another forty years, but it did provoke a passionate dissent from Justice Louis
Brandeis: &quot;Subtler and more far-reaching means of invading privacy have
become available to the government. The progress of science in furnishing the
government with means of espionage is not likely to stop with wiretapping.&quot;</P>
<P>Prescient words. Government surveillance has gone way beyond phone tapping,

beyond anything Justice Brandeis -- not to mention the Constitution's framers --

could possibly have imagined. New devices able to penetrate, track, record and
report our most private transactions and communications seem to pop up every
other day -- and, unfortunately, the current Administration and the
Gingrich-Dole Congressional leadership have been no friend of privacy rights.
This spring, the Administration advocated and Congress enacted counter-terrorism
legislation to expand FBI wiretapping authority. After the TWA tragedy in July,
the Administration renewed the call for reduced court scrutiny of roving
wiretaps, allowing the government to listen in on calls from phones primarily
used by people other than the suspect.</P>
<P>Just imagine if the government required every building contractor in the
country to equip the walls of all new homes and offices with listening devices
in case it wanted to snoop. That is exactly what the Administration-sponsored

national digital telephony plan would do:  require the entire telephone industry

to retrofit all if its digital equipment, making it more wiretap-ready. And our
telephones, unfortunately, are not the only targets. The Clinton Administration
wants every U.S.-made computer to have a Clipper chip, enabling the government
to intercept and unlock encrypted electronic messages between and among private
individuals, groups and businesses.</P>
<P>Welfare legislation signed into law this summer mandates a National New Hire
Directory -- a huge, interlocking government database that will eventually
contain the name, address, social security number, and other personal
information about every employee in America. Administration-backed health care
reform would require every one of us to carry an easy-access, digitized national
&quot;health security card,&quot; containing many bytes of intimate medical
information.</P>
<P>Of course, each of these Orwellian developments comes with justifications
and bland assurances that our privacy will be respected.</P>
<P>The government says more wiretapping power is needed to combat terrorism.
But the FBI is already authorized to obtain wiretap warrants in cases of
bombing, arson, firearms, assassination, hostage-taking, and threats to the
national security, yet it hardly uses that authority: in the past ten years,
fewer than 0.2 percent of all law enforcement wiretap requests were connected to
these crimes. Most wiretapping is for petty drug possession and gambling cases.
What the FBI really wants is a lower standard for obtaining a warrant _ which in
light of the Bureau's sorry history of tapping innocent people, is not a good
idea.  Besides, wiretaps are notoriously inefficient at obtaining incriminating
information about violent crime: 80% of the conversations intercepted in law
enforcement wiretaps are non-incriminating.</P>
<P>The government argues it needs the Clipper Chip to eavesdrop on the e-mail
of terrorists, gangsters and other riff raff. Therefore, terrorists and
gangsters will probably use imported equipment from Japan or Germany that
includes encoding devices. And tracking down deadbeat dads is a laudable goal,
but does the government need a National New Hire Registry containing information
on every single American employee in order to achieve it?</P>
<P>Hanging us all to catch the guilty few is not the constitutional way.</P>
<P>We shouldn't take the Administration seriously when it assures us this
information will be collected and used carefully and circumspectly. Wiretaps and
other forms of electronic surveillance overhear indiscriminately: they're like
vacuum cleaners, sweeping up everything in their paths. Tapping a phone of one
family member is going to capture the conversations of everyone in that family _
not to mention any other person speaking to them by telephone. And although a
vast database network to prevent fraud and other illegal activities sounds
benign enough, the list of government bureaucrats and functionaries who will be
tempted to use this information against political enemies -- in the grand
tradition of J. Edgar Hoover and Richard M. Nixon -- is very long.</P>
<P>Today, America stands at a constitutional crossroads: it will be
extraordinarily difficult to curtail, much less dismantle these surveillance
systems once they are in place, so it is imperative that we oppose unbridled
governmental use of new technology to track and spy on us now. That's why we are
embarking on the strengthened grassroots program Nadine discusses in her column.
We need you -- all ACLU members -- to give us the political muscle we require to
prevail.</P>
<P>Almost 70 years ago, branding wiretaps &quot;instruments of tyranny and
oppression,&quot;Justice Brandeis asked, &quot;Can it be that the Constitution
affords no protection against such invasions of individual security?&quot; The
ACLU says: No. This cannot be.</P>
<P>New technological development is inevitable, but it is up to us to keep
technology honest.</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER" CELLPADDING="20" WIDTH="400">
<TR>
<TD>
