<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Nadine Strossen</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>
<blockquote>
<img src="/graphics/abouthdr.gif">
<h2>Nadine Strossen - President of the ACLU</h2>
<img src="/graphics/nadg.jpg">
<br clear=all>
<p>
Nadine Strossen was elected President of the ACLU's National Board of
Directors in January 1991. She was first elected to the ACLU's National Board
in 1983 and to its Executive Committee in 1985. She became a General Counsel
in 1986.
<P>
A Professor of Law at New York Law School, Strossen teaches Constitutional
Law, Federal Courts and International Human Rights. She also has been an
adjunct professor at Columbia University. The National Law Journal recently
included Professor Strossen in its special section, "Profiles in Power: The
100 Most Influential Lawyers in America."
<P>
Prior to entering academia, Professor Strossen practiced law for 10 years at
several firms, including New York's Sullivan & Cromwell.
<P>
The first American woman to receive "The Outstanding Young People of the
World Award" given by Jaycees International to seven people selected from 75
countries, Professor Strossen is published widely in professional journals
and lectures throughout the United States and abroad.
<P>
She is the author of several books, including Defending Pornography: Free
Speech, Sex, and the Fight for Women's Rights, published in 1995 by Scribner.
<P>
Professor Strossen graduated Phi Beta Kappa from Harvard-Radcliffe College in
1972 and, in 1975, with high honors from Harvard Law School, where she was an
editor of the Harvard Law Review.
<P>
She lives in New York with her husband Eli Noam, a Professor at Columbia
University. She is a native of Minneapolis, Minnesota.
<P>
</blockquote>

